230 DEFAULT_LAST_PASS: Final = 1 # Pass numbers start at 0

232 # Maximum length of fixed tuple types inferred when narrowing from variadic tuples.
233 MAX_PRECISE_TUPLE_SIZE: Final = 8

235 DeferredNodeType: _TypeAlias = Union[FuncDef, LambdaExpr, OverloadedFuncDef, Decorator]
236 FineGrainedDeferredNodeType: _TypeAlias = Union[FuncDef, MypyFile, OverloadedFuncDef]

238  
239 # A node which is postponed to be processed during the next pass.
240 # In normal mode one can defer functions and methods (also decorated and/or overloaded)
241 # and lambda expressions. Nested functions can't be deferred -- only top-level functions
242 # and methods of classes not defined within a function can be deferred.
243 class DeferredNode(NamedTuple):
244 node: DeferredNodeType
245 # And its TypeInfo (for semantic analysis self type handling
246 active_typeinfo: TypeInfo | None
247  
248  
249 # Same as above, but for fine-grained mode targets. Only top-level functions/methods
250 # and module top levels are allowed as such.
251 class FineGrainedDeferredNode(NamedTuple):
252 node: FineGrainedDeferredNodeType
253 active_typeinfo: TypeInfo | None
254  
255  
256 # Data structure returned by find_isinstance_check representing
257 # information learned from the truth or falsehood of a condition. The
258 # dict maps nodes representing expressions like 'a[0].x' to their
259 # refined types under the assumption that the condition has a
260 # particular truth value. A value of None means that the condition can
261 # never have that truth value.
262  
263 # NB: The keys of this dict are nodes in the original source program,
264 # which are compared by reference equality--effectively, being *the
265 # same* expression of the program, not just two identical expressions
266 # (such as two references to the same variable). TODO: it would
267 # probably be better to have the dict keyed by the nodes' literal_hash
268 # field instead.
269 TypeMap: _TypeAlias = Optional[Dict[Expression, Type]]
270  
271  
272 # An object that represents either a precise type or a type with an upper bound;
273 # it is important for correct type inference with isinstance.
274 class TypeRange(NamedTuple):
275 item: Type
276 is_upper_bound: bool # False => precise type
277  
278  
279 # Keeps track of partial types in a single scope. In fine-grained incremental
280 # mode partial types initially defined at the top level cannot be completed in
281 # a function, and we use the 'is_function' attribute to enforce this.
282 class PartialTypeScope(NamedTuple):
283 map: dict[Var, Context]
284 is_function: bool
285 is_local: bool

288 class TypeChecker(NodeVisitor[None], CheckerPluginInterface):
289 """Mypy type checker.
290  
291 Type check mypy source files that have been semantically analyzed.
292  
293 You must create a separate instance for each source file.
294 """
295  
296 # Are we type checking a stub?
297 is_stub = False
298 # Error message reporter
299 errors: Errors
300 # Utility for generating messages
301 msg: MessageBuilder
302 # Types of type checked nodes. The first item is the "master" type
303 # map that will store the final, exported types. Additional items
304 # are temporary type maps used during type inference, and these
305 # will be eventually popped and either discarded or merged into
306 # the master type map.
307 #
308 # Avoid accessing this directly, but prefer the lookup_type(),
309 # has_type() etc. helpers instead.
310 _type_maps: list[dict[Expression, Type]]
311  
312 # Helper for managing conditional types
313 binder: ConditionalTypeBinder
314 # Helper for type checking expressions
315 expr_checker: mypy.checkexpr.ExpressionChecker
316  
317 pattern_checker: PatternChecker
318  
319 tscope: Scope
320 scope: CheckerScope
321 # Stack of function return types
322 return_types: list[Type]
323 # Flags; true for dynamically typed functions
324 dynamic_funcs: list[bool]
325 # Stack of collections of variables with partial types
326 partial_types: list[PartialTypeScope]
327 # Vars for which partial type errors are already reported
328 # (to avoid logically duplicate errors with different error context).
329 partial_reported: set[Var]
330 globals: SymbolTable
331 modules: dict[str, MypyFile]
332 # Nodes that couldn't be checked because some types weren't available. We'll run
333 # another pass and try these again.
334 deferred_nodes: list[DeferredNode]
335 # Type checking pass number (0 = first pass)
336 pass_num = 0
337 # Last pass number to take
338 last_pass = DEFAULT_LAST_PASS
339 # Have we deferred the current function? If yes, don't infer additional
340 # types during this pass within the function.
341 current_node_deferred = False
342 # Is this file a typeshed stub?
343 is_typeshed_stub = False
344 options: Options
345 # Used for collecting inferred attribute types so that they can be checked
346 # for consistency.
347 inferred_attribute_types: dict[Var, Type] | None = None
348 # Don't infer partial None types if we are processing assignment from Union
349 no_partial_types: bool = False
350  
351 # The set of all dependencies (suppressed or not) that this module accesses, either
352 # directly or indirectly.
353 module_refs: set[str]
354  
355 # A map from variable nodes to a snapshot of the frame ids of the
356 # frames that were active when the variable was declared. This can
357 # be used to determine nearest common ancestor frame of a variable's
358 # declaration and the current frame, which lets us determine if it
359 # was declared in a different branch of the same `if` statement
360 # (if that frame is a conditional_frame).
361 var_decl_frames: dict[Var, set[int]]
362  
363 # Plugin that provides special type checking rules for specific library
364 # functions such as open(), etc.
365 plugin: Plugin
366  
367 def __init__(
368 self,
369 errors: Errors,
370 modules: dict[str, MypyFile],
371 options: Options,
372 tree: MypyFile,
373 path: str,
374 plugin: Plugin,
375 per_line_checking_time_ns: dict[int, int],
376 ) -> None:
377 """Construct a type checker.
378  
379 Use errors to report type check errors.
380 """
381 self.errors = errors
382 self.modules = modules
383 self.options = options
384 self.tree = tree
385 self.path = path
386 self.msg = MessageBuilder(errors, modules)
387 self.plugin = plugin
388 self.tscope = Scope()
389 self.scope = CheckerScope(tree)
390 self.binder = ConditionalTypeBinder()
391 self.globals = tree.names
392 self.return_types = []
393 self.dynamic_funcs = []
394 self.partial_types = []
395 self.partial_reported = set()
396 self.var_decl_frames = {}
397 self.deferred_nodes = []
398 self._type_maps = [{}]
399 self.module_refs = set()
400 self.pass_num = 0
401 self.current_node_deferred = False
402 self.is_stub = tree.is_stub
403 self.is_typeshed_stub = tree.is_typeshed_file(options)
404 self.inferred_attribute_types = None
405  
406 # If True, process function definitions. If False, don't. This is used
407 # for processing module top levels in fine-grained incremental mode.
408 self.recurse_into_functions = True
409 # This internal flag is used to track whether we a currently type-checking
410 # a final declaration (assignment), so that some errors should be suppressed.
411 # Should not be set manually, use get_final_context/enter_final_context instead.
412 # NOTE: we use the context manager to avoid "threading" an additional `is_final_def`
413 # argument through various `checker` and `checkmember` functions.
414 self._is_final_def = False
415  
416 # This flag is set when we run type-check or attribute access check for the purpose
417 # of giving a note on possibly missing "await". It is used to avoid infinite recursion.
418 self.checking_missing_await = False
419  
420 # While this is True, allow passing an abstract class where Type[T] is expected.
421 # although this is technically unsafe, this is desirable in some context, for
422 # example when type-checking class decorators.
423 self.allow_abstract_call = False
424  
425 # Child checker objects for specific AST node types
426 self.expr_checker = mypy.checkexpr.ExpressionChecker(
427 self, self.msg, self.plugin, per_line_checking_time_ns
428 )
429 self.pattern_checker = PatternChecker(self, self.msg, self.plugin, options)
430  
431 @property
432 def type_context(self) -> list[Type | None]:
433 return self.expr_checker.type_context
434  
435 def reset(self) -> None:
436 """Cleanup stale state that might be left over from a typechecking run.
437  
438 This allows us to reuse TypeChecker objects in fine-grained
439 incremental mode.
440 """
441 # TODO: verify this is still actually worth it over creating new checkers
442 self.partial_reported.clear()
443 self.module_refs.clear()
444 self.binder = ConditionalTypeBinder()
445 self._type_maps[1:] = []
446 self._type_maps[0].clear()
447 self.temp_type_map = None
448 self.expr_checker.reset()
449  
450 assert self.inferred_attribute_types is None
451 assert self.partial_types == []
452 assert self.deferred_nodes == []
453 assert len(self.scope.stack) == 1
454 assert self.partial_types == []
455  
456 def check_first_pass(self) -> None:
457 """Type check the entire file, but defer functions with unresolved references.
458  
459 Unresolved references are forward references to variables
460 whose types haven't been inferred yet. They may occur later
461 in the same file or in a different file that's being processed
462 later (usually due to an import cycle).
463  
464 Deferred functions will be processed by check_second_pass().
465 """
466 self.recurse_into_functions = True
467 with state.strict_optional_set(self.options.strict_optional):
468 self.errors.set_file(
469 self.path, self.tree.fullname, scope=self.tscope, options=self.options
470 )
471 with self.tscope.module_scope(self.tree.fullname):
472 with self.enter_partial_types(), self.binder.top_frame_context():
473 for d in self.tree.defs:
474 if self.binder.is_unreachable():
475 if not self.should_report_unreachable_issues():
476 break
477 if not self.is_noop_for_reachability(d):
478 self.msg.unreachable_statement(d)
479 break
480 else:
481 self.accept(d)
482  
483 assert not self.current_node_deferred
484  
485 all_ = self.globals.get("__all__")
486 if all_ is not None and all_.type is not None:
487 all_node = all_.node
488 assert all_node is not None
489 seq_str = self.named_generic_type(
490 "typing.Sequence", [self.named_type("builtins.str")]
491 )
492 if not is_subtype(all_.type, seq_str):
493 str_seq_s, all_s = format_type_distinctly(
494 seq_str, all_.type, options=self.options
495 )
496 self.fail(
497 message_registry.ALL_MUST_BE_SEQ_STR.format(str_seq_s, all_s), all_node
498 )
499  
500 def check_second_pass(
501 self, todo: Sequence[DeferredNode | FineGrainedDeferredNode] | None = None
502 ) -> bool:
503 """Run second or following pass of type checking.
504  
505 This goes through deferred nodes, returning True if there were any.
506 """
507 self.recurse_into_functions = True
508 with state.strict_optional_set(self.options.strict_optional):
509 if not todo and not self.deferred_nodes:
510 return False
511 self.errors.set_file(
512 self.path, self.tree.fullname, scope=self.tscope, options=self.options
513 )
514 with self.tscope.module_scope(self.tree.fullname):
515 self.pass_num += 1
516 if not todo:
517 todo = self.deferred_nodes
518 else:
519 assert not self.deferred_nodes
520 self.deferred_nodes = []
521 done: set[DeferredNodeType | FineGrainedDeferredNodeType] = set()
522 for node, active_typeinfo in todo:
523 if node in done:
524 continue
525 # This is useful for debugging:
526 # print("XXX in pass %d, class %s, function %s" %
527 # (self.pass_num, type_name, node.fullname or node.name))
528 done.add(node)
529 with self.tscope.class_scope(
530 active_typeinfo
531 ) if active_typeinfo else nullcontext():
532 with self.scope.push_class(
533 active_typeinfo
534 ) if active_typeinfo else nullcontext():
535 self.check_partial(node)
536 return True
537  
538 def check_partial(self, node: DeferredNodeType | FineGrainedDeferredNodeType) -> None:
539 if isinstance(node, MypyFile):
540 self.check_top_level(node)
541 else:
542 self.recurse_into_functions = True
543 if isinstance(node, LambdaExpr):
544 self.expr_checker.accept(node)
545 else:
546 self.accept(node)
547  
548 def check_top_level(self, node: MypyFile) -> None:
549 """Check only the top-level of a module, skipping function definitions."""
550 self.recurse_into_functions = False
551 with self.enter_partial_types():
552 with self.binder.top_frame_context():
553 for d in node.defs:
554 d.accept(self)
555  
556 assert not self.current_node_deferred
557 # TODO: Handle __all__
558  
559 def defer_node(self, node: DeferredNodeType, enclosing_class: TypeInfo | None) -> None:
560 """Defer a node for processing during next type-checking pass.
561  
562 Args:
563 node: function/method being deferred
564 enclosing_class: for methods, the class where the method is defined
565 NOTE: this can't handle nested functions/methods.
566 """
567 # We don't freeze the entire scope since only top-level functions and methods
568 # can be deferred. Only module/class level scope information is needed.
569 # Module-level scope information is preserved in the TypeChecker instance.
570 self.deferred_nodes.append(DeferredNode(node, enclosing_class))
571  
572 def handle_cannot_determine_type(self, name: str, context: Context) -> None:
573 node = self.scope.top_non_lambda_function()
574 if self.pass_num < self.last_pass and isinstance(node, FuncDef):
575 # Don't report an error yet. Just defer. Note that we don't defer
576 # lambdas because they are coupled to the surrounding function
577 # through the binder and the inferred type of the lambda, so it
578 # would get messy.
579 enclosing_class = self.scope.enclosing_class()
580 self.defer_node(node, enclosing_class)
581 # Set a marker so that we won't infer additional types in this
582 # function. Any inferred types could be bogus, because there's at
583 # least one type that we don't know.
584 self.current_node_deferred = True
585 else:
586 self.msg.cannot_determine_type(name, context)
587  
588 def accept(self, stmt: Statement) -> None:
589 """Type check a node in the given type context."""
590 try:
591 stmt.accept(self)
592 except Exception as err:
593 report_internal_error(err, self.errors.file, stmt.line, self.errors, self.options)
594  
595 def accept_loop(
596 self,
597 body: Statement,
598 else_body: Statement | None = None,
599 *,
600 exit_condition: Expression | None = None,
601 ) -> None:
602 """Repeatedly type check a loop body until the frame doesn't change.
603 If exit_condition is set, assume it must be False on exit from the loop.
604  
605 Then check the else_body.
606 """
607 # The outer frame accumulates the results of all iterations
608 with self.binder.frame_context(can_skip=False, conditional_frame=True):
609 while True:
610 with self.binder.frame_context(can_skip=True, break_frame=2, continue_frame=1):
611 self.accept(body)
612 if not self.binder.last_pop_changed:
613 break
614 if exit_condition:
615 _, else_map = self.find_isinstance_check(exit_condition)
616 self.push_type_map(else_map)
617 if else_body:
618 self.accept(else_body)
619  
620 #
621 # Definitions
622 #
623  
624 def visit_overloaded_func_def(self, defn: OverloadedFuncDef) -> None:
625 if not self.recurse_into_functions:
626 return
627 with self.tscope.function_scope(defn):
628 self._visit_overloaded_func_def(defn)
629  
630 def _visit_overloaded_func_def(self, defn: OverloadedFuncDef) -> None:
631 num_abstract = 0
632 if not defn.items:
633 # In this case we have already complained about none of these being
634 # valid overloads.
635 return None
636 if len(defn.items) == 1:
637 self.fail(message_registry.MULTIPLE_OVERLOADS_REQUIRED, defn)
638  
639 if defn.is_property:
640 # HACK: Infer the type of the property.
641 assert isinstance(defn.items[0], Decorator)
642 self.visit_decorator(defn.items[0])
643 for fdef in defn.items:
644 assert isinstance(fdef, Decorator)
645 if defn.is_property:
646 self.check_func_item(fdef.func, name=fdef.func.name, allow_empty=True)
647 else:
648 # Perform full check for real overloads to infer type of all decorated
649 # overload variants.
650 self.visit_decorator_inner(fdef, allow_empty=True)
651 if fdef.func.abstract_status in (IS_ABSTRACT, IMPLICITLY_ABSTRACT):
652 num_abstract += 1
653 if num_abstract not in (0, len(defn.items)):
654 self.fail(message_registry.INCONSISTENT_ABSTRACT_OVERLOAD, defn)
655 if defn.impl:
656 defn.impl.accept(self)
657 if not defn.is_property:
658 self.check_overlapping_overloads(defn)
659 if defn.type is None:
660 item_types = []
661 for item in defn.items:
662 assert isinstance(item, Decorator)
663 item_type = self.extract_callable_type(item.var.type, item)
664 if item_type is not None:
665 item_types.append(item_type)
666 if item_types:
667 defn.type = Overloaded(item_types)
668 # Check override validity after we analyzed current definition.
669 if defn.info:
670 found_method_base_classes = self.check_method_override(defn)
671 if (
672 defn.is_explicit_override
673 and not found_method_base_classes
674 and found_method_base_classes is not None
675 ):
676 self.msg.no_overridable_method(defn.name, defn)
677 self.check_explicit_override_decorator(defn, found_method_base_classes, defn.impl)
678 self.check_inplace_operator_method(defn)
679 return None
680  
681 def extract_callable_type(self, inner_type: Type | None, ctx: Context) -> CallableType | None:
682 """Get type as seen by an overload item caller."""
683 inner_type = get_proper_type(inner_type)
684 outer_type: CallableType | None = None
685 if inner_type is not None and not isinstance(inner_type, AnyType):
686 if isinstance(inner_type, CallableType):
687 outer_type = inner_type
688 elif isinstance(inner_type, Instance):
689 inner_call = get_proper_type(
690 analyze_member_access(
691 name="__call__",
692 typ=inner_type,
693 context=ctx,
694 is_lvalue=False,
695 is_super=False,
696 is_operator=True,
697 msg=self.msg,
698 original_type=inner_type,
699 chk=self,
700 )
701 )
702 if isinstance(inner_call, CallableType):
703 outer_type = inner_call
704 if outer_type is None:
705 self.msg.not_callable(inner_type, ctx)
706 return outer_type
707  
708 def check_overlapping_overloads(self, defn: OverloadedFuncDef) -> None:
709 # At this point we should have set the impl already, and all remaining
710 # items are decorators
711  
712 if self.msg.errors.file in self.msg.errors.ignored_files:
713 # This is a little hacky, however, the quadratic check here is really expensive, this
714 # method has no side effects, so we should skip it if we aren't going to report
715 # anything. In some other places we swallow errors in stubs, but this error is very
716 # useful for stubs!
717 return
718  
719 # Compute some info about the implementation (if it exists) for use below
720 impl_type: CallableType | None = None
721 if defn.impl:
722 if isinstance(defn.impl, FuncDef):
723 inner_type: Type | None = defn.impl.type
724 elif isinstance(defn.impl, Decorator):
725 inner_type = defn.impl.var.type
726 else:
727 assert False, "Impl isn't the right type"
728  
729 # This can happen if we've got an overload with a different
730 # decorator or if the implementation is untyped -- we gave up on the types.
731 impl_type = self.extract_callable_type(inner_type, defn.impl)
732  
733 is_descriptor_get = defn.info and defn.name == "__get__"
734 for i, item in enumerate(defn.items):
735 assert isinstance(item, Decorator)
736 sig1 = self.extract_callable_type(item.var.type, item)
737 if sig1 is None:
738 continue
739  
  • E203 Whitespace before ':'
740 for j, item2 in enumerate(defn.items[i + 1 :]):
741 assert isinstance(item2, Decorator)
742 sig2 = self.extract_callable_type(item2.var.type, item2)
743 if sig2 is None:
744 continue
745  
746 if not are_argument_counts_overlapping(sig1, sig2):
747 continue
748  
749 if overload_can_never_match(sig1, sig2):
750 self.msg.overloaded_signature_will_never_match(i + 1, i + j + 2, item2.func)
751 elif not is_descriptor_get:
752 # Note: we force mypy to check overload signatures in strict-optional mode
753 # so we don't incorrectly report errors when a user tries typing an overload
754 # that happens to have a 'if the argument is None' fallback.
755 #
756 # For example, the following is fine in strict-optional mode but would throw
757 # the unsafe overlap error when strict-optional is disabled:
758 #
759 # @overload
760 # def foo(x: None) -> int: ...
761 # @overload
762 # def foo(x: str) -> str: ...
763 #
764 # See Python 2's map function for a concrete example of this kind of overload.
765 current_class = self.scope.active_class()
766 type_vars = current_class.defn.type_vars if current_class else []
767 with state.strict_optional_set(True):
768 if is_unsafe_overlapping_overload_signatures(sig1, sig2, type_vars):
769 self.msg.overloaded_signatures_overlap(i + 1, i + j + 2, item.func)
770  
771 if impl_type is not None:
772 assert defn.impl is not None
773  
774 # We perform a unification step that's very similar to what
775 # 'is_callable_compatible' would have done if we had set
776 # 'unify_generics' to True -- the only difference is that
777 # we check and see if the impl_type's return value is a
778 # *supertype* of the overload alternative, not a *subtype*.
779 #
780 # This is to match the direction the implementation's return
781 # needs to be compatible in.
782 if impl_type.variables:
783 impl: CallableType | None = unify_generic_callable(
784 # Normalize both before unifying
785 impl_type.with_unpacked_kwargs(),
786 sig1.with_unpacked_kwargs(),
787 ignore_return=False,
788 return_constraint_direction=SUPERTYPE_OF,
789 )
790 if impl is None:
791 self.msg.overloaded_signatures_typevar_specific(i + 1, defn.impl)
792 continue
793 else:
794 impl = impl_type
795  
796 # Prevent extra noise from inconsistent use of @classmethod by copying
797 # the first arg from the method being checked against.
798 if sig1.arg_types and defn.info:
799 impl = impl.copy_modified(arg_types=[sig1.arg_types[0]] + impl.arg_types[1:])
800  
801 # Is the overload alternative's arguments subtypes of the implementation's?
802 if not is_callable_compatible(
803 impl, sig1, is_compat=is_subtype, is_proper_subtype=False, ignore_return=True
804 ):
805 self.msg.overloaded_signatures_arg_specific(i + 1, defn.impl)
806  
807 # Is the overload alternative's return type a subtype of the implementation's?
808 if not (
809 is_subtype(sig1.ret_type, impl.ret_type)
810 or is_subtype(impl.ret_type, sig1.ret_type)
811 ):
812 self.msg.overloaded_signatures_ret_specific(i + 1, defn.impl)

814 # Here's the scoop about generators and coroutines.
815 #
816 # There are two kinds of generators: classic generators (functions
817 # with `yield` or `yield from` in the body) and coroutines
818 # (functions declared with `async def`). The latter are specified
819 # in PEP 492 and only available in Python >= 3.5.
820 #
821 # Classic generators can be parameterized with three types:
822 # - ty is the Yield type (the type of y in `yield y`)
823 # - tc is the type reCeived by yield (the type of c in `c = yield`).
824 # - tr is the Return type (the type of r in `return r`)
825 #
826 # A classic generator must define a return type that's either
827 # `Generator[ty, tc, tr]`, Iterator[ty], or Iterable[ty] (or
828 # object or Any). If tc/tr are not given, both are None.
829 #
830 # A coroutine must define a return type corresponding to tr; the
831 # other two are unconstrained. The "external" return type (seen
832 # by the caller) is Awaitable[tr].
833 #
834 # In addition, there's the synthetic type AwaitableGenerator: it
835 # inherits from both Awaitable and Generator and can be used both
836 # in `yield from` and in `await`. This type is set automatically
837 # for functions decorated with `@types.coroutine` or
838 # `@asyncio.coroutine`. Its single parameter corresponds to tr.
839 #
840 # PEP 525 adds a new type, the asynchronous generator, which was
841 # first released in Python 3.6. Async generators are `async def`
842 # functions that can also `yield` values. They can be parameterized
843 # with two types, ty and tc, because they cannot return a value.
844 #
845 # There are several useful methods, each taking a type t and a
846 # flag c indicating whether it's for a generator or coroutine:
847 #
848 # - is_generator_return_type(t, c) returns whether t is a Generator,
849 # Iterator, Iterable (if not c), or Awaitable (if c), or
850 # AwaitableGenerator (regardless of c).
851 # - is_async_generator_return_type(t) returns whether t is an
852 # AsyncGenerator.
853 # - get_generator_yield_type(t, c) returns ty.
854 # - get_generator_receive_type(t, c) returns tc.
855 # - get_generator_return_type(t, c) returns tr.
856  
857 def is_generator_return_type(self, typ: Type, is_coroutine: bool) -> bool:
858 """Is `typ` a valid type for a generator/coroutine?
859  
860 True if `typ` is a *supertype* of Generator or Awaitable.
861 Also true it it's *exactly* AwaitableGenerator (modulo type parameters).
862 """
863 typ = get_proper_type(typ)
864 if is_coroutine:
865 # This means we're in Python 3.5 or later.
866 at = self.named_generic_type("typing.Awaitable", [AnyType(TypeOfAny.special_form)])
867 if is_subtype(at, typ):
868 return True
869 else:
870 any_type = AnyType(TypeOfAny.special_form)
871 gt = self.named_generic_type("typing.Generator", [any_type, any_type, any_type])
872 if is_subtype(gt, typ):
873 return True
874 return isinstance(typ, Instance) and typ.type.fullname == "typing.AwaitableGenerator"
875  
876 def is_async_generator_return_type(self, typ: Type) -> bool:
877 """Is `typ` a valid type for an async generator?
878  
879 True if `typ` is a supertype of AsyncGenerator.
880 """
881 try:
882 any_type = AnyType(TypeOfAny.special_form)
883 agt = self.named_generic_type("typing.AsyncGenerator", [any_type, any_type])
884 except KeyError:
885 # we're running on a version of typing that doesn't have AsyncGenerator yet
886 return False
887 return is_subtype(agt, typ)
888  
889 def get_generator_yield_type(self, return_type: Type, is_coroutine: bool) -> Type:
890 """Given the declared return type of a generator (t), return the type it yields (ty)."""
891 return_type = get_proper_type(return_type)
892  
893 if isinstance(return_type, AnyType):
894 return AnyType(TypeOfAny.from_another_any, source_any=return_type)
895 elif isinstance(return_type, UnionType):
896 return make_simplified_union(
897 [self.get_generator_yield_type(item, is_coroutine) for item in return_type.items]
898 )
899 elif not self.is_generator_return_type(
900 return_type, is_coroutine
901 ) and not self.is_async_generator_return_type(return_type):
902 # If the function doesn't have a proper Generator (or
903 # Awaitable) return type, anything is permissible.
904 return AnyType(TypeOfAny.from_error)
905 elif not isinstance(return_type, Instance):
906 # Same as above, but written as a separate branch so the typechecker can understand.
907 return AnyType(TypeOfAny.from_error)
908 elif return_type.type.fullname == "typing.Awaitable":
909 # Awaitable: ty is Any.
910 return AnyType(TypeOfAny.special_form)
911 elif return_type.args:
912 # AwaitableGenerator, Generator, AsyncGenerator, Iterator, or Iterable; ty is args[0].
913 ret_type = return_type.args[0]
914 # TODO not best fix, better have dedicated yield token
915 return ret_type
916 else:
917 # If the function's declared supertype of Generator has no type
918 # parameters (i.e. is `object`), then the yielded values can't
919 # be accessed so any type is acceptable. IOW, ty is Any.
920 # (However, see https://github.com/python/mypy/issues/1933)
921 return AnyType(TypeOfAny.special_form)
922  
923 def get_generator_receive_type(self, return_type: Type, is_coroutine: bool) -> Type:
924 """Given a declared generator return type (t), return the type its yield receives (tc)."""
925 return_type = get_proper_type(return_type)
926  
927 if isinstance(return_type, AnyType):
928 return AnyType(TypeOfAny.from_another_any, source_any=return_type)
929 elif isinstance(return_type, UnionType):
930 return make_simplified_union(
931 [self.get_generator_receive_type(item, is_coroutine) for item in return_type.items]
932 )
933 elif not self.is_generator_return_type(
934 return_type, is_coroutine
935 ) and not self.is_async_generator_return_type(return_type):
936 # If the function doesn't have a proper Generator (or
937 # Awaitable) return type, anything is permissible.
938 return AnyType(TypeOfAny.from_error)
939 elif not isinstance(return_type, Instance):
940 # Same as above, but written as a separate branch so the typechecker can understand.
941 return AnyType(TypeOfAny.from_error)
942 elif return_type.type.fullname == "typing.Awaitable":
943 # Awaitable, AwaitableGenerator: tc is Any.
944 return AnyType(TypeOfAny.special_form)
945 elif (
946 return_type.type.fullname in ("typing.Generator", "typing.AwaitableGenerator")
947 and len(return_type.args) >= 3
948 ):
949 # Generator: tc is args[1].
950 return return_type.args[1]
951 elif return_type.type.fullname == "typing.AsyncGenerator" and len(return_type.args) >= 2:
952 return return_type.args[1]
953 else:
954 # `return_type` is a supertype of Generator, so callers won't be able to send it
955 # values. IOW, tc is None.
956 return NoneType()
957  
958 def get_coroutine_return_type(self, return_type: Type) -> Type:
959 return_type = get_proper_type(return_type)
960 if isinstance(return_type, AnyType):
961 return AnyType(TypeOfAny.from_another_any, source_any=return_type)
962 assert isinstance(return_type, Instance), "Should only be called on coroutine functions."
963 # Note: return type is the 3rd type parameter of Coroutine.
964 return return_type.args[2]
965  
966 def get_generator_return_type(self, return_type: Type, is_coroutine: bool) -> Type:
967 """Given the declared return type of a generator (t), return the type it returns (tr)."""
968 return_type = get_proper_type(return_type)
969  
970 if isinstance(return_type, AnyType):
971 return AnyType(TypeOfAny.from_another_any, source_any=return_type)
972 elif isinstance(return_type, UnionType):
973 return make_simplified_union(
974 [self.get_generator_return_type(item, is_coroutine) for item in return_type.items]
975 )
976 elif not self.is_generator_return_type(return_type, is_coroutine):
977 # If the function doesn't have a proper Generator (or
978 # Awaitable) return type, anything is permissible.
979 return AnyType(TypeOfAny.from_error)
980 elif not isinstance(return_type, Instance):
981 # Same as above, but written as a separate branch so the typechecker can understand.
982 return AnyType(TypeOfAny.from_error)
983 elif return_type.type.fullname == "typing.Awaitable" and len(return_type.args) == 1:
984 # Awaitable: tr is args[0].
985 return return_type.args[0]
986 elif (
987 return_type.type.fullname in ("typing.Generator", "typing.AwaitableGenerator")
988 and len(return_type.args) >= 3
989 ):
990 # AwaitableGenerator, Generator: tr is args[2].
991 return return_type.args[2]
992 else:
993 # Supertype of Generator (Iterator, Iterable, object): tr is any.
994 return AnyType(TypeOfAny.special_form)

996 def visit_func_def(self, defn: FuncDef) -> None:
997 if not self.recurse_into_functions:
998 return
999 with self.tscope.function_scope(defn):
1000 self._visit_func_def(defn)

1002 def _visit_func_def(self, defn: FuncDef) -> None:
1003 """Type check a function definition."""
1004 self.check_func_item(defn, name=defn.name)
1005 if defn.info:
1006 if not defn.is_dynamic() and not defn.is_overload and not defn.is_decorated:
1007 # If the definition is the implementation for an
1008 # overload, the legality of the override has already
1009 # been typechecked, and decorated methods will be
1010 # checked when the decorator is.
1011 found_method_base_classes = self.check_method_override(defn)
1012 self.check_explicit_override_decorator(defn, found_method_base_classes)
1013 self.check_inplace_operator_method(defn)
1014 if defn.original_def:
1015 # Override previous definition.
1016 new_type = self.function_type(defn)
1017 if isinstance(defn.original_def, FuncDef):
1018 # Function definition overrides function definition.
1019 old_type = self.function_type(defn.original_def)
1020 if not is_same_type(new_type, old_type):
1021 self.msg.incompatible_conditional_function_def(defn, old_type, new_type)
1022 else:
1023 # Function definition overrides a variable initialized via assignment or a
1024 # decorated function.
1025 orig_type = defn.original_def.type
1026 if orig_type is None:
1027 # If other branch is unreachable, we don't type check it and so we might
1028 # not have a type for the original definition
1029 return
1030 if isinstance(orig_type, PartialType):
1031 if orig_type.type is None:
1032 # Ah this is a partial type. Give it the type of the function.
1033 orig_def = defn.original_def
1034 if isinstance(orig_def, Decorator):
1035 var = orig_def.var
1036 else:
1037 var = orig_def
1038 partial_types = self.find_partial_types(var)
1039 if partial_types is not None:
1040 var.type = new_type
1041 del partial_types[var]
1042 else:
1043 # Trying to redefine something like partial empty list as function.
1044 self.fail(message_registry.INCOMPATIBLE_REDEFINITION, defn)
1045 else:
1046 name_expr = NameExpr(defn.name)
1047 name_expr.node = defn.original_def
1048 self.binder.assign_type(name_expr, new_type, orig_type)
1049 self.check_subtype(
1050 new_type,
1051 orig_type,
1052 defn,
1053 message_registry.INCOMPATIBLE_REDEFINITION,
1054 "redefinition with type",
1055 "original type",
1056 )
1057  
1058 def check_func_item(
1059 self,
1060 defn: FuncItem,
1061 type_override: CallableType | None = None,
1062 name: str | None = None,
1063 allow_empty: bool = False,
1064 ) -> None:
1065 """Type check a function.
1066  
1067 If type_override is provided, use it as the function type.
1068 """
1069 self.dynamic_funcs.append(defn.is_dynamic() and not type_override)
1070  
1071 with self.enter_partial_types(is_function=True):
1072 typ = self.function_type(defn)
1073 if type_override:
1074 typ = type_override.copy_modified(line=typ.line, column=typ.column)
1075 if isinstance(typ, CallableType):
1076 with self.enter_attribute_inference_context():
1077 self.check_func_def(defn, typ, name, allow_empty)
1078 else:
1079 raise RuntimeError("Not supported")
1080  
1081 self.dynamic_funcs.pop()
1082 self.current_node_deferred = False
1083  
1084 if name == "__exit__":
1085 self.check__exit__return_type(defn)
1086 # TODO: the following logic should move to the dataclasses plugin
1087 # https://github.com/python/mypy/issues/15515
1088 if name == "__post_init__":
1089 if dataclasses_plugin.is_processed_dataclass(defn.info):
1090 dataclasses_plugin.check_post_init(self, defn, defn.info)
1091  
1092 @contextmanager
1093 def enter_attribute_inference_context(self) -> Iterator[None]:
1094 old_types = self.inferred_attribute_types
1095 self.inferred_attribute_types = {}
1096 yield None
1097 self.inferred_attribute_types = old_types

1099 def check_func_def(
1100 self, defn: FuncItem, typ: CallableType, name: str | None, allow_empty: bool = False
1101 ) -> None:
1102 """Type check a function definition."""
1103 # Expand type variables with value restrictions to ordinary types.
1104 expanded = self.expand_typevars(defn, typ)
1105 original_typ = typ
1106 for item, typ in expanded:
1107 old_binder = self.binder
1108 self.binder = ConditionalTypeBinder()
1109 with self.binder.top_frame_context():
1110 defn.expanded.append(item)
1111  
1112 # We may be checking a function definition or an anonymous
1113 # function. In the first case, set up another reference with the
1114 # precise type.
1115 if isinstance(item, FuncDef):
1116 fdef = item
1117 # Check if __init__ has an invalid return type.
1118 if (
1119 fdef.info
1120 and fdef.name in ("__init__", "__init_subclass__")
1121 and not isinstance(
1122 get_proper_type(typ.ret_type), (NoneType, UninhabitedType)
1123 )
1124 and not self.dynamic_funcs[-1]
1125 ):
1126 self.fail(
1127 message_registry.MUST_HAVE_NONE_RETURN_TYPE.format(fdef.name), item
1128 )
1129  
1130 # Check validity of __new__ signature
1131 if fdef.info and fdef.name == "__new__":
1132 self.check___new___signature(fdef, typ)
1133  
1134 self.check_for_missing_annotations(fdef)
1135 if self.options.disallow_any_unimported:
1136 if fdef.type and isinstance(fdef.type, CallableType):
1137 ret_type = fdef.type.ret_type
1138 if has_any_from_unimported_type(ret_type):
1139 self.msg.unimported_type_becomes_any("Return type", ret_type, fdef)
1140 for idx, arg_type in enumerate(fdef.type.arg_types):
1141 if has_any_from_unimported_type(arg_type):
1142 prefix = f'Argument {idx + 1} to "{fdef.name}"'
1143 self.msg.unimported_type_becomes_any(prefix, arg_type, fdef)
1144 check_for_explicit_any(
1145 fdef.type, self.options, self.is_typeshed_stub, self.msg, context=fdef
1146 )
1147  
1148 if name: # Special method names
1149 if defn.info and self.is_reverse_op_method(name):
1150 self.check_reverse_op_method(item, typ, name, defn)
1151 elif name in ("__getattr__", "__getattribute__"):
1152 self.check_getattr_method(typ, defn, name)
1153 elif name == "__setattr__":
1154 self.check_setattr_method(typ, defn)
1155  
1156 # Refuse contravariant return type variable
1157 if isinstance(typ.ret_type, TypeVarType):
1158 if typ.ret_type.variance == CONTRAVARIANT:
1159 self.fail(
1160 message_registry.RETURN_TYPE_CANNOT_BE_CONTRAVARIANT, typ.ret_type
1161 )
1162 self.check_unbound_return_typevar(typ)
1163 elif (
1164 isinstance(original_typ.ret_type, TypeVarType) and original_typ.ret_type.values
1165 ):
1166 # Since type vars with values are expanded, the return type is changed
1167 # to a raw value. This is a hack to get it back.
1168 self.check_unbound_return_typevar(original_typ)
1169  
1170 # Check that Generator functions have the appropriate return type.
1171 if defn.is_generator:
1172 if defn.is_async_generator:
1173 if not self.is_async_generator_return_type(typ.ret_type):
1174 self.fail(
1175 message_registry.INVALID_RETURN_TYPE_FOR_ASYNC_GENERATOR, typ
1176 )
1177 else:
1178 if not self.is_generator_return_type(typ.ret_type, defn.is_coroutine):
1179 self.fail(message_registry.INVALID_RETURN_TYPE_FOR_GENERATOR, typ)
1180  
1181 # Fix the type if decorated with `@types.coroutine` or `@asyncio.coroutine`.
1182 if defn.is_awaitable_coroutine:
1183 # Update the return type to AwaitableGenerator.
1184 # (This doesn't exist in typing.py, only in typing.pyi.)
1185 t = typ.ret_type
1186 c = defn.is_coroutine
1187 ty = self.get_generator_yield_type(t, c)
1188 tc = self.get_generator_receive_type(t, c)
1189 if c:
1190 tr = self.get_coroutine_return_type(t)
1191 else:
1192 tr = self.get_generator_return_type(t, c)
1193 ret_type = self.named_generic_type(
1194 "typing.AwaitableGenerator", [ty, tc, tr, t]
1195 )
1196 typ = typ.copy_modified(ret_type=ret_type)
1197 defn.type = typ
1198  
1199 # Push return type.
1200 self.return_types.append(typ.ret_type)
1201  
1202 with self.scope.push_function(defn):
1203 # We temporary push the definition to get the self type as
1204 # visible from *inside* of this function/method.
1205 ref_type: Type | None = self.scope.active_self_type()
1206  
1207 # Store argument types.
1208 for i in range(len(typ.arg_types)):
1209 arg_type = typ.arg_types[i]
1210 if (
1211 isinstance(defn, FuncDef)
1212 and ref_type is not None
1213 and i == 0
1214 and (not defn.is_static or defn.name == "__new__")
1215 and typ.arg_kinds[0] not in [nodes.ARG_STAR, nodes.ARG_STAR2]
1216 ):
1217 if defn.is_class or defn.name == "__new__":
1218 ref_type = mypy.types.TypeType.make_normalized(ref_type)
1219 if not is_same_type(arg_type, ref_type):
1220 # This level of erasure matches the one in checkmember.check_self_arg(),
1221 # better keep these two checks consistent.
1222 erased = get_proper_type(erase_typevars(erase_to_bound(arg_type)))
1223 if not is_subtype(ref_type, erased, ignore_type_params=True):
1224 if (
1225 isinstance(erased, Instance)
1226 and erased.type.is_protocol
1227 or isinstance(erased, TypeType)
1228 and isinstance(erased.item, Instance)
1229 and erased.item.type.is_protocol
1230 ):
1231 # We allow the explicit self-type to be not a supertype of
1232 # the current class if it is a protocol. For such cases
1233 # the consistency check will be performed at call sites.
1234 msg = None
1235 elif typ.arg_names[i] in {"self", "cls"}:
1236 msg = message_registry.ERASED_SELF_TYPE_NOT_SUPERTYPE.format(
1237 erased.str_with_options(self.options),
1238 ref_type.str_with_options(self.options),
1239 )
1240 else:
1241 msg = message_registry.MISSING_OR_INVALID_SELF_TYPE
1242 if msg:
1243 self.fail(msg, defn)
1244 elif isinstance(arg_type, TypeVarType):
1245 # Refuse covariant parameter type variables
1246 # TODO: check recursively for inner type variables
1247 if (
1248 arg_type.variance == COVARIANT
1249 and defn.name not in ("__init__", "__new__", "__post_init__")
1250 and not is_private(defn.name) # private methods are not inherited
1251 ):
1252 ctx: Context = arg_type
1253 if ctx.line < 0:
1254 ctx = typ
1255 self.fail(message_registry.FUNCTION_PARAMETER_CANNOT_BE_COVARIANT, ctx)
1256 # Need to store arguments again for the expanded item.
1257 store_argument_type(item, i, typ, self.named_generic_type)
1258  
1259 # Type check initialization expressions.
1260 body_is_trivial = is_trivial_body(defn.body)
1261 self.check_default_args(item, body_is_trivial)
1262  
1263 # Type check body in a new scope.
1264 with self.binder.top_frame_context():
1265 # Copy some type narrowings from an outer function when it seems safe enough
1266 # (i.e. we can't find an assignment that might change the type of the
1267 # variable afterwards).
1268 new_frame: Frame | None = None
1269 for frame in old_binder.frames:
1270 for key, narrowed_type in frame.types.items():
1271 key_var = extract_var_from_literal_hash(key)
1272 if key_var is not None and not self.is_var_redefined_in_outer_context(
1273 key_var, defn.line
1274 ):
1275 # It seems safe to propagate the type narrowing to a nested scope.
1276 if new_frame is None:
1277 new_frame = self.binder.push_frame()
1278 new_frame.types[key] = narrowed_type
1279 self.binder.declarations[key] = old_binder.declarations[key]
1280 with self.scope.push_function(defn):
1281 # We suppress reachability warnings for empty generator functions
1282 # (return; yield) which have a "yield" that's unreachable by definition
1283 # since it's only there to promote the function into a generator function.
1284 #
1285 # We also suppress reachability warnings when we use TypeVars with value
1286 # restrictions: we only want to report a warning if a certain statement is
1287 # marked as being suppressed in *all* of the expansions, but we currently
1288 # have no good way of doing this.
1289 #
1290 # TODO: Find a way of working around this limitation
1291 if _is_empty_generator_function(item) or len(expanded) >= 2:
1292 self.binder.suppress_unreachable_warnings()
1293 self.accept(item.body)
1294 unreachable = self.binder.is_unreachable()
1295 if new_frame is not None:
1296 self.binder.pop_frame(True, 0)
1297  
1298 if not unreachable:
1299 if defn.is_generator or is_named_instance(
1300 self.return_types[-1], "typing.AwaitableGenerator"
1301 ):
1302 return_type = self.get_generator_return_type(
1303 self.return_types[-1], defn.is_coroutine
1304 )
1305 elif defn.is_coroutine:
1306 return_type = self.get_coroutine_return_type(self.return_types[-1])
1307 else:
1308 return_type = self.return_types[-1]
1309 return_type = get_proper_type(return_type)
1310  
1311 allow_empty = allow_empty or self.options.allow_empty_bodies
1312  
1313 show_error = (
1314 not body_is_trivial
1315 or
1316 # Allow empty bodies for abstract methods, overloads, in tests and stubs.
1317 (
1318 not allow_empty
1319 and not (
1320 isinstance(defn, FuncDef) and defn.abstract_status != NOT_ABSTRACT
1321 )
1322 and not self.is_stub
1323 )
1324 )
1325  
1326 # Ignore plugin generated methods, these usually don't need any bodies.
1327 if defn.info is not FUNC_NO_INFO and (
1328 defn.name not in defn.info.names or defn.info.names[defn.name].plugin_generated
1329 ):
1330 show_error = False
1331  
1332 # Ignore also definitions that appear in `if TYPE_CHECKING: ...` blocks.
1333 # These can't be called at runtime anyway (similar to plugin-generated).
1334 if isinstance(defn, FuncDef) and defn.is_mypy_only:
1335 show_error = False
1336  
1337 # We want to minimize the fallout from checking empty bodies
1338 # that was absent in many mypy versions.
1339 if body_is_trivial and is_subtype(NoneType(), return_type):
1340 show_error = False
1341  
1342 may_be_abstract = (
1343 body_is_trivial
1344 and defn.info is not FUNC_NO_INFO
1345 and defn.info.metaclass_type is not None
1346 and defn.info.metaclass_type.type.has_base("abc.ABCMeta")
1347 )
1348  
1349 if self.options.warn_no_return:
1350 if (
1351 not self.current_node_deferred
1352 and not isinstance(return_type, (NoneType, AnyType))
1353 and show_error
1354 ):
1355 # Control flow fell off the end of a function that was
1356 # declared to return a non-None type.
1357 if isinstance(return_type, UninhabitedType):
1358 # This is a NoReturn function
1359 msg = message_registry.INVALID_IMPLICIT_RETURN
1360 else:
1361 msg = message_registry.MISSING_RETURN_STATEMENT
1362 if body_is_trivial:
1363 msg = msg._replace(code=codes.EMPTY_BODY)
1364 self.fail(msg, defn)
1365 if may_be_abstract:
1366 self.note(message_registry.EMPTY_BODY_ABSTRACT, defn)
1367 elif show_error:
1368 msg = message_registry.INCOMPATIBLE_RETURN_VALUE_TYPE
1369 if body_is_trivial:
1370 msg = msg._replace(code=codes.EMPTY_BODY)
1371 # similar to code in check_return_stmt
1372 if (
1373 not self.check_subtype(
1374 subtype_label="implicitly returns",
1375 subtype=NoneType(),
1376 supertype_label="expected",
1377 supertype=return_type,
1378 context=defn,
1379 msg=msg,
1380 )
1381 and may_be_abstract
1382 ):
1383 self.note(message_registry.EMPTY_BODY_ABSTRACT, defn)
1384  
1385 self.return_types.pop()
1386  
1387 self.binder = old_binder
1388  
1389 def is_var_redefined_in_outer_context(self, v: Var, after_line: int) -> bool:
1390 """Can the variable be assigned to at module top level or outer function?
1391  
1392 Note that this doesn't do a full CFG analysis but uses a line number based
1393 heuristic that isn't correct in some (rare) cases.
1394 """
1395 outers = self.tscope.outer_functions()
1396 if not outers:
1397 # Top-level function -- outer context is top level, and we can't reason about
1398 # globals
1399 return True
1400 for outer in outers:
1401 if isinstance(outer, FuncDef):
1402 if find_last_var_assignment_line(outer.body, v) >= after_line:
1403 return True
1404 return False
1405  
1406 def check_unbound_return_typevar(self, typ: CallableType) -> None:
1407 """Fails when the return typevar is not defined in arguments."""
1408 if isinstance(typ.ret_type, TypeVarType) and typ.ret_type in typ.variables:
1409 arg_type_visitor = CollectArgTypeVarTypes()
1410 for argtype in typ.arg_types:
1411 argtype.accept(arg_type_visitor)
1412  
1413 if typ.ret_type not in arg_type_visitor.arg_types:
1414 self.fail(message_registry.UNBOUND_TYPEVAR, typ.ret_type, code=TYPE_VAR)
1415 upper_bound = get_proper_type(typ.ret_type.upper_bound)
1416 if not (
1417 isinstance(upper_bound, Instance)
1418 and upper_bound.type.fullname == "builtins.object"
1419 ):
1420 self.note(
1421 "Consider using the upper bound "
1422 f"{format_type(typ.ret_type.upper_bound, self.options)} instead",
1423 context=typ.ret_type,
1424 )
1425  
1426 def check_default_args(self, item: FuncItem, body_is_trivial: bool) -> None:
1427 for arg in item.arguments:
1428 if arg.initializer is None:
1429 continue
1430 if body_is_trivial and isinstance(arg.initializer, EllipsisExpr):
1431 continue
1432 name = arg.variable.name
1433 msg = "Incompatible default for "
1434 if name.startswith("__tuple_arg_"):
1435 msg += f"tuple argument {name[12:]}"
1436 else:
1437 msg += f'argument "{name}"'
1438 if (
1439 not self.options.implicit_optional
1440 and isinstance(arg.initializer, NameExpr)
1441 and arg.initializer.fullname == "builtins.None"
1442 ):
1443 notes = [
1444 "PEP 484 prohibits implicit Optional. "
1445 "Accordingly, mypy has changed its default to no_implicit_optional=True",
1446 "Use https://github.com/hauntsaninja/no_implicit_optional to automatically "
1447 "upgrade your codebase",
1448 ]
1449 else:
1450 notes = None
1451 self.check_simple_assignment(
1452 arg.variable.type,
1453 arg.initializer,
1454 context=arg.initializer,
1455 msg=ErrorMessage(msg, code=codes.ASSIGNMENT),
1456 lvalue_name="argument",
1457 rvalue_name="default",
1458 notes=notes,
1459 )
1460  
1461 def is_forward_op_method(self, method_name: str) -> bool:
1462 return method_name in operators.reverse_op_methods
1463  
1464 def is_reverse_op_method(self, method_name: str) -> bool:
1465 return method_name in operators.reverse_op_method_set
1466  
1467 def check_for_missing_annotations(self, fdef: FuncItem) -> None:
1468 # Check for functions with unspecified/not fully specified types.
1469 def is_unannotated_any(t: Type) -> bool:
1470 if not isinstance(t, ProperType):
1471 return False
1472 return isinstance(t, AnyType) and t.type_of_any == TypeOfAny.unannotated
1473  
1474 has_explicit_annotation = isinstance(fdef.type, CallableType) and any(
1475 not is_unannotated_any(t) for t in fdef.type.arg_types + [fdef.type.ret_type]
1476 )
1477  
1478 show_untyped = not self.is_typeshed_stub or self.options.warn_incomplete_stub
1479 check_incomplete_defs = self.options.disallow_incomplete_defs and has_explicit_annotation
1480 if show_untyped and (self.options.disallow_untyped_defs or check_incomplete_defs):
1481 if fdef.type is None and self.options.disallow_untyped_defs:
1482 if not fdef.arguments or (
1483 len(fdef.arguments) == 1
1484 and (fdef.arg_names[0] == "self" or fdef.arg_names[0] == "cls")
1485 ):
1486 self.fail(message_registry.RETURN_TYPE_EXPECTED, fdef)
1487 if not has_return_statement(fdef) and not fdef.is_generator:
1488 self.note(
1489 'Use "-> None" if function does not return a value',
1490 fdef,
1491 code=codes.NO_UNTYPED_DEF,
1492 )
1493 else:
1494 self.fail(message_registry.FUNCTION_TYPE_EXPECTED, fdef)
1495 elif isinstance(fdef.type, CallableType):
1496 ret_type = get_proper_type(fdef.type.ret_type)
1497 if is_unannotated_any(ret_type):
1498 self.fail(message_registry.RETURN_TYPE_EXPECTED, fdef)
1499 elif fdef.is_generator:
1500 if is_unannotated_any(
1501 self.get_generator_return_type(ret_type, fdef.is_coroutine)
1502 ):
1503 self.fail(message_registry.RETURN_TYPE_EXPECTED, fdef)
1504 elif fdef.is_coroutine and isinstance(ret_type, Instance):
1505 if is_unannotated_any(self.get_coroutine_return_type(ret_type)):
1506 self.fail(message_registry.RETURN_TYPE_EXPECTED, fdef)
1507 if any(is_unannotated_any(t) for t in fdef.type.arg_types):
1508 self.fail(message_registry.ARGUMENT_TYPE_EXPECTED, fdef)
1509  
1510 def check___new___signature(self, fdef: FuncDef, typ: CallableType) -> None:
1511 self_type = fill_typevars_with_any(fdef.info)
1512 bound_type = bind_self(typ, self_type, is_classmethod=True)
1513 # Check that __new__ (after binding cls) returns an instance
1514 # type (or any).
1515 if fdef.info.is_metaclass():
1516 # This is a metaclass, so it must return a new unrelated type.
1517 self.check_subtype(
1518 bound_type.ret_type,
1519 self.type_type(),
1520 fdef,
1521 message_registry.INVALID_NEW_TYPE,
1522 "returns",
1523 "but must return a subtype of",
1524 )
1525 elif not isinstance(
1526 get_proper_type(bound_type.ret_type), (AnyType, Instance, TupleType, UninhabitedType)
1527 ):
1528 self.fail(
1529 message_registry.NON_INSTANCE_NEW_TYPE.format(
1530 format_type(bound_type.ret_type, self.options)
1531 ),
1532 fdef,
1533 )
1534 else:
1535 # And that it returns a subtype of the class
1536 self.check_subtype(
1537 bound_type.ret_type,
1538 self_type,
1539 fdef,
1540 message_registry.INVALID_NEW_TYPE,
1541 "returns",
1542 "but must return a subtype of",
1543 )

1545 def check_reverse_op_method(
1546 self, defn: FuncItem, reverse_type: CallableType, reverse_name: str, context: Context
1547 ) -> None:
1548 """Check a reverse operator method such as __radd__."""
1549 # Decides whether it's worth calling check_overlapping_op_methods().
1550  
1551 # This used to check for some very obscure scenario. It now
1552 # just decides whether it's worth calling
1553 # check_overlapping_op_methods().
1554  
1555 assert defn.info
1556  
1557 # First check for a valid signature
1558 method_type = CallableType(
1559 [AnyType(TypeOfAny.special_form), AnyType(TypeOfAny.special_form)],
1560 [nodes.ARG_POS, nodes.ARG_POS],
1561 [None, None],
1562 AnyType(TypeOfAny.special_form),
1563 self.named_type("builtins.function"),
1564 )
1565 if not is_subtype(reverse_type, method_type):
1566 self.msg.invalid_signature(reverse_type, context)
1567 return
1568  
1569 if reverse_name in ("__eq__", "__ne__"):
1570 # These are defined for all objects => can't cause trouble.
1571 return
1572  
1573 # With 'Any' or 'object' return type we are happy, since any possible
1574 # return value is valid.
1575 ret_type = get_proper_type(reverse_type.ret_type)
1576 if isinstance(ret_type, AnyType):
1577 return
1578 if isinstance(ret_type, Instance):
1579 if ret_type.type.fullname == "builtins.object":
1580 return
1581 if reverse_type.arg_kinds[0] == ARG_STAR:
1582 reverse_type = reverse_type.copy_modified(
1583 arg_types=[reverse_type.arg_types[0]] * 2,
1584 arg_kinds=[ARG_POS] * 2,
1585 arg_names=[reverse_type.arg_names[0], "_"],
1586 )
1587 assert len(reverse_type.arg_types) >= 2
1588  
1589 forward_name = operators.normal_from_reverse_op[reverse_name]
1590 forward_inst = get_proper_type(reverse_type.arg_types[1])
1591 if isinstance(forward_inst, TypeVarType):
1592 forward_inst = get_proper_type(forward_inst.upper_bound)
1593 elif isinstance(forward_inst, TupleType):
1594 forward_inst = tuple_fallback(forward_inst)
1595 elif isinstance(forward_inst, (FunctionLike, TypedDictType, LiteralType)):
1596 forward_inst = forward_inst.fallback
1597 if isinstance(forward_inst, TypeType):
1598 item = forward_inst.item
1599 if isinstance(item, Instance):
1600 opt_meta = item.type.metaclass_type
1601 if opt_meta is not None:
1602 forward_inst = opt_meta
1603  
1604 def has_readable_member(typ: UnionType | Instance, name: str) -> bool:
1605 # TODO: Deal with attributes of TupleType etc.
1606 if isinstance(typ, Instance):
1607 return typ.type.has_readable_member(name)
1608 return all(
1609 (isinstance(x, UnionType) and has_readable_member(x, name))
1610 or (isinstance(x, Instance) and x.type.has_readable_member(name))
1611 for x in get_proper_types(typ.relevant_items())
1612 )
1613  
1614 if not (
1615 isinstance(forward_inst, (Instance, UnionType))
1616 and has_readable_member(forward_inst, forward_name)
1617 ):
1618 return
1619 forward_base = reverse_type.arg_types[1]
1620 forward_type = self.expr_checker.analyze_external_member_access(
1621 forward_name, forward_base, context=defn
1622 )
1623 self.check_overlapping_op_methods(
1624 reverse_type,
1625 reverse_name,
1626 defn.info,
1627 forward_type,
1628 forward_name,
1629 forward_base,
1630 context=defn,
1631 )
1632  
1633 def check_overlapping_op_methods(
1634 self,
1635 reverse_type: CallableType,
1636 reverse_name: str,
1637 reverse_class: TypeInfo,
1638 forward_type: Type,
1639 forward_name: str,
1640 forward_base: Type,
1641 context: Context,
1642 ) -> None:
1643 """Check for overlapping method and reverse method signatures.
1644  
1645 This function assumes that:
1646  
1647 - The reverse method has valid argument count and kinds.
1648 - If the reverse operator method accepts some argument of type
1649 X, the forward operator method also belong to class X.
1650  
1651 For example, if we have the reverse operator `A.__radd__(B)`, then the
1652 corresponding forward operator must have the type `B.__add__(...)`.
1653 """
1654  
1655 # Note: Suppose we have two operator methods "A.__rOP__(B) -> R1" and
1656 # "B.__OP__(C) -> R2". We check if these two methods are unsafely overlapping
1657 # by using the following algorithm:
1658 #
1659 # 1. Rewrite "B.__OP__(C) -> R1" to "temp1(B, C) -> R1"
1660 #
1661 # 2. Rewrite "A.__rOP__(B) -> R2" to "temp2(B, A) -> R2"
1662 #
1663 # 3. Treat temp1 and temp2 as if they were both variants in the same
1664 # overloaded function. (This mirrors how the Python runtime calls
1665 # operator methods: we first try __OP__, then __rOP__.)
1666 #
1667 # If the first signature is unsafely overlapping with the second,
1668 # report an error.
1669 #
1670 # 4. However, if temp1 shadows temp2 (e.g. the __rOP__ method can never
1671 # be called), do NOT report an error.
1672 #
1673 # This behavior deviates from how we handle overloads -- many of the
1674 # modules in typeshed seem to define __OP__ methods that shadow the
1675 # corresponding __rOP__ method.
1676 #
1677 # Note: we do not attempt to handle unsafe overlaps related to multiple
1678 # inheritance. (This is consistent with how we handle overloads: we also
1679 # do not try checking unsafe overlaps due to multiple inheritance there.)
1680  
1681 for forward_item in flatten_nested_unions([forward_type]):
1682 forward_item = get_proper_type(forward_item)
1683 if isinstance(forward_item, CallableType):
1684 if self.is_unsafe_overlapping_op(forward_item, forward_base, reverse_type):
1685 self.msg.operator_method_signatures_overlap(
1686 reverse_class, reverse_name, forward_base, forward_name, context
1687 )
1688 elif isinstance(forward_item, Overloaded):
1689 for item in forward_item.items:
1690 if self.is_unsafe_overlapping_op(item, forward_base, reverse_type):
1691 self.msg.operator_method_signatures_overlap(
1692 reverse_class, reverse_name, forward_base, forward_name, context
1693 )
1694 elif not isinstance(forward_item, AnyType):
1695 self.msg.forward_operator_not_callable(forward_name, context)
1696  
1697 def is_unsafe_overlapping_op(
1698 self, forward_item: CallableType, forward_base: Type, reverse_type: CallableType
1699 ) -> bool:
1700 # TODO: check argument kinds?
1701 if len(forward_item.arg_types) < 1:
1702 # Not a valid operator method -- can't succeed anyway.
1703 return False
1704  
1705 # Erase the type if necessary to make sure we don't have a single
1706 # TypeVar in forward_tweaked. (Having a function signature containing
1707 # just a single TypeVar can lead to unpredictable behavior.)
1708 forward_base_erased = forward_base
1709 if isinstance(forward_base, TypeVarType):
1710 forward_base_erased = erase_to_bound(forward_base)
1711  
1712 # Construct normalized function signatures corresponding to the
1713 # operator methods. The first argument is the left operand and the
1714 # second operand is the right argument -- we switch the order of
1715 # the arguments of the reverse method.
1716  
1717 forward_tweaked = forward_item.copy_modified(
1718 arg_types=[forward_base_erased, forward_item.arg_types[0]],
1719 arg_kinds=[nodes.ARG_POS] * 2,
1720 arg_names=[None] * 2,
1721 )
1722 reverse_tweaked = reverse_type.copy_modified(
1723 arg_types=[reverse_type.arg_types[1], reverse_type.arg_types[0]],
1724 arg_kinds=[nodes.ARG_POS] * 2,
1725 arg_names=[None] * 2,
1726 )
1727  
1728 reverse_base_erased = reverse_type.arg_types[0]
1729 if isinstance(reverse_base_erased, TypeVarType):
1730 reverse_base_erased = erase_to_bound(reverse_base_erased)
1731  
1732 if is_same_type(reverse_base_erased, forward_base_erased):
1733 return False
1734 elif is_subtype(reverse_base_erased, forward_base_erased):
1735 first = reverse_tweaked
1736 second = forward_tweaked
1737 else:
1738 first = forward_tweaked
1739 second = reverse_tweaked
1740  
1741 current_class = self.scope.active_class()
1742 type_vars = current_class.defn.type_vars if current_class else []
1743 return is_unsafe_overlapping_overload_signatures(first, second, type_vars)
1744  
1745 def check_inplace_operator_method(self, defn: FuncBase) -> None:
1746 """Check an inplace operator method such as __iadd__.
1747  
1748 They cannot arbitrarily overlap with __add__.
1749 """
1750 method = defn.name
1751 if method not in operators.inplace_operator_methods:
1752 return
1753 typ = bind_self(self.function_type(defn))
1754 cls = defn.info
1755 other_method = "__" + method[3:]
1756 if cls.has_readable_member(other_method):
1757 instance = fill_typevars(cls)
1758 typ2 = get_proper_type(
1759 self.expr_checker.analyze_external_member_access(other_method, instance, defn)
1760 )
1761 fail = False
1762 if isinstance(typ2, FunctionLike):
1763 if not is_more_general_arg_prefix(typ, typ2):
1764 fail = True
1765 else:
1766 # TODO overloads
1767 fail = True
1768 if fail:
1769 self.msg.signatures_incompatible(method, other_method, defn)
1770  
1771 def check_getattr_method(self, typ: Type, context: Context, name: str) -> None:
1772 if len(self.scope.stack) == 1:
1773 # module scope
1774 if name == "__getattribute__":
1775 self.fail(message_registry.MODULE_LEVEL_GETATTRIBUTE, context)
1776 return
1777 # __getattr__ is fine at the module level as of Python 3.7 (PEP 562). We could
1778 # show an error for Python < 3.7, but that would be annoying in code that supports
1779 # both 3.7 and older versions.
1780 method_type = CallableType(
1781 [self.named_type("builtins.str")],
1782 [nodes.ARG_POS],
1783 [None],
1784 AnyType(TypeOfAny.special_form),
1785 self.named_type("builtins.function"),
1786 )
1787 elif self.scope.active_class():
1788 method_type = CallableType(
1789 [AnyType(TypeOfAny.special_form), self.named_type("builtins.str")],
1790 [nodes.ARG_POS, nodes.ARG_POS],
1791 [None, None],
1792 AnyType(TypeOfAny.special_form),
1793 self.named_type("builtins.function"),
1794 )
1795 else:
1796 return
1797 if not is_subtype(typ, method_type):
1798 self.msg.invalid_signature_for_special_method(typ, context, name)
1799  
1800 def check_setattr_method(self, typ: Type, context: Context) -> None:
1801 if not self.scope.active_class():
1802 return
1803 method_type = CallableType(
1804 [
1805 AnyType(TypeOfAny.special_form),
1806 self.named_type("builtins.str"),
1807 AnyType(TypeOfAny.special_form),
1808 ],
1809 [nodes.ARG_POS, nodes.ARG_POS, nodes.ARG_POS],
1810 [None, None, None],
1811 NoneType(),
1812 self.named_type("builtins.function"),
1813 )
1814 if not is_subtype(typ, method_type):
1815 self.msg.invalid_signature_for_special_method(typ, context, "__setattr__")
1816  
1817 def check_slots_definition(self, typ: Type, context: Context) -> None:
1818 """Check the type of __slots__."""
1819 str_type = self.named_type("builtins.str")
1820 expected_type = UnionType(
1821 [str_type, self.named_generic_type("typing.Iterable", [str_type])]
1822 )
1823 self.check_subtype(
1824 typ,
1825 expected_type,
1826 context,
1827 message_registry.INVALID_TYPE_FOR_SLOTS,
1828 "actual type",
1829 "expected type",
1830 code=codes.ASSIGNMENT,
1831 )
