1833 def check_match_args(self, var: Var, typ: Type, context: Context) -> None:
1834 """Check that __match_args__ contains literal strings"""
1835 if not self.scope.active_class():
1836 return
1837 typ = get_proper_type(typ)
1838 if not isinstance(typ, TupleType) or not all(
1839 [is_string_literal(item) for item in typ.items]
1840 ):
1841 self.msg.note(
1842 "__match_args__ must be a tuple containing string literals for checking "
1843 "of match statements to work",
1844 context,
1845 code=codes.LITERAL_REQ,
1846 )
1847  
1848 def expand_typevars(
1849 self, defn: FuncItem, typ: CallableType
1850 ) -> list[tuple[FuncItem, CallableType]]:
1851 # TODO use generator
1852 subst: list[list[tuple[TypeVarId, Type]]] = []
1853 tvars = list(typ.variables) or []
1854 if defn.info:
1855 # Class type variables
1856 tvars += defn.info.defn.type_vars or []
1857 for tvar in tvars:
1858 if isinstance(tvar, TypeVarType) and tvar.values:
1859 subst.append([(tvar.id, value) for value in tvar.values])
1860 # Make a copy of the function to check for each combination of
1861 # value restricted type variables. (Except when running mypyc,
1862 # where we need one canonical version of the function.)
1863 if subst and not (self.options.mypyc or self.options.inspections):
1864 result: list[tuple[FuncItem, CallableType]] = []
1865 for substitutions in itertools.product(*subst):
1866 mapping = dict(substitutions)
1867 result.append((expand_func(defn, mapping), expand_type(typ, mapping)))
1868 return result
1869 else:
1870 return [(defn, typ)]
1871  
1872 def check_explicit_override_decorator(
1873 self,
1874 defn: FuncDef | OverloadedFuncDef,
1875 found_method_base_classes: list[TypeInfo] | None,
1876 context: Context | None = None,
1877 ) -> None:
1878 if (
1879 found_method_base_classes
1880 and not defn.is_explicit_override
1881 and defn.name not in ("__init__", "__new__")
1882 and not is_private(defn.name)
1883 ):
1884 self.msg.explicit_override_decorator_missing(
1885 defn.name, found_method_base_classes[0].fullname, context or defn
1886 )
1887  
1888 def check_method_override(
1889 self, defn: FuncDef | OverloadedFuncDef | Decorator
1890 ) -> list[TypeInfo] | None:
1891 """Check if function definition is compatible with base classes.
1892  
1893 This may defer the method if a signature is not available in at least one base class.
1894 Return ``None`` if that happens.
1895  
1896 Return a list of base classes which contain an attribute with the method name.
1897 """
1898 # Check against definitions in base classes.
1899 found_method_base_classes: list[TypeInfo] = []
1900 for base in defn.info.mro[1:]:
1901 result = self.check_method_or_accessor_override_for_base(defn, base)
1902 if result is None:
1903 # Node was deferred, we will have another attempt later.
1904 return None
1905 if result:
1906 found_method_base_classes.append(base)
1907 return found_method_base_classes
1908  
1909 def check_method_or_accessor_override_for_base(
1910 self, defn: FuncDef | OverloadedFuncDef | Decorator, base: TypeInfo
1911 ) -> bool | None:
1912 """Check if method definition is compatible with a base class.
1913  
1914 Return ``None`` if the node was deferred because one of the corresponding
1915 superclass nodes is not ready.
1916  
1917 Return ``True`` if an attribute with the method name was found in the base class.
1918 """
1919 found_base_method = False
1920 if base:
1921 name = defn.name
1922 base_attr = base.names.get(name)
1923 if base_attr:
1924 # First, check if we override a final (always an error, even with Any types).
1925 if is_final_node(base_attr.node) and not is_private(name):
1926 self.msg.cant_override_final(name, base.name, defn)
1927 # Second, final can't override anything writeable independently of types.
1928 if defn.is_final:
1929 self.check_if_final_var_override_writable(name, base_attr.node, defn)
1930 found_base_method = True
1931  
1932 # Check the type of override.
1933 if name not in ("__init__", "__new__", "__init_subclass__", "__post_init__"):
1934 # Check method override
1935 # (__init__, __new__, __init_subclass__ are special).
1936 if self.check_method_override_for_base_with_name(defn, name, base):
1937 return None
1938 if name in operators.inplace_operator_methods:
1939 # Figure out the name of the corresponding operator method.
1940 method = "__" + name[3:]
1941 # An inplace operator method such as __iadd__ might not be
1942 # always introduced safely if a base class defined __add__.
1943 # TODO can't come up with an example where this is
1944 # necessary; now it's "just in case"
1945 if self.check_method_override_for_base_with_name(defn, method, base):
1946 return None
1947 return found_base_method
1948  
1949 def check_method_override_for_base_with_name(
1950 self, defn: FuncDef | OverloadedFuncDef | Decorator, name: str, base: TypeInfo
1951 ) -> bool:
1952 """Check if overriding an attribute `name` of `base` with `defn` is valid.
1953  
1954 Return True if the supertype node was not analysed yet, and `defn` was deferred.
1955 """
1956 base_attr = base.names.get(name)
1957 if base_attr:
1958 # The name of the method is defined in the base class.
1959  
1960 # Point errors at the 'def' line (important for backward compatibility
1961 # of type ignores).
1962 if not isinstance(defn, Decorator):
1963 context = defn
1964 else:
1965 context = defn.func
1966  
1967 # Construct the type of the overriding method.
1968 # TODO: this logic is much less complete than similar one in checkmember.py
1969 if isinstance(defn, (FuncDef, OverloadedFuncDef)):
1970 typ: Type = self.function_type(defn)
1971 override_class_or_static = defn.is_class or defn.is_static
1972 override_class = defn.is_class
1973 else:
1974 assert defn.var.is_ready
1975 assert defn.var.type is not None
1976 typ = defn.var.type
1977 override_class_or_static = defn.func.is_class or defn.func.is_static
1978 override_class = defn.func.is_class
1979 typ = get_proper_type(typ)
1980 if isinstance(typ, FunctionLike) and not is_static(context):
1981 typ = bind_self(typ, self.scope.active_self_type(), is_classmethod=override_class)
1982 # Map the overridden method type to subtype context so that
1983 # it can be checked for compatibility.
1984 original_type = get_proper_type(base_attr.type)
1985 original_node = base_attr.node
1986 # `original_type` can be partial if (e.g.) it is originally an
1987 # instance variable from an `__init__` block that becomes deferred.
1988 if original_type is None or isinstance(original_type, PartialType):
1989 if self.pass_num < self.last_pass:
1990 # If there are passes left, defer this node until next pass,
1991 # otherwise try reconstructing the method type from available information.
1992 self.defer_node(defn, defn.info)
1993 return True
1994 elif isinstance(original_node, (FuncDef, OverloadedFuncDef)):
1995 original_type = self.function_type(original_node)
1996 elif isinstance(original_node, Decorator):
1997 original_type = self.function_type(original_node.func)
1998 elif isinstance(original_node, Var):
1999 # Super type can define method as an attribute.
2000 # See https://github.com/python/mypy/issues/10134
2001  
2002 # We also check that sometimes `original_node.type` is None.
2003 # This is the case when we use something like `__hash__ = None`.
2004 if original_node.type is not None:
2005 original_type = get_proper_type(original_node.type)
2006 else:
2007 original_type = NoneType()
2008 else:
2009 # Will always fail to typecheck below, since we know the node is a method
2010 original_type = NoneType()
2011 if isinstance(original_node, (FuncDef, OverloadedFuncDef)):
2012 original_class_or_static = original_node.is_class or original_node.is_static
2013 elif isinstance(original_node, Decorator):
2014 fdef = original_node.func
2015 original_class_or_static = fdef.is_class or fdef.is_static
2016 else:
2017 original_class_or_static = False # a variable can't be class or static
2018  
2019 if isinstance(original_type, FunctionLike):
2020 original_type = self.bind_and_map_method(base_attr, original_type, defn.info, base)
2021 if original_node and is_property(original_node):
2022 original_type = get_property_type(original_type)
2023  
2024 if isinstance(typ, FunctionLike) and is_property(defn):
2025 typ = get_property_type(typ)
2026 if (
2027 isinstance(original_node, Var)
2028 and not original_node.is_final
2029 and (not original_node.is_property or original_node.is_settable_property)
2030 and isinstance(defn, Decorator)
2031 ):
2032 # We only give an error where no other similar errors will be given.
2033 if not isinstance(original_type, AnyType):
2034 self.msg.fail(
2035 "Cannot override writeable attribute with read-only property",
2036 # Give an error on function line to match old behaviour.
2037 defn.func,
2038 code=codes.OVERRIDE,
2039 )
2040  
2041 if isinstance(original_type, AnyType) or isinstance(typ, AnyType):
2042 pass
2043 elif isinstance(original_type, FunctionLike) and isinstance(typ, FunctionLike):
2044 # Check that the types are compatible.
2045 self.check_override(
2046 typ,
2047 original_type,
2048 defn.name,
2049 name,
2050 base.name,
2051 original_class_or_static,
2052 override_class_or_static,
2053 context,
2054 )
2055 elif is_equivalent(original_type, typ):
2056 # Assume invariance for a non-callable attribute here. Note
2057 # that this doesn't affect read-only properties which can have
2058 # covariant overrides.
2059 pass
2060 elif (
2061 original_node
2062 and not self.is_writable_attribute(original_node)
2063 and is_subtype(typ, original_type)
2064 ):
2065 # If the attribute is read-only, allow covariance
2066 pass
2067 else:
2068 self.msg.signature_incompatible_with_supertype(
2069 defn.name, name, base.name, context, original=original_type, override=typ
2070 )
2071 return False
2072  
2073 def bind_and_map_method(
2074 self, sym: SymbolTableNode, typ: FunctionLike, sub_info: TypeInfo, super_info: TypeInfo
2075 ) -> FunctionLike:
2076 """Bind self-type and map type variables for a method.
2077  
2078 Arguments:
2079 sym: a symbol that points to method definition
2080 typ: method type on the definition
2081 sub_info: class where the method is used
2082 super_info: class where the method was defined
2083 """
2084 if isinstance(sym.node, (FuncDef, OverloadedFuncDef, Decorator)) and not is_static(
2085 sym.node
2086 ):
2087 if isinstance(sym.node, Decorator):
2088 is_class_method = sym.node.func.is_class
2089 else:
2090 is_class_method = sym.node.is_class
2091  
2092 mapped_typ = cast(FunctionLike, map_type_from_supertype(typ, sub_info, super_info))
2093 active_self_type = self.scope.active_self_type()
2094 if isinstance(mapped_typ, Overloaded) and active_self_type:
2095 # If we have an overload, filter to overloads that match the self type.
2096 # This avoids false positives for concrete subclasses of generic classes,
2097 # see testSelfTypeOverrideCompatibility for an example.
2098 filtered_items = []
2099 for item in mapped_typ.items:
2100 if not item.arg_types:
2101 filtered_items.append(item)
2102 item_arg = item.arg_types[0]
2103 if isinstance(item_arg, TypeVarType):
2104 item_arg = item_arg.upper_bound
2105 if is_subtype(active_self_type, item_arg):
2106 filtered_items.append(item)
2107 # If we don't have any filtered_items, maybe it's always a valid override
2108 # of the superclass? However if you get to that point you're in murky type
2109 # territory anyway, so we just preserve the type and have the behaviour match
2110 # that of older versions of mypy.
2111 if filtered_items:
2112 mapped_typ = Overloaded(filtered_items)
2113  
2114 return bind_self(mapped_typ, active_self_type, is_class_method)
2115 else:
2116 return cast(FunctionLike, map_type_from_supertype(typ, sub_info, super_info))
2117  
2118 def get_op_other_domain(self, tp: FunctionLike) -> Type | None:
2119 if isinstance(tp, CallableType):
2120 if tp.arg_kinds and tp.arg_kinds[0] == ARG_POS:
2121 return tp.arg_types[0]
2122 return None
2123 elif isinstance(tp, Overloaded):
2124 raw_items = [self.get_op_other_domain(it) for it in tp.items]
2125 items = [it for it in raw_items if it]
2126 if items:
2127 return make_simplified_union(items)
2128 return None
2129 else:
2130 assert False, "Need to check all FunctionLike subtypes here"
2131  
2132 def check_override(
2133 self,
2134 override: FunctionLike,
2135 original: FunctionLike,
2136 name: str,
2137 name_in_super: str,
2138 supertype: str,
2139 original_class_or_static: bool,
2140 override_class_or_static: bool,
2141 node: Context,
2142 ) -> None:
2143 """Check a method override with given signatures.
2144  
2145 Arguments:
2146 override: The signature of the overriding method.
2147 original: The signature of the original supertype method.
2148 name: The name of the subtype. This and the next argument are
2149 only used for generating error messages.
2150 supertype: The name of the supertype.
2151 """
2152 # Use boolean variable to clarify code.
2153 fail = False
2154 op_method_wider_note = False
2155 if not is_subtype(override, original, ignore_pos_arg_names=True):
2156 fail = True
2157 elif isinstance(override, Overloaded) and self.is_forward_op_method(name):
2158 # Operator method overrides cannot extend the domain, as
2159 # this could be unsafe with reverse operator methods.
2160 original_domain = self.get_op_other_domain(original)
2161 override_domain = self.get_op_other_domain(override)
2162 if (
2163 original_domain
2164 and override_domain
2165 and not is_subtype(override_domain, original_domain)
2166 ):
2167 fail = True
2168 op_method_wider_note = True
2169 if isinstance(override, FunctionLike):
2170 if original_class_or_static and not override_class_or_static:
2171 fail = True
2172 elif isinstance(original, CallableType) and isinstance(override, CallableType):
2173 if original.type_guard is not None and override.type_guard is None:
2174 fail = True
2175  
2176 if is_private(name):
2177 fail = False
2178  
2179 if fail:
2180 emitted_msg = False
2181  
2182 # Normalize signatures, so we get better diagnostics.
2183 if isinstance(override, (CallableType, Overloaded)):
2184 override = override.with_unpacked_kwargs()
2185 if isinstance(original, (CallableType, Overloaded)):
2186 original = original.with_unpacked_kwargs()
2187  
2188 if (
2189 isinstance(override, CallableType)
2190 and isinstance(original, CallableType)
2191 and len(override.arg_types) == len(original.arg_types)
2192 and override.min_args == original.min_args
2193 ):
2194 # Give more detailed messages for the common case of both
2195 # signatures having the same number of arguments and no
2196 # overloads.
2197  
2198 # override might have its own generic function type
2199 # variables. If an argument or return type of override
2200 # does not have the correct subtyping relationship
2201 # with the original type even after these variables
2202 # are erased, then it is definitely an incompatibility.
2203  
2204 override_ids = override.type_var_ids()
2205 type_name = None
2206 if isinstance(override.definition, FuncDef):
2207 type_name = override.definition.info.name
2208  
2209 def erase_override(t: Type) -> Type:
2210 return erase_typevars(t, ids_to_erase=override_ids)
2211  
2212 for i in range(len(override.arg_types)):
2213 if not is_subtype(
2214 original.arg_types[i], erase_override(override.arg_types[i])
2215 ):
2216 arg_type_in_super = original.arg_types[i]
2217  
2218 if isinstance(node, FuncDef):
2219 context: Context = node.arguments[i + len(override.bound_args)]
2220 else:
2221 context = node
2222 self.msg.argument_incompatible_with_supertype(
2223 i + 1,
2224 name,
2225 type_name,
2226 name_in_super,
2227 arg_type_in_super,
2228 supertype,
2229 context,
2230 secondary_context=node,
2231 )
2232 emitted_msg = True
2233  
2234 if not is_subtype(erase_override(override.ret_type), original.ret_type):
2235 self.msg.return_type_incompatible_with_supertype(
2236 name, name_in_super, supertype, original.ret_type, override.ret_type, node
2237 )
2238 emitted_msg = True
2239 elif isinstance(override, Overloaded) and isinstance(original, Overloaded):
2240 # Give a more detailed message in the case where the user is trying to
2241 # override an overload, and the subclass's overload is plausible, except
2242 # that the order of the variants are wrong.
2243 #
2244 # For example, if the parent defines the overload f(int) -> int and f(str) -> str
2245 # (in that order), and if the child swaps the two and does f(str) -> str and
2246 # f(int) -> int
2247 order = []
2248 for child_variant in override.items:
2249 for i, parent_variant in enumerate(original.items):
2250 if is_subtype(child_variant, parent_variant):
2251 order.append(i)
2252 break
2253  
2254 if len(order) == len(original.items) and order != sorted(order):
2255 self.msg.overload_signature_incompatible_with_supertype(
2256 name, name_in_super, supertype, node
2257 )
2258 emitted_msg = True
2259  
2260 if not emitted_msg:
2261 # Fall back to generic incompatibility message.
2262 self.msg.signature_incompatible_with_supertype(
2263 name, name_in_super, supertype, node, original=original, override=override
2264 )
2265 if op_method_wider_note:
2266 self.note(
2267 "Overloaded operator methods can't have wider argument types in overrides",
2268 node,
2269 code=codes.OVERRIDE,
2270 )
2271  
2272 def check__exit__return_type(self, defn: FuncItem) -> None:
2273 """Generate error if the return type of __exit__ is problematic.
2274  
2275 If __exit__ always returns False but the return type is declared
2276 as bool, mypy thinks that a with statement may "swallow"
2277 exceptions even though this is not the case, resulting in
2278 invalid reachability inference.
2279 """
2280 if not defn.type or not isinstance(defn.type, CallableType):
2281 return
2282  
2283 ret_type = get_proper_type(defn.type.ret_type)
2284 if not has_bool_item(ret_type):
2285 return
2286  
2287 returns = all_return_statements(defn)
2288 if not returns:
2289 return
2290  
2291 if all(
2292 isinstance(ret.expr, NameExpr) and ret.expr.fullname == "builtins.False"
2293 for ret in returns
2294 ):
2295 self.msg.incorrect__exit__return(defn)
2296  
2297 def visit_class_def(self, defn: ClassDef) -> None:
2298 """Type check a class definition."""
2299 typ = defn.info
2300 for base in typ.mro[1:]:
2301 if base.is_final:
2302 self.fail(message_registry.CANNOT_INHERIT_FROM_FINAL.format(base.name), defn)
2303 with self.tscope.class_scope(defn.info), self.enter_partial_types(is_class=True):
2304 old_binder = self.binder
2305 self.binder = ConditionalTypeBinder()
2306 with self.binder.top_frame_context():
2307 with self.scope.push_class(defn.info):
2308 self.accept(defn.defs)
2309 self.binder = old_binder
2310 if not (defn.info.typeddict_type or defn.info.tuple_type or defn.info.is_enum):
2311 # If it is not a normal class (not a special form) check class keywords.
2312 self.check_init_subclass(defn)
2313 if not defn.has_incompatible_baseclass:
2314 # Otherwise we've already found errors; more errors are not useful
2315 self.check_multiple_inheritance(typ)
2316 self.check_metaclass_compatibility(typ)
2317 self.check_final_deletable(typ)
2318  
2319 if defn.decorators:
2320 sig: Type = type_object_type(defn.info, self.named_type)
2321 # Decorators are applied in reverse order.
2322 for decorator in reversed(defn.decorators):
2323 if isinstance(decorator, CallExpr) and isinstance(
2324 decorator.analyzed, PromoteExpr
2325 ):
2326 # _promote is a special type checking related construct.
2327 continue
2328  
2329 dec = self.expr_checker.accept(decorator)
2330 temp = self.temp_node(sig, context=decorator)
2331 fullname = None
2332 if isinstance(decorator, RefExpr):
2333 fullname = decorator.fullname or None
2334  
2335 # TODO: Figure out how to have clearer error messages.
2336 # (e.g. "class decorator must be a function that accepts a type."
2337 old_allow_abstract_call = self.allow_abstract_call
2338 self.allow_abstract_call = True
2339 sig, _ = self.expr_checker.check_call(
2340 dec, [temp], [nodes.ARG_POS], defn, callable_name=fullname
2341 )
2342 self.allow_abstract_call = old_allow_abstract_call
2343 # TODO: Apply the sig to the actual TypeInfo so we can handle decorators
2344 # that completely swap out the type. (e.g. Callable[[Type[A]], Type[B]])
2345 if typ.defn.type_vars:
2346 for base_inst in typ.bases:
2347 for base_tvar, base_decl_tvar in zip(
2348 base_inst.args, base_inst.type.defn.type_vars
2349 ):
2350 if (
2351 isinstance(base_tvar, TypeVarType)
2352 and base_tvar.variance != INVARIANT
2353 and isinstance(base_decl_tvar, TypeVarType)
2354 and base_decl_tvar.variance != base_tvar.variance
2355 ):
2356 self.fail(
2357 f'Variance of TypeVar "{base_tvar.name}" incompatible '
2358 "with variance in parent type",
2359 context=defn,
2360 code=codes.TYPE_VAR,
2361 )
2362  
2363 if typ.is_protocol and typ.defn.type_vars:
2364 self.check_protocol_variance(defn)
2365 if not defn.has_incompatible_baseclass and defn.info.is_enum:
2366 self.check_enum(defn)
2367  
2368 def check_final_deletable(self, typ: TypeInfo) -> None:
2369 # These checks are only for mypyc. Only perform some checks that are easier
2370 # to implement here than in mypyc.
2371 for attr in typ.deletable_attributes:
2372 node = typ.names.get(attr)
2373 if node and isinstance(node.node, Var) and node.node.is_final:
2374 self.fail(message_registry.CANNOT_MAKE_DELETABLE_FINAL, node.node)
2375  
2376 def check_init_subclass(self, defn: ClassDef) -> None:
2377 """Check that keywords in a class definition are valid arguments for __init_subclass__().
2378  
2379 In this example:
2380 1 class Base:
2381 2 def __init_subclass__(cls, thing: int):
2382 3 pass
2383 4 class Child(Base, thing=5):
2384 5 def __init_subclass__(cls):
2385 6 pass
2386 7 Child()
2387  
2388 Base.__init_subclass__(thing=5) is called at line 4. This is what we simulate here.
2389 Child.__init_subclass__ is never called.
2390 """
2391 if defn.info.metaclass_type and defn.info.metaclass_type.type.fullname not in (
2392 "builtins.type",
2393 "abc.ABCMeta",
2394 ):
2395 # We can't safely check situations when both __init_subclass__ and a custom
2396 # metaclass are present.
2397 return
2398 # At runtime, only Base.__init_subclass__ will be called, so
2399 # we skip the current class itself.
2400 for base in defn.info.mro[1:]:
2401 if "__init_subclass__" not in base.names:
2402 continue
2403 name_expr = NameExpr(defn.name)
2404 name_expr.node = base
2405 callee = MemberExpr(name_expr, "__init_subclass__")
2406 args = list(defn.keywords.values())
2407 arg_names: list[str | None] = list(defn.keywords.keys())
2408 # 'metaclass' keyword is consumed by the rest of the type machinery,
2409 # and is never passed to __init_subclass__ implementations
2410 if "metaclass" in arg_names:
2411 idx = arg_names.index("metaclass")
2412 arg_names.pop(idx)
2413 args.pop(idx)
2414 arg_kinds = [ARG_NAMED] * len(args)
2415 call_expr = CallExpr(callee, args, arg_kinds, arg_names)
2416 call_expr.line = defn.line
2417 call_expr.column = defn.column
2418 call_expr.end_line = defn.end_line
2419 self.expr_checker.accept(call_expr, allow_none_return=True, always_allow_any=True)
2420 # We are only interested in the first Base having __init_subclass__,
2421 # all other bases have already been checked.
2422 break
2423  
2424 def check_enum(self, defn: ClassDef) -> None:
2425 assert defn.info.is_enum
2426 if defn.info.fullname not in ENUM_BASES:
2427 for sym in defn.info.names.values():
2428 if (
2429 isinstance(sym.node, Var)
2430 and sym.node.has_explicit_value
2431 and sym.node.name == "__members__"
2432 ):
2433 # `__members__` will always be overwritten by `Enum` and is considered
2434 # read-only so we disallow assigning a value to it
2435 self.fail(message_registry.ENUM_MEMBERS_ATTR_WILL_BE_OVERRIDEN, sym.node)
2436 for base in defn.info.mro[1:-1]: # we don't need self and `object`
2437 if base.is_enum and base.fullname not in ENUM_BASES:
2438 self.check_final_enum(defn, base)
2439  
2440 self.check_enum_bases(defn)
2441 self.check_enum_new(defn)
2442  
2443 def check_final_enum(self, defn: ClassDef, base: TypeInfo) -> None:
2444 for sym in base.names.values():
2445 if self.is_final_enum_value(sym):
2446 self.fail(f'Cannot extend enum with existing members: "{base.name}"', defn)
2447 break
2448  
2449 def is_final_enum_value(self, sym: SymbolTableNode) -> bool:
2450 if isinstance(sym.node, (FuncBase, Decorator)):
2451 return False # A method is fine
2452 if not isinstance(sym.node, Var):
2453 return True # Can be a class or anything else
2454  
2455 # Now, only `Var` is left, we need to check:
2456 # 1. Private name like in `__prop = 1`
2457 # 2. Dunder name like `__hash__ = some_hasher`
2458 # 3. Sunder name like `_order_ = 'a, b, c'`
2459 # 4. If it is a method / descriptor like in `method = classmethod(func)`
2460 if (
2461 is_private(sym.node.name)
2462 or is_dunder(sym.node.name)
2463 or is_sunder(sym.node.name)
2464 # TODO: make sure that `x = @class/staticmethod(func)`
2465 # and `x = property(prop)` both work correctly.
2466 # Now they are incorrectly counted as enum members.
2467 or isinstance(get_proper_type(sym.node.type), FunctionLike)
2468 ):
2469 return False
2470  
2471 return self.is_stub or sym.node.has_explicit_value
2472  
2473 def check_enum_bases(self, defn: ClassDef) -> None:
2474 """
2475 Non-enum mixins cannot appear after enum bases; this is disallowed at runtime:
2476  
2477 class Foo: ...
2478 class Bar(enum.Enum, Foo): ...
2479  
2480 But any number of enum mixins can appear in a class definition
2481 (even if multiple enum bases define __new__). So this is fine:
2482  
2483 class Foo(enum.Enum):
2484 def __new__(cls, val): ...
2485 class Bar(enum.Enum):
2486 def __new__(cls, val): ...
2487 class Baz(int, Foo, Bar, enum.Flag): ...
2488 """
2489 enum_base: Instance | None = None
2490 for base in defn.info.bases:
2491 if enum_base is None and base.type.is_enum:
2492 enum_base = base
2493 continue
2494 elif enum_base is not None and not base.type.is_enum:
2495 self.fail(
2496 f'No non-enum mixin classes are allowed after "{enum_base.str_with_options(self.options)}"',
2497 defn,
2498 )
2499 break
2500  
2501 def check_enum_new(self, defn: ClassDef) -> None:
2502 def has_new_method(info: TypeInfo) -> bool:
2503 new_method = info.get("__new__")
2504 return bool(
2505 new_method
2506 and new_method.node
2507 and new_method.node.fullname != "builtins.object.__new__"
2508 )
2509  
2510 has_new = False
2511 for base in defn.info.bases:
2512 candidate = False
2513  
2514 if base.type.is_enum:
2515 # If we have an `Enum`, then we need to check all its bases.
2516 candidate = any(not b.is_enum and has_new_method(b) for b in base.type.mro[1:-1])
2517 else:
2518 candidate = has_new_method(base.type)
2519  
2520 if candidate and has_new:
2521 self.fail(
2522 "Only a single data type mixin is allowed for Enum subtypes, "
2523 'found extra "{}"'.format(base.str_with_options(self.options)),
2524 defn,
2525 )
2526 elif candidate:
2527 has_new = True

2529 def check_protocol_variance(self, defn: ClassDef) -> None:
2530 """Check that protocol definition is compatible with declared
2531 variances of type variables.
2532  
2533 Note that we also prohibit declaring protocol classes as invariant
2534 if they are actually covariant/contravariant, since this may break
2535 transitivity of subtyping, see PEP 544.
2536 """
2537 info = defn.info
2538 object_type = Instance(info.mro[-1], [])
2539 tvars = info.defn.type_vars
2540 for i, tvar in enumerate(tvars):
2541 if not isinstance(tvar, TypeVarType):
2542 # Variance of TypeVarTuple and ParamSpec is underspecified by PEPs.
2543 continue
2544 up_args: list[Type] = [
2545 object_type if i == j else AnyType(TypeOfAny.special_form)
2546 for j, _ in enumerate(tvars)
2547 ]
2548 down_args: list[Type] = [
2549 UninhabitedType() if i == j else AnyType(TypeOfAny.special_form)
2550 for j, _ in enumerate(tvars)
2551 ]
2552 up, down = Instance(info, up_args), Instance(info, down_args)
2553 # TODO: add advanced variance checks for recursive protocols
2554 if is_subtype(down, up, ignore_declared_variance=True):
2555 expected = COVARIANT
2556 elif is_subtype(up, down, ignore_declared_variance=True):
2557 expected = CONTRAVARIANT
2558 else:
2559 expected = INVARIANT
2560 if expected != tvar.variance:
2561 self.msg.bad_proto_variance(tvar.variance, tvar.name, expected, defn)
2562  
2563 def check_multiple_inheritance(self, typ: TypeInfo) -> None:
2564 """Check for multiple inheritance related errors."""
2565 if len(typ.bases) <= 1:
2566 # No multiple inheritance.
2567 return
2568 # Verify that inherited attributes are compatible.
2569 mro = typ.mro[1:]
2570 for i, base in enumerate(mro):
2571 # Attributes defined in both the type and base are skipped.
2572 # Normal checks for attribute compatibility should catch any problems elsewhere.
2573 non_overridden_attrs = base.names.keys() - typ.names.keys()
2574 for name in non_overridden_attrs:
2575 if is_private(name):
2576 continue
  • E203 Whitespace before ':'
2577 for base2 in mro[i + 1 :]:
2578 # We only need to check compatibility of attributes from classes not
2579 # in a subclass relationship. For subclasses, normal (single inheritance)
2580 # checks suffice (these are implemented elsewhere).
2581 if name in base2.names and base2 not in base.mro:
2582 self.check_compatibility(name, base, base2, typ)
2583  
2584 def determine_type_of_member(self, sym: SymbolTableNode) -> Type | None:
2585 if sym.type is not None:
2586 return sym.type
2587 if isinstance(sym.node, FuncBase):
2588 return self.function_type(sym.node)
2589 if isinstance(sym.node, TypeInfo):
2590 if sym.node.typeddict_type:
2591 # We special-case TypedDict, because they don't define any constructor.
2592 return self.expr_checker.typeddict_callable(sym.node)
2593 else:
2594 return type_object_type(sym.node, self.named_type)
2595 if isinstance(sym.node, TypeVarExpr):
2596 # Use of TypeVars is rejected in an expression/runtime context, so
2597 # we don't need to check supertype compatibility for them.
2598 return AnyType(TypeOfAny.special_form)
2599 if isinstance(sym.node, TypeAlias):
2600 with self.msg.filter_errors():
2601 # Suppress any errors, they will be given when analyzing the corresponding node.
2602 # Here we may have incorrect options and location context.
2603 return self.expr_checker.alias_type_in_runtime_context(sym.node, ctx=sym.node)
2604 # TODO: handle more node kinds here.
2605 return None

2607 def check_compatibility(
2608 self, name: str, base1: TypeInfo, base2: TypeInfo, ctx: TypeInfo
2609 ) -> None:
2610 """Check if attribute name in base1 is compatible with base2 in multiple inheritance.
2611  
2612 Assume base1 comes before base2 in the MRO, and that base1 and base2 don't have
2613 a direct subclass relationship (i.e., the compatibility requirement only derives from
2614 multiple inheritance).
2615  
2616 This check verifies that a definition taken from base1 (and mapped to the current
2617 class ctx), is type compatible with the definition taken from base2 (also mapped), so
2618 that unsafe subclassing like this can be detected:
2619 class A(Generic[T]):
2620 def foo(self, x: T) -> None: ...
2621  
2622 class B:
2623 def foo(self, x: str) -> None: ...
2624  
2625 class C(B, A[int]): ... # this is unsafe because...
2626  
2627 x: A[int] = C()
2628 x.foo # ...runtime type is (str) -> None, while static type is (int) -> None
2629 """
2630 if name in ("__init__", "__new__", "__init_subclass__"):
2631 # __init__ and friends can be incompatible -- it's a special case.
2632 return
2633 first = base1.names[name]
2634 second = base2.names[name]
2635 first_type = get_proper_type(self.determine_type_of_member(first))
2636 second_type = get_proper_type(self.determine_type_of_member(second))
2637  
2638 # TODO: use more principled logic to decide is_subtype() vs is_equivalent().
2639 # We should rely on mutability of superclass node, not on types being Callable.
2640  
2641 # start with the special case that Instance can be a subtype of FunctionLike
2642 call = None
2643 if isinstance(first_type, Instance):
2644 call = find_member("__call__", first_type, first_type, is_operator=True)
2645 if call and isinstance(second_type, FunctionLike):
2646 second_sig = self.bind_and_map_method(second, second_type, ctx, base2)
2647 ok = is_subtype(call, second_sig, ignore_pos_arg_names=True)
2648 elif isinstance(first_type, FunctionLike) and isinstance(second_type, FunctionLike):
2649 if first_type.is_type_obj() and second_type.is_type_obj():
2650 # For class objects only check the subtype relationship of the classes,
2651 # since we allow incompatible overrides of '__init__'/'__new__'
2652 ok = is_subtype(
2653 left=fill_typevars_with_any(first_type.type_object()),
2654 right=fill_typevars_with_any(second_type.type_object()),
2655 )
2656 else:
2657 # First bind/map method types when necessary.
2658 first_sig = self.bind_and_map_method(first, first_type, ctx, base1)
2659 second_sig = self.bind_and_map_method(second, second_type, ctx, base2)
2660 ok = is_subtype(first_sig, second_sig, ignore_pos_arg_names=True)
2661 elif first_type and second_type:
2662 if isinstance(first.node, Var):
2663 first_type = expand_self_type(first.node, first_type, fill_typevars(ctx))
2664 if isinstance(second.node, Var):
2665 second_type = expand_self_type(second.node, second_type, fill_typevars(ctx))
2666 ok = is_equivalent(first_type, second_type)
2667 if not ok:
2668 second_node = base2[name].node
2669 if (
2670 isinstance(second_type, FunctionLike)
2671 and second_node is not None
2672 and is_property(second_node)
2673 ):
2674 second_type = get_property_type(second_type)
2675 ok = is_subtype(first_type, second_type)
2676 else:
2677 if first_type is None:
2678 self.msg.cannot_determine_type_in_base(name, base1.name, ctx)
2679 if second_type is None:
2680 self.msg.cannot_determine_type_in_base(name, base2.name, ctx)
2681 ok = True
2682 # Final attributes can never be overridden, but can override
2683 # non-final read-only attributes.
2684 if is_final_node(second.node) and not is_private(name):
2685 self.msg.cant_override_final(name, base2.name, ctx)
2686 if is_final_node(first.node):
2687 self.check_if_final_var_override_writable(name, second.node, ctx)
2688 # Some attributes like __slots__ and __deletable__ are special, and the type can
2689 # vary across class hierarchy.
2690 if isinstance(second.node, Var) and second.node.allow_incompatible_override:
2691 ok = True
2692 if not ok:
2693 self.msg.base_class_definitions_incompatible(name, base1, base2, ctx)
2694  
2695 def check_metaclass_compatibility(self, typ: TypeInfo) -> None:
2696 """Ensures that metaclasses of all parent types are compatible."""
2697 if (
2698 typ.is_metaclass()
2699 or typ.is_protocol
2700 or typ.is_named_tuple
2701 or typ.is_enum
2702 or typ.typeddict_type is not None
2703 ):
2704 return # Reasonable exceptions from this check
2705  
2706 metaclasses = [
2707 entry.metaclass_type
2708 for entry in typ.mro[1:-1]
2709 if entry.metaclass_type
2710 and not is_named_instance(entry.metaclass_type, "builtins.type")
2711 ]
2712 if not metaclasses:
2713 return
2714 if typ.metaclass_type is not None and all(
2715 is_subtype(typ.metaclass_type, meta) for meta in metaclasses
2716 ):
2717 return
2718 self.fail(
2719 "Metaclass conflict: the metaclass of a derived class must be "
2720 "a (non-strict) subclass of the metaclasses of all its bases",
2721 typ,
2722 )

2724 def visit_import_from(self, node: ImportFrom) -> None:
2725 self.check_import(node)

2730 def visit_import(self, node: Import) -> None:

2733 def check_import(self, node: ImportBase) -> None:
2734 for assign in node.assignments:
2735 lvalue = assign.lvalues[0]
2736 lvalue_type, _, __ = self.check_lvalue(lvalue)
2737 if lvalue_type is None:
2738 # TODO: This is broken.
2739 lvalue_type = AnyType(TypeOfAny.special_form)
2740 assert isinstance(assign.rvalue, NameExpr)
2741 message = message_registry.INCOMPATIBLE_IMPORT_OF.format(assign.rvalue.name)
2742 self.check_simple_assignment(
2743 lvalue_type,
2744 assign.rvalue,
2745 node,
2746 msg=message,
2747 lvalue_name="local name",
2748 rvalue_name="imported name",
2749 )

2752 # Statements

2754  
2755 def visit_block(self, b: Block) -> None:
2756 if b.is_unreachable:
2757 # This block was marked as being unreachable during semantic analysis.
2758 # It turns out any blocks marked in this way are *intentionally* marked
2759 # as unreachable -- so we don't display an error.
2760 self.binder.unreachable()
2761 return
2762 for s in b.body:
2763 if self.binder.is_unreachable():
2764 if not self.should_report_unreachable_issues():
2765 break
2766 if not self.is_noop_for_reachability(s):
2767 self.msg.unreachable_statement(s)
2768 break
2769 else:
2770 self.accept(s)
2771  
2772 def should_report_unreachable_issues(self) -> bool:
2773 return (
2774 self.in_checked_function()
2775 and self.options.warn_unreachable
2776 and not self.current_node_deferred
2777 and not self.binder.is_unreachable_warning_suppressed()
2778 )
2779  
2780 def is_noop_for_reachability(self, s: Statement) -> bool:
2781 """Returns 'true' if the given statement either throws an error of some kind
2782 or is a no-op.
2783  
2784 We use this function while handling the '--warn-unreachable' flag. When
2785 that flag is present, we normally report an error on any unreachable statement.
2786 But if that statement is just something like a 'pass' or a just-in-case 'assert False',
2787 reporting an error would be annoying.
2788 """
2789 if isinstance(s, AssertStmt) and is_false_literal(s.expr):
2790 return True
2791 elif isinstance(s, (RaiseStmt, PassStmt)):
2792 return True
2793 elif isinstance(s, ExpressionStmt):
2794 if isinstance(s.expr, EllipsisExpr):
2795 return True
2796 elif isinstance(s.expr, CallExpr):
2797 with self.expr_checker.msg.filter_errors():
2798 typ = get_proper_type(
2799 self.expr_checker.accept(
2800 s.expr, allow_none_return=True, always_allow_any=True
2801 )
2802 )
2803  
2804 if isinstance(typ, UninhabitedType):
2805 return True
2806 return False
2807  
2808 def visit_assignment_stmt(self, s: AssignmentStmt) -> None:
2809 """Type check an assignment statement.
2810  
2811 Handle all kinds of assignment statements (simple, indexed, multiple).
2812 """
2813 # Avoid type checking type aliases in stubs to avoid false
2814 # positives about modern type syntax available in stubs such
2815 # as X | Y.
2816 if not (s.is_alias_def and self.is_stub):
2817 with self.enter_final_context(s.is_final_def):
2818 self.check_assignment(s.lvalues[-1], s.rvalue, s.type is None, s.new_syntax)
2819  
2820 if s.is_alias_def:
2821 self.check_type_alias_rvalue(s)
2822  
2823 if (
2824 s.type is not None
2825 and self.options.disallow_any_unimported
2826 and has_any_from_unimported_type(s.type)
2827 ):
2828 if isinstance(s.lvalues[-1], TupleExpr):
2829 # This is a multiple assignment. Instead of figuring out which type is problematic,
2830 # give a generic error message.
2831 self.msg.unimported_type_becomes_any(
2832 "A type on this line", AnyType(TypeOfAny.special_form), s
2833 )
2834 else:
2835 self.msg.unimported_type_becomes_any("Type of variable", s.type, s)
2836 check_for_explicit_any(s.type, self.options, self.is_typeshed_stub, self.msg, context=s)
2837  
2838 if len(s.lvalues) > 1:
2839 # Chained assignment (e.g. x = y = ...).
2840 # Make sure that rvalue type will not be reinferred.
2841 if not self.has_type(s.rvalue):
2842 self.expr_checker.accept(s.rvalue)
2843 rvalue = self.temp_node(self.lookup_type(s.rvalue), s)
2844 for lv in s.lvalues[:-1]:
2845 with self.enter_final_context(s.is_final_def):
2846 self.check_assignment(lv, rvalue, s.type is None)
2847  
2848 self.check_final(s)
2849 if (
2850 s.is_final_def
2851 and s.type
2852 and not has_no_typevars(s.type)
2853 and self.scope.active_class() is not None
2854 ):
2855 self.fail(message_registry.DEPENDENT_FINAL_IN_CLASS_BODY, s)
2856  
2857 if s.unanalyzed_type and not self.in_checked_function():
2858 self.msg.annotation_in_unchecked_function(context=s)
2859  
2860 def check_type_alias_rvalue(self, s: AssignmentStmt) -> None:
2861 alias_type = self.expr_checker.accept(s.rvalue)
2862 self.store_type(s.lvalues[-1], alias_type)
2863  
2864 def check_assignment(
2865 self,
2866 lvalue: Lvalue,
2867 rvalue: Expression,
2868 infer_lvalue_type: bool = True,
2869 new_syntax: bool = False,
2870 ) -> None:
2871 """Type check a single assignment: lvalue = rvalue."""
2872 if isinstance(lvalue, (TupleExpr, ListExpr)):
2873 self.check_assignment_to_multiple_lvalues(
2874 lvalue.items, rvalue, rvalue, infer_lvalue_type
2875 )
2876 else:
2877 self.try_infer_partial_generic_type_from_assignment(lvalue, rvalue, "=")
2878 lvalue_type, index_lvalue, inferred = self.check_lvalue(lvalue)
2879 # If we're assigning to __getattr__ or similar methods, check that the signature is
2880 # valid.
2881 if isinstance(lvalue, NameExpr) and lvalue.node:
2882 name = lvalue.node.name
2883 if name in ("__setattr__", "__getattribute__", "__getattr__"):
2884 # If an explicit type is given, use that.
2885 if lvalue_type:
2886 signature = lvalue_type
2887 else:
2888 signature = self.expr_checker.accept(rvalue)
2889 if signature:
2890 if name == "__setattr__":
2891 self.check_setattr_method(signature, lvalue)
2892 else:
2893 self.check_getattr_method(signature, lvalue, name)
2894  
2895 if name == "__slots__":
2896 typ = lvalue_type or self.expr_checker.accept(rvalue)
2897 self.check_slots_definition(typ, lvalue)
2898 if name == "__match_args__" and inferred is not None:
2899 typ = self.expr_checker.accept(rvalue)
2900 self.check_match_args(inferred, typ, lvalue)
2901 if name == "__post_init__":
2902 active_class = self.scope.active_class()
2903 if active_class and dataclasses_plugin.is_processed_dataclass(active_class):
2904 self.fail(message_registry.DATACLASS_POST_INIT_MUST_BE_A_FUNCTION, rvalue)
2905  
2906 # Defer PartialType's super type checking.
2907 if (
2908 isinstance(lvalue, RefExpr)
2909 and not (isinstance(lvalue_type, PartialType) and lvalue_type.type is None)
2910 and not (isinstance(lvalue, NameExpr) and lvalue.name == "__match_args__")
2911 ):
2912 if self.check_compatibility_all_supers(lvalue, lvalue_type, rvalue):
2913 # We hit an error on this line; don't check for any others
2914 return
2915  
2916 if isinstance(lvalue, MemberExpr) and lvalue.name == "__match_args__":
2917 self.fail(message_registry.CANNOT_MODIFY_MATCH_ARGS, lvalue)
2918  
2919 if lvalue_type:
2920 if isinstance(lvalue_type, PartialType) and lvalue_type.type is None:
2921 # Try to infer a proper type for a variable with a partial None type.
2922 rvalue_type = self.expr_checker.accept(rvalue)
2923 if isinstance(get_proper_type(rvalue_type), NoneType):
2924 # This doesn't actually provide any additional information -- multiple
2925 # None initializers preserve the partial None type.
2926 return
2927  
2928 var = lvalue_type.var
2929 if is_valid_inferred_type(rvalue_type, is_lvalue_final=var.is_final):
2930 partial_types = self.find_partial_types(var)
2931 if partial_types is not None:
2932 if not self.current_node_deferred:
2933 # Partial type can't be final, so strip any literal values.
2934 rvalue_type = remove_instance_last_known_values(rvalue_type)
2935 inferred_type = make_simplified_union([rvalue_type, NoneType()])
2936 self.set_inferred_type(var, lvalue, inferred_type)
2937 else:
2938 var.type = None
2939 del partial_types[var]
2940 lvalue_type = var.type
2941 else:
2942 # Try to infer a partial type. No need to check the return value, as
2943 # an error will be reported elsewhere.
2944 self.infer_partial_type(lvalue_type.var, lvalue, rvalue_type)
2945 # Handle None PartialType's super type checking here, after it's resolved.
2946 if isinstance(lvalue, RefExpr) and self.check_compatibility_all_supers(
2947 lvalue, lvalue_type, rvalue
2948 ):
2949 # We hit an error on this line; don't check for any others
2950 return
2951 elif (
2952 is_literal_none(rvalue)
2953 and isinstance(lvalue, NameExpr)
2954 and isinstance(lvalue.node, Var)
2955 and lvalue.node.is_initialized_in_class
2956 and not new_syntax
2957 ):
2958 # Allow None's to be assigned to class variables with non-Optional types.
2959 rvalue_type = lvalue_type
2960 elif (
2961 isinstance(lvalue, MemberExpr) and lvalue.kind is None
2962 ): # Ignore member access to modules
2963 instance_type = self.expr_checker.accept(lvalue.expr)
2964 rvalue_type, lvalue_type, infer_lvalue_type = self.check_member_assignment(
2965 instance_type, lvalue_type, rvalue, context=rvalue
2966 )
2967 else:
2968 # Hacky special case for assigning a literal None
2969 # to a variable defined in a previous if
2970 # branch. When we detect this, we'll go back and
2971 # make the type optional. This is somewhat
2972 # unpleasant, and a generalization of this would
2973 # be an improvement!
2974 if (
2975 is_literal_none(rvalue)
2976 and isinstance(lvalue, NameExpr)
2977 and lvalue.kind == LDEF
2978 and isinstance(lvalue.node, Var)
2979 and lvalue.node.type
2980 and lvalue.node in self.var_decl_frames
2981 and not isinstance(get_proper_type(lvalue_type), AnyType)
2982 ):
2983 decl_frame_map = self.var_decl_frames[lvalue.node]
2984 # Check if the nearest common ancestor frame for the definition site
2985 # and the current site is the enclosing frame of an if/elif/else block.
2986 has_if_ancestor = False
2987 for frame in reversed(self.binder.frames):
2988 if frame.id in decl_frame_map:
2989 has_if_ancestor = frame.conditional_frame
2990 break
2991 if has_if_ancestor:
2992 lvalue_type = make_optional_type(lvalue_type)
2993 self.set_inferred_type(lvalue.node, lvalue, lvalue_type)
2994  
2995 rvalue_type = self.check_simple_assignment(lvalue_type, rvalue, context=rvalue)
2996  
2997 # Special case: only non-abstract non-protocol classes can be assigned to
2998 # variables with explicit type Type[A], where A is protocol or abstract.
2999 p_rvalue_type = get_proper_type(rvalue_type)
3000 p_lvalue_type = get_proper_type(lvalue_type)
3001 if (
3002 isinstance(p_rvalue_type, FunctionLike)
3003 and p_rvalue_type.is_type_obj()
3004 and (
3005 p_rvalue_type.type_object().is_abstract
3006 or p_rvalue_type.type_object().is_protocol
3007 )
3008 and isinstance(p_lvalue_type, TypeType)
3009 and isinstance(p_lvalue_type.item, Instance)
3010 and (
3011 p_lvalue_type.item.type.is_abstract or p_lvalue_type.item.type.is_protocol
3012 )
3013 ):
3014 self.msg.concrete_only_assign(p_lvalue_type, rvalue)
3015 return
3016 if rvalue_type and infer_lvalue_type and not isinstance(lvalue_type, PartialType):
3017 # Don't use type binder for definitions of special forms, like named tuples.
3018 if not (isinstance(lvalue, NameExpr) and lvalue.is_special_form):
3019 self.binder.assign_type(lvalue, rvalue_type, lvalue_type, False)
3020  
3021 elif index_lvalue:
3022 self.check_indexed_assignment(index_lvalue, rvalue, lvalue)
3023  
3024 if inferred:
3025 type_context = self.get_variable_type_context(inferred)
3026 rvalue_type = self.expr_checker.accept(rvalue, type_context=type_context)
3027 if not (
3028 inferred.is_final
3029 or (isinstance(lvalue, NameExpr) and lvalue.name == "__match_args__")
3030 ):
3031 rvalue_type = remove_instance_last_known_values(rvalue_type)
3032 self.infer_variable_type(inferred, lvalue, rvalue_type, rvalue)
3033 self.check_assignment_to_slots(lvalue)
3034  
3035 # (type, operator) tuples for augmented assignments supported with partial types
3036 partial_type_augmented_ops: Final = {("builtins.list", "+"), ("builtins.set", "|")}
3037  
3038 def get_variable_type_context(self, inferred: Var) -> Type | None:
3039 type_contexts = []
3040 if inferred.info:
3041 for base in inferred.info.mro[1:]:
3042 base_type, base_node = self.lvalue_type_from_base(inferred, base)
3043 if (
3044 base_type
3045 and not (isinstance(base_node, Var) and base_node.invalid_partial_type)
3046 and not isinstance(base_type, PartialType)
3047 ):
3048 type_contexts.append(base_type)
3049 # Use most derived supertype as type context if available.
3050 if not type_contexts:
3051 return None
3052 candidate = type_contexts[0]
3053 for other in type_contexts:
3054 if is_proper_subtype(other, candidate):
3055 candidate = other
3056 elif not is_subtype(candidate, other):
3057 # Multiple incompatible candidates, cannot use any of them as context.
3058 return None
3059 return candidate

3061 def try_infer_partial_generic_type_from_assignment(
3062 self, lvalue: Lvalue, rvalue: Expression, op: str
3063 ) -> None:
3064 """Try to infer a precise type for partial generic type from assignment.
3065  
3066 'op' is '=' for normal assignment and a binary operator ('+', ...) for
3067 augmented assignment.
3068  
3069 Example where this happens:
3070  
3071 x = []
3072 if foo():
3073 x = [1] # Infer List[int] as type of 'x'
3074 """
3075 var = None
3076 if (
3077 isinstance(lvalue, NameExpr)
3078 and isinstance(lvalue.node, Var)
3079 and isinstance(lvalue.node.type, PartialType)
3080 ):
3081 var = lvalue.node
3082 elif isinstance(lvalue, MemberExpr):
3083 var = self.expr_checker.get_partial_self_var(lvalue)
3084 if var is not None:
3085 typ = var.type
3086 assert isinstance(typ, PartialType)
3087 if typ.type is None:
3088 return
3089 # Return if this is an unsupported augmented assignment.
3090 if op != "=" and (typ.type.fullname, op) not in self.partial_type_augmented_ops:
3091 return
3092 # TODO: some logic here duplicates the None partial type counterpart
3093 # inlined in check_assignment(), see #8043.
3094 partial_types = self.find_partial_types(var)
3095 if partial_types is None:
3096 return
3097 rvalue_type = self.expr_checker.accept(rvalue)
3098 rvalue_type = get_proper_type(rvalue_type)
3099 if isinstance(rvalue_type, Instance):
3100 if rvalue_type.type == typ.type and is_valid_inferred_type(rvalue_type):
3101 var.type = rvalue_type
3102 del partial_types[var]
3103 elif isinstance(rvalue_type, AnyType):
3104 var.type = fill_typevars_with_any(typ.type)
3105 del partial_types[var]

3107 def check_compatibility_all_supers(
3108 self, lvalue: RefExpr, lvalue_type: Type | None, rvalue: Expression
3109 ) -> bool:
3110 lvalue_node = lvalue.node
3111 # Check if we are a class variable with at least one base class
3112 if (
3113 isinstance(lvalue_node, Var)
3114 and lvalue.kind in (MDEF, None)
3115 and len(lvalue_node.info.bases) > 0 # None for Vars defined via self
3116 ):
3117 for base in lvalue_node.info.mro[1:]:
3118 tnode = base.names.get(lvalue_node.name)
3119 if tnode is not None:
3120 if not self.check_compatibility_classvar_super(lvalue_node, base, tnode.node):
3121 # Show only one error per variable
3122 break
3123  
3124 if not self.check_compatibility_final_super(lvalue_node, base, tnode.node):
3125 # Show only one error per variable
3126 break
3127  
3128 direct_bases = lvalue_node.info.direct_base_classes()
3129 last_immediate_base = direct_bases[-1] if direct_bases else None
3130  
3131 for base in lvalue_node.info.mro[1:]:
3132 # The type of "__slots__" and some other attributes usually doesn't need to
3133 # be compatible with a base class. We'll still check the type of "__slots__"
3134 # against "object" as an exception.
3135 if lvalue_node.allow_incompatible_override and not (
3136 lvalue_node.name == "__slots__" and base.fullname == "builtins.object"
3137 ):
3138 continue
3139  
3140 if is_private(lvalue_node.name):
3141 continue
3142  
3143 base_type, base_node = self.lvalue_type_from_base(lvalue_node, base)
3144 if isinstance(base_type, PartialType):
3145 base_type = None
3146  
3147 if base_type:
3148 assert base_node is not None
3149 if not self.check_compatibility_super(
3150 lvalue, lvalue_type, rvalue, base, base_type, base_node
3151 ):
3152 # Only show one error per variable; even if other
3153 # base classes are also incompatible
3154 return True
3155 if base is last_immediate_base:
3156 # At this point, the attribute was found to be compatible with all
3157 # immediate parents.
3158 break
3159 return False

3161 def check_compatibility_super(
3162 self,
3163 lvalue: RefExpr,
3164 lvalue_type: Type | None,
3165 rvalue: Expression,
3166 base: TypeInfo,
3167 base_type: Type,
3168 base_node: Node,
3169 ) -> bool:
3170 lvalue_node = lvalue.node
3171 assert isinstance(lvalue_node, Var)
3172  
3173 # Do not check whether the rvalue is compatible if the
3174 # lvalue had a type defined; this is handled by other
3175 # parts, and all we have to worry about in that case is
3176 # that lvalue is compatible with the base class.
3177 compare_node = None
3178 if lvalue_type:
3179 compare_type = lvalue_type
3180 compare_node = lvalue.node
3181 else:
3182 compare_type = self.expr_checker.accept(rvalue, base_type)
3183 if isinstance(rvalue, NameExpr):
3184 compare_node = rvalue.node
3185 if isinstance(compare_node, Decorator):
3186 compare_node = compare_node.func
3187  
3188 base_type = get_proper_type(base_type)
3189 compare_type = get_proper_type(compare_type)
3190 if compare_type:
3191 if isinstance(base_type, CallableType) and isinstance(compare_type, CallableType):
3192 base_static = is_node_static(base_node)
3193 compare_static = is_node_static(compare_node)
3194  
3195 # In case compare_static is unknown, also check
3196 # if 'definition' is set. The most common case for
3197 # this is with TempNode(), where we lose all
3198 # information about the real rvalue node (but only get
3199 # the rvalue type)
3200 if compare_static is None and compare_type.definition:
3201 compare_static = is_node_static(compare_type.definition)
3202  
3203 # Compare against False, as is_node_static can return None
3204 if base_static is False and compare_static is False:
3205 # Class-level function objects and classmethods become bound
3206 # methods: the former to the instance, the latter to the
3207 # class
3208 base_type = bind_self(base_type, self.scope.active_self_type())
3209 compare_type = bind_self(compare_type, self.scope.active_self_type())
3210  
3211 # If we are a static method, ensure to also tell the
3212 # lvalue it now contains a static method
3213 if base_static and compare_static:
3214 lvalue_node.is_staticmethod = True
3215  
3216 ok = self.check_subtype(
3217 compare_type,
3218 base_type,
3219 rvalue,
3220 message_registry.INCOMPATIBLE_TYPES_IN_ASSIGNMENT,
3221 "expression has type",
3222 f'base class "{base.name}" defined the type as',
3223 )
3224 if (
3225 ok
3226 and codes.MUTABLE_OVERRIDE in self.options.enabled_error_codes
3227 and self.is_writable_attribute(base_node)
3228 ):
3229 ok = self.check_subtype(
3230 base_type,
3231 compare_type,
3232 rvalue,
3233 message_registry.COVARIANT_OVERRIDE_OF_MUTABLE_ATTRIBUTE,
3234 f'base class "{base.name}" defined the type as',
3235 "expression has type",
3236 )
3237 return ok
3238 return True

3240 def lvalue_type_from_base(
3241 self, expr_node: Var, base: TypeInfo
3242 ) -> tuple[Type | None, Node | None]:
3243 """For a NameExpr that is part of a class, walk all base classes and try
3244 to find the first class that defines a Type for the same name."""
3245 expr_name = expr_node.name
3246 base_var = base.names.get(expr_name)
3247  
3248 if base_var:
3249 base_node = base_var.node
3250 base_type = base_var.type
3251 if isinstance(base_node, Var) and base_type is not None:
3252 base_type = expand_self_type(base_node, base_type, fill_typevars(expr_node.info))
3253 if isinstance(base_node, Decorator):
3254 base_node = base_node.func
3255 base_type = base_node.type
3256  
3257 if base_type:
3258 if not has_no_typevars(base_type):
3259 self_type = self.scope.active_self_type()
3260 assert self_type is not None, "Internal error: base lookup outside class"
3261 if isinstance(self_type, TupleType):
3262 instance = tuple_fallback(self_type)
3263 else:
3264 instance = self_type
3265 itype = map_instance_to_supertype(instance, base)
3266 base_type = expand_type_by_instance(base_type, itype)
3267  
3268 base_type = get_proper_type(base_type)
3269 if isinstance(base_type, CallableType) and isinstance(base_node, FuncDef):
3270 # If we are a property, return the Type of the return
3271 # value, not the Callable
3272 if base_node.is_property:
3273 base_type = get_proper_type(base_type.ret_type)
3274 if isinstance(base_type, FunctionLike) and isinstance(
3275 base_node, OverloadedFuncDef
3276 ):
3277 # Same for properties with setter
3278 if base_node.is_property:
3279 base_type = base_type.items[0].ret_type
3280  
3281 return base_type, base_node
3282  
3283 return None, None

3288 if not isinstance(base_node, Var):

3298 def check_compatibility_final_super(
3299 self, node: Var, base: TypeInfo, base_node: Node | None
3300 ) -> bool:
3301 """Check if an assignment overrides a final attribute in a base class.
3302  
3303 This only checks situations where either a node in base class is not a variable
3304 but a final method, or where override is explicitly declared as final.
3305 In these cases we give a more detailed error message. In addition, we check that
3306 a final variable doesn't override writeable attribute, which is not safe.
3307  
3308 Other situations are checked in `check_final()`.
3309 """
3310 if not isinstance(base_node, (Var, FuncBase, Decorator)):
3311 return True
3312 if is_private(node.name):
3313 return True
3314 if base_node.is_final and (node.is_final or not isinstance(base_node, Var)):
3315 # Give this error only for explicit override attempt with `Final`, or
3316 # if we are overriding a final method with variable.
3317 # Other override attempts will be flagged as assignment to constant
3318 # in `check_final()`.
3319 self.msg.cant_override_final(node.name, base.name, node)
3320 return False
3321 if node.is_final:
3322 if base.fullname in ENUM_BASES or node.name in ENUM_SPECIAL_PROPS:
3323 return True
3324 self.check_if_final_var_override_writable(node.name, base_node, node)
3325 return True

3361 def check_final(self, s: AssignmentStmt | OperatorAssignmentStmt | AssignmentExpr) -> None:
3362 """Check if this assignment does not assign to a final attribute.
3363  
3364 This function performs the check only for name assignments at module
3365 and class scope. The assignments to `obj.attr` and `Cls.attr` are checked
3366 in checkmember.py.
3367 """
3368 if isinstance(s, AssignmentStmt):
3369 lvs = self.flatten_lvalues(s.lvalues)
3370 elif isinstance(s, AssignmentExpr):
3371 lvs = [s.target]
3372 else:
3373 lvs = [s.lvalue]
3374 is_final_decl = s.is_final_def if isinstance(s, AssignmentStmt) else False
3375 if is_final_decl and self.scope.active_class():
3376 lv = lvs[0]
3377 assert isinstance(lv, RefExpr)
3378 if lv.node is not None:
3379 assert isinstance(lv.node, Var)
3380 if (
3381 lv.node.final_unset_in_class
3382 and not lv.node.final_set_in_init
3383 and not self.is_stub
3384 and # It is OK to skip initializer in stub files.
3385 # Avoid extra error messages, if there is no type in Final[...],
3386 # then we already reported the error about missing r.h.s.
3387 isinstance(s, AssignmentStmt)
3388 and s.type is not None
3389 ):
3390 self.msg.final_without_value(s)
3391 for lv in lvs:
3392 if isinstance(lv, RefExpr) and isinstance(lv.node, Var):
3393 name = lv.node.name
3394 cls = self.scope.active_class()
3395 if cls is not None:
3396 # These additional checks exist to give more error messages
3397 # even if the final attribute was overridden with a new symbol
3398 # (which is itself an error)...
3399 for base in cls.mro[1:]:
3400 sym = base.names.get(name)
3401 # We only give this error if base node is variable,
3402 # overriding final method will be caught in
3403 # `check_compatibility_final_super()`.
3404 if sym and isinstance(sym.node, Var):
3405 if sym.node.is_final and not is_final_decl:
3406 self.msg.cant_assign_to_final(name, sym.node.info is None, s)
3407 # ...but only once
3408 break
3409 if lv.node.is_final and not is_final_decl:
3410 self.msg.cant_assign_to_final(name, lv.node.info is None, s)

3412 def check_assignment_to_slots(self, lvalue: Lvalue) -> None:
3413 if not isinstance(lvalue, MemberExpr):
3414 return
3415  
3416 inst = get_proper_type(self.expr_checker.accept(lvalue.expr))
3417 if not isinstance(inst, Instance):
3418 return
3419 if inst.type.slots is None:
3420 return # Slots do not exist, we can allow any assignment
3421 if lvalue.name in inst.type.slots:
3422 return # We are assigning to an existing slot
3423 for base_info in inst.type.mro[:-1]:
3424 if base_info.names.get("__setattr__") is not None:
3425 # When type has `__setattr__` defined,
3426 # we can assign any dynamic value.
3427 # We exclude object, because it always has `__setattr__`.
3428 return
3429  
3430 definition = inst.type.get(lvalue.name)
3431 if definition is None:
3432 # We don't want to duplicate
3433 # `"SomeType" has no attribute "some_attr"`
3434 # error twice.
3435 return
3436 if self.is_assignable_slot(lvalue, definition.type):
3437 return
3438  
3439 self.fail(
3440 message_registry.NAME_NOT_IN_SLOTS.format(lvalue.name, inst.type.fullname), lvalue
3441 )
3442  
3443 def is_assignable_slot(self, lvalue: Lvalue, typ: Type | None) -> bool:
3444 if getattr(lvalue, "node", None):
3445 return False # This is a definition
3446  
3447 typ = get_proper_type(typ)
3448 if typ is None or isinstance(typ, AnyType):
3449 return True # Any can be literally anything, like `@propery`
3450 if isinstance(typ, Instance):
3451 # When working with instances, we need to know if they contain
3452 # `__set__` special method. Like `@property` does.
3453 # This makes assigning to properties possible,
3454 # even without extra slot spec.
3455 return typ.type.get("__set__") is not None
3456 if isinstance(typ, FunctionLike):
3457 return True # Can be a property, or some other magic
3458 if isinstance(typ, UnionType):
3459 return all(self.is_assignable_slot(lvalue, u) for u in typ.items)
3460 return False

3462 def flatten_rvalues(self, rvalues: list[Expression]) -> list[Expression]:
3463 """Flatten expression list by expanding those * items that have tuple type.
3464  
3465 For each regular type item in the tuple type use a TempNode(), for an Unpack
3466 item use a corresponding StarExpr(TempNode()).
3467 """
3468 new_rvalues = []
3469 for rv in rvalues:
3470 if not isinstance(rv, StarExpr):
3471 new_rvalues.append(rv)
3472 continue
3473 typ = get_proper_type(self.expr_checker.accept(rv.expr))
3474 if not isinstance(typ, TupleType):
3475 new_rvalues.append(rv)
3476 continue
3477 for t in typ.items:
3478 if not isinstance(t, UnpackType):
3479 new_rvalues.append(TempNode(t))
3480 else:
3481 unpacked = get_proper_type(t.type)
3482 if isinstance(unpacked, TypeVarTupleType):
3483 fallback = unpacked.upper_bound
3484 else:
3485 assert (
3486 isinstance(unpacked, Instance)
3487 and unpacked.type.fullname == "builtins.tuple"
3488 )
3489 fallback = unpacked
3490 new_rvalues.append(StarExpr(TempNode(fallback)))
3491 return new_rvalues

3493 def check_assignment_to_multiple_lvalues(

3577 def check_rvalue_count_in_assignment(
3578 self,
3579 lvalues: list[Lvalue],
3580 rvalue_count: int,
3581 context: Context,
3582 rvalue_unpack: int | None = None,
3583 ) -> bool:
3584 if rvalue_unpack is not None:
3585 if not any(isinstance(e, StarExpr) for e in lvalues):
3586 self.fail("Variadic tuple unpacking requires a star target", context)
3587 return False
3588 if len(lvalues) > rvalue_count:
3589 self.fail(message_registry.TOO_MANY_TARGETS_FOR_VARIADIC_UNPACK, context)
3590 return False
3591 left_star_index = next(i for i, lv in enumerate(lvalues) if isinstance(lv, StarExpr))
3592 left_prefix = left_star_index
3593 left_suffix = len(lvalues) - left_star_index - 1
3594 right_prefix = rvalue_unpack
3595 right_suffix = rvalue_count - rvalue_unpack - 1
3596 if left_suffix > right_suffix or left_prefix > right_prefix:
3597 # Case of asymmetric unpack like:
3598 # rv: tuple[int, *Ts, int, int]
3599 # x, y, *xs, z = rv
3600 # it is technically valid, but is tricky to reason about.
3601 # TODO: support this (at least if the r.h.s. unpack is a homogeneous tuple).
3602 self.fail(message_registry.TOO_MANY_TARGETS_FOR_VARIADIC_UNPACK, context)
3603 return True
3604 if any(isinstance(lvalue, StarExpr) for lvalue in lvalues):
3605 if len(lvalues) - 1 > rvalue_count:
3606 self.msg.wrong_number_values_to_unpack(rvalue_count, len(lvalues) - 1, context)
3607 return False
3608 elif rvalue_count != len(lvalues):
3609 self.msg.wrong_number_values_to_unpack(rvalue_count, len(lvalues), context)
3610 return False
3611 return True
3612  
3613 def check_multi_assignment(
3614 self,
3615 lvalues: list[Lvalue],
3616 rvalue: Expression,
3617 context: Context,
3618 infer_lvalue_type: bool = True,
3619 rv_type: Type | None = None,
3620 undefined_rvalue: bool = False,
3621 ) -> None:
3622 """Check the assignment of one rvalue to a number of lvalues."""
3623  
3624 # Infer the type of an ordinary rvalue expression.
3625 # TODO: maybe elsewhere; redundant.
3626 rvalue_type = get_proper_type(rv_type or self.expr_checker.accept(rvalue))
3627  
3628 if isinstance(rvalue_type, TypeVarLikeType):
3629 rvalue_type = get_proper_type(rvalue_type.upper_bound)
3630  
3631 if isinstance(rvalue_type, UnionType):
3632 # If this is an Optional type in non-strict Optional code, unwrap it.
3633 relevant_items = rvalue_type.relevant_items()
3634 if len(relevant_items) == 1:
3635 rvalue_type = get_proper_type(relevant_items[0])
3636  
3637 if (
3638 isinstance(rvalue_type, TupleType)
3639 and find_unpack_in_list(rvalue_type.items) is not None
3640 ):
3641 # Normalize for consistent handling with "old-style" homogeneous tuples.
3642 rvalue_type = expand_type(rvalue_type, {})
3643  
3644 if isinstance(rvalue_type, AnyType):
3645 for lv in lvalues:
3646 if isinstance(lv, StarExpr):
3647 lv = lv.expr
3648 temp_node = self.temp_node(
3649 AnyType(TypeOfAny.from_another_any, source_any=rvalue_type), context
3650 )
3651 self.check_assignment(lv, temp_node, infer_lvalue_type)
3652 elif isinstance(rvalue_type, TupleType):
3653 self.check_multi_assignment_from_tuple(
3654 lvalues, rvalue, rvalue_type, context, undefined_rvalue, infer_lvalue_type
3655 )
3656 elif isinstance(rvalue_type, UnionType):
3657 self.check_multi_assignment_from_union(
3658 lvalues, rvalue, rvalue_type, context, infer_lvalue_type
3659 )
3660 elif isinstance(rvalue_type, Instance) and rvalue_type.type.fullname == "builtins.str":
3661 self.msg.unpacking_strings_disallowed(context)
3662 else:
3663 self.check_multi_assignment_from_iterable(
3664 lvalues, rvalue_type, context, infer_lvalue_type
3665 )
3666  
3667 def check_multi_assignment_from_union(
3668 self,
3669 lvalues: list[Expression],
3670 rvalue: Expression,
3671 rvalue_type: UnionType,
3672 context: Context,
3673 infer_lvalue_type: bool,
3674 ) -> None:
3675 """Check assignment to multiple lvalue targets when rvalue type is a Union[...].
3676 For example:
3677  
3678 t: Union[Tuple[int, int], Tuple[str, str]]
3679 x, y = t
3680 reveal_type(x) # Union[int, str]
3681  
3682 The idea in this case is to process the assignment for every item of the union.
3683 Important note: the types are collected in two places, 'union_types' contains
3684 inferred types for first assignments, 'assignments' contains the narrowed types
3685 for binder.
3686 """
3687 self.no_partial_types = True
3688 transposed: tuple[list[Type], ...] = tuple([] for _ in self.flatten_lvalues(lvalues))
3689 # Notify binder that we want to defer bindings and instead collect types.
3690 with self.binder.accumulate_type_assignments() as assignments:
3691 for item in rvalue_type.items:
3692 # Type check the assignment separately for each union item and collect
3693 # the inferred lvalue types for each union item.
3694 self.check_multi_assignment(
3695 lvalues,
3696 rvalue,
3697 context,
3698 infer_lvalue_type=infer_lvalue_type,
3699 rv_type=item,
3700 undefined_rvalue=True,
3701 )
3702 for t, lv in zip(transposed, self.flatten_lvalues(lvalues)):
3703 # We can access _type_maps directly since temporary type maps are
3704 # only created within expressions.
3705 t.append(self._type_maps[0].pop(lv, AnyType(TypeOfAny.special_form)))
3706 union_types = tuple(make_simplified_union(col) for col in transposed)
3707 for expr, items in assignments.items():
3708 # Bind a union of types collected in 'assignments' to every expression.
3709 if isinstance(expr, StarExpr):
3710 expr = expr.expr
3711  
3712 # TODO: See todo in binder.py, ConditionalTypeBinder.assign_type
3713 # It's unclear why the 'declared_type' param is sometimes 'None'
3714 clean_items: list[tuple[Type, Type]] = []
3715 for type, declared_type in items:
3716 assert declared_type is not None
3717 clean_items.append((type, declared_type))
3718  
3719 types, declared_types = zip(*clean_items)
3720 self.binder.assign_type(
3721 expr,
3722 make_simplified_union(list(types)),
3723 make_simplified_union(list(declared_types)),
3724 False,
3725 )
3726 for union, lv in zip(union_types, self.flatten_lvalues(lvalues)):
3727 # Properly store the inferred types.
3728 _1, _2, inferred = self.check_lvalue(lv)
3729 if inferred:
3730 self.set_inferred_type(inferred, lv, union)
3731 else:
3732 self.store_type(lv, union)
3733 self.no_partial_types = False
3734  
3735 def flatten_lvalues(self, lvalues: list[Expression]) -> list[Expression]:
3736 res: list[Expression] = []
3737 for lv in lvalues:
3738 if isinstance(lv, (TupleExpr, ListExpr)):
3739 res.extend(self.flatten_lvalues(lv.items))
3740 if isinstance(lv, StarExpr):
3741 # Unwrap StarExpr, since it is unwrapped by other helpers.
3742 lv = lv.expr
3743 res.append(lv)
3744 return res

3746 def check_multi_assignment_from_tuple(
3747 self,
3748 lvalues: list[Lvalue],
3749 rvalue: Expression,
3750 rvalue_type: TupleType,
3751 context: Context,
3752 undefined_rvalue: bool,
3753 infer_lvalue_type: bool = True,
3754 ) -> None:
3755 rvalue_unpack = find_unpack_in_list(rvalue_type.items)
3756 if self.check_rvalue_count_in_assignment(
3757 lvalues, len(rvalue_type.items), context, rvalue_unpack=rvalue_unpack
3758 ):
3759 star_index = next(
3760 (i for i, lv in enumerate(lvalues) if isinstance(lv, StarExpr)), len(lvalues)
3761 )
3762  
3763 left_lvs = lvalues[:star_index]
3764 star_lv = cast(StarExpr, lvalues[star_index]) if star_index != len(lvalues) else None
  • E203 Whitespace before ':'
3765 right_lvs = lvalues[star_index + 1 :]
3766  
3767 if not undefined_rvalue:
3768 # Infer rvalue again, now in the correct type context.
3769 lvalue_type = self.lvalue_type_for_inference(lvalues, rvalue_type)
3770 reinferred_rvalue_type = get_proper_type(
3771 self.expr_checker.accept(rvalue, lvalue_type)
3772 )
3773  
3774 if isinstance(reinferred_rvalue_type, UnionType):
3775 # If this is an Optional type in non-strict Optional code, unwrap it.
3776 relevant_items = reinferred_rvalue_type.relevant_items()
3777 if len(relevant_items) == 1:
3778 reinferred_rvalue_type = get_proper_type(relevant_items[0])
3779 if isinstance(reinferred_rvalue_type, UnionType):
3780 self.check_multi_assignment_from_union(
3781 lvalues, rvalue, reinferred_rvalue_type, context, infer_lvalue_type
3782 )
3783 return
3784 if isinstance(reinferred_rvalue_type, AnyType):
3785 # We can get Any if the current node is
3786 # deferred. Doing more inference in deferred nodes
3787 # is hard, so give up for now. We can also get
3788 # here if reinferring types above changes the
3789 # inferred return type for an overloaded function
3790 # to be ambiguous.
3791 return
3792 assert isinstance(reinferred_rvalue_type, TupleType)
3793 rvalue_type = reinferred_rvalue_type
3794  
3795 left_rv_types, star_rv_types, right_rv_types = self.split_around_star(
3796 rvalue_type.items, star_index, len(lvalues)
3797 )
3798  
3799 for lv, rv_type in zip(left_lvs, left_rv_types):
3800 self.check_assignment(lv, self.temp_node(rv_type, context), infer_lvalue_type)
3801 if star_lv:
3802 list_expr = ListExpr(
3803 [
3804 self.temp_node(rv_type, context)
3805 if not isinstance(rv_type, UnpackType)
3806 else StarExpr(self.temp_node(rv_type.type, context))
3807 for rv_type in star_rv_types
3808 ]
3809 )
3810 list_expr.set_line(context)
3811 self.check_assignment(star_lv.expr, list_expr, infer_lvalue_type)
3812 for lv, rv_type in zip(right_lvs, right_rv_types):
3813 self.check_assignment(lv, self.temp_node(rv_type, context), infer_lvalue_type)
3814 else:
3815 # Store meaningful Any types for lvalues, errors are already given
3816 # by check_rvalue_count_in_assignment()
3817 if infer_lvalue_type:
3818 for lv in lvalues:
3819 if (
3820 isinstance(lv, NameExpr)
3821 and isinstance(lv.node, Var)
3822 and lv.node.type is None
3823 ):
3824 lv.node.type = AnyType(TypeOfAny.from_error)
3825 elif isinstance(lv, StarExpr):
3826 if (
3827 isinstance(lv.expr, NameExpr)
3828 and isinstance(lv.expr.node, Var)
3829 and lv.expr.node.type is None
3830 ):
3831 lv.expr.node.type = self.named_generic_type(
3832 "builtins.list", [AnyType(TypeOfAny.from_error)]
3833 )

3835 def lvalue_type_for_inference(self, lvalues: list[Lvalue], rvalue_type: TupleType) -> Type:
3836 star_index = next(
3837 (i for i, lv in enumerate(lvalues) if isinstance(lv, StarExpr)), len(lvalues)
3838 )
3839 left_lvs = lvalues[:star_index]
3840 star_lv = cast(StarExpr, lvalues[star_index]) if star_index != len(lvalues) else None
  • E203 Whitespace before ':'
3841 right_lvs = lvalues[star_index + 1 :]
3842 left_rv_types, star_rv_types, right_rv_types = self.split_around_star(
3843 rvalue_type.items, star_index, len(lvalues)
3844 )
3845  
3846 type_parameters: list[Type] = []
3847  
3848 def append_types_for_inference(lvs: list[Expression], rv_types: list[Type]) -> None:
3849 for lv, rv_type in zip(lvs, rv_types):
3850 sub_lvalue_type, index_expr, inferred = self.check_lvalue(lv)
3851 if sub_lvalue_type and not isinstance(sub_lvalue_type, PartialType):
3852 type_parameters.append(sub_lvalue_type)
3853 else: # index lvalue
3854 # TODO Figure out more precise type context, probably
3855 # based on the type signature of the _set method.
3856 type_parameters.append(rv_type)
3857  
3858 append_types_for_inference(left_lvs, left_rv_types)
3859  
3860 if star_lv:
3861 sub_lvalue_type, index_expr, inferred = self.check_lvalue(star_lv.expr)
3862 if sub_lvalue_type and not isinstance(sub_lvalue_type, PartialType):
3863 type_parameters.extend([sub_lvalue_type] * len(star_rv_types))
3864 else: # index lvalue
3865 # TODO Figure out more precise type context, probably
3866 # based on the type signature of the _set method.
3867 type_parameters.extend(star_rv_types)
3868  
3869 append_types_for_inference(right_lvs, right_rv_types)
3870  
3871 return TupleType(type_parameters, self.named_type("builtins.tuple"))
3872  
3873 def split_around_star(
3874 self, items: list[T], star_index: int, length: int
3875 ) -> tuple[list[T], list[T], list[T]]:
3876 """Splits a list of items in three to match another list of length 'length'
3877 that contains a starred expression at 'star_index' in the following way:
3878  
3879 star_index = 2, length = 5 (i.e., [a,b,*,c,d]), items = [1,2,3,4,5,6,7]
3880 returns in: ([1,2], [3,4,5], [6,7])
3881 """
3882 nr_right_of_star = length - star_index - 1
3883 right_index = -nr_right_of_star if nr_right_of_star != 0 else len(items)
3884 left = items[:star_index]
3885 star = items[star_index:right_index]
3886 right = items[right_index:]
3887 return left, star, right

3889 def type_is_iterable(self, type: Type) -> bool:
3890 type = get_proper_type(type)
3891 if isinstance(type, FunctionLike) and type.is_type_obj():
3892 type = type.fallback
3893 return is_subtype(
3894 type, self.named_generic_type("typing.Iterable", [AnyType(TypeOfAny.special_form)])
3895 )

3897 def check_multi_assignment_from_iterable(
3898 self,
3899 lvalues: list[Lvalue],
3900 rvalue_type: Type,
3901 context: Context,
3902 infer_lvalue_type: bool = True,
3903 ) -> None:
3904 rvalue_type = get_proper_type(rvalue_type)
3905 if self.type_is_iterable(rvalue_type) and isinstance(
3906 rvalue_type, (Instance, CallableType, TypeType, Overloaded)
3907 ):
3908 item_type = self.iterable_item_type(rvalue_type, context)
3909 for lv in lvalues:
3910 if isinstance(lv, StarExpr):
3911 items_type = self.named_generic_type("builtins.list", [item_type])
3912 self.check_assignment(
3913 lv.expr, self.temp_node(items_type, context), infer_lvalue_type
3914 )
3915 else:
3916 self.check_assignment(
3917 lv, self.temp_node(item_type, context), infer_lvalue_type
3918 )
3919 else:
3920 self.msg.type_not_iterable(rvalue_type, context)

3922 def check_lvalue(self, lvalue: Lvalue) -> tuple[Type | None, IndexExpr | None, Var | None]:
3923 lvalue_type = None
3924 index_lvalue = None
3925 inferred = None
3926  
3927 if self.is_definition(lvalue) and (
3928 not isinstance(lvalue, NameExpr) or isinstance(lvalue.node, Var)
3929 ):
3930 if isinstance(lvalue, NameExpr):
3931 assert isinstance(lvalue.node, Var)
3932 inferred = lvalue.node
3933 else:
3934 assert isinstance(lvalue, MemberExpr)
3935 self.expr_checker.accept(lvalue.expr)
3936 inferred = lvalue.def_var
3937 elif isinstance(lvalue, IndexExpr):
3938 index_lvalue = lvalue
3939 elif isinstance(lvalue, MemberExpr):
3940 lvalue_type = self.expr_checker.analyze_ordinary_member_access(lvalue, True)
3941 self.store_type(lvalue, lvalue_type)
3942 elif isinstance(lvalue, NameExpr):
3943 lvalue_type = self.expr_checker.analyze_ref_expr(lvalue, lvalue=True)
3944 self.store_type(lvalue, lvalue_type)
3945 elif isinstance(lvalue, (TupleExpr, ListExpr)):
3946 types = [
3947 self.check_lvalue(sub_expr)[0] or
3948 # This type will be used as a context for further inference of rvalue,
3949 # we put Uninhabited if there is no information available from lvalue.
3950 UninhabitedType()
3951 for sub_expr in lvalue.items
3952 ]
3953 lvalue_type = TupleType(types, self.named_type("builtins.tuple"))
3954 elif isinstance(lvalue, StarExpr):
3955 lvalue_type, _, _ = self.check_lvalue(lvalue.expr)
3956 else:
3957 lvalue_type = self.expr_checker.accept(lvalue)
3958  
3959 return lvalue_type, index_lvalue, inferred

3961 def is_definition(self, s: Lvalue) -> bool:
3962 if isinstance(s, NameExpr):
3963 if s.is_inferred_def:
3964 return True
3965 # If the node type is not defined, this must the first assignment
3966 # that we process => this is a definition, even though the semantic
3967 # analyzer did not recognize this as such. This can arise in code
3968 # that uses isinstance checks, if type checking of the primary
3969 # definition is skipped due to an always False type check.
3970 node = s.node
3971 if isinstance(node, Var):
3972 return node.type is None
3973 elif isinstance(s, MemberExpr):
3974 return s.is_inferred_def
3975 return False
