4877 def visit_decorator(self, e: Decorator) -> None:
4878 for d in e.decorators:
4879 if isinstance(d, RefExpr):
4880 if d.fullname == "typing.no_type_check":
4881 e.var.type = AnyType(TypeOfAny.special_form)
4882 e.var.is_ready = True
4883 return
4884 self.visit_decorator_inner(e)
4885  
4886 def visit_decorator_inner(self, e: Decorator, allow_empty: bool = False) -> None:
4887 if self.recurse_into_functions:
4888 with self.tscope.function_scope(e.func):
4889 self.check_func_item(e.func, name=e.func.name, allow_empty=allow_empty)
4890  
4891 # Process decorators from the inside out to determine decorated signature, which
4892 # may be different from the declared signature.
4893 sig: Type = self.function_type(e.func)
4894 for d in reversed(e.decorators):
4895 if refers_to_fullname(d, OVERLOAD_NAMES):
4896 if not allow_empty:
4897 self.fail(message_registry.MULTIPLE_OVERLOADS_REQUIRED, e)
4898 continue
4899 dec = self.expr_checker.accept(d)
4900 temp = self.temp_node(sig, context=e)
4901 fullname = None
4902 if isinstance(d, RefExpr):
4903 fullname = d.fullname or None
4904 # if this is a expression like @b.a where b is an object, get the type of b
4905 # so we can pass it the method hook in the plugins
4906 object_type: Type | None = None
4907 if fullname is None and isinstance(d, MemberExpr) and self.has_type(d.expr):
4908 object_type = self.lookup_type(d.expr)
4909 fullname = self.expr_checker.method_fullname(object_type, d.name)
4910 self.check_for_untyped_decorator(e.func, dec, d)
4911 sig, t2 = self.expr_checker.check_call(
4912 dec, [temp], [nodes.ARG_POS], e, callable_name=fullname, object_type=object_type
4913 )
4914 self.check_untyped_after_decorator(sig, e.func)
4915 sig = set_callable_name(sig, e.func)
4916 e.var.type = sig
4917 e.var.is_ready = True
4918 if e.func.is_property:
4919 if isinstance(sig, CallableType):
4920 if len([k for k in sig.arg_kinds if k.is_required()]) > 1:
4921 self.msg.fail("Too many arguments for property", e)
4922 self.check_incompatible_property_override(e)
4923 # For overloaded functions we already checked override for overload as a whole.
4924 if allow_empty:
4925 return
4926 if e.func.info and not e.func.is_dynamic() and not e.is_overload:
4927 found_method_base_classes = self.check_method_override(e)
4928 if (
4929 e.func.is_explicit_override
4930 and not found_method_base_classes
4931 and found_method_base_classes is not None
4932 ):
4933 self.msg.no_overridable_method(e.func.name, e.func)
4934 self.check_explicit_override_decorator(e.func, found_method_base_classes)
4935  
4936 if e.func.info and e.func.name in ("__init__", "__new__"):
4937 if e.type and not isinstance(get_proper_type(e.type), (FunctionLike, AnyType)):
4938 self.fail(message_registry.BAD_CONSTRUCTOR_TYPE, e)
4939  
4940 def check_for_untyped_decorator(
4941 self, func: FuncDef, dec_type: Type, dec_expr: Expression
4942 ) -> None:
4943 if (
4944 self.options.disallow_untyped_decorators
4945 and is_typed_callable(func.type)
4946 and is_untyped_decorator(dec_type)
4947 ):
4948 self.msg.typed_function_untyped_decorator(func.name, dec_expr)
4949  
4950 def check_incompatible_property_override(self, e: Decorator) -> None:
4951 if not e.var.is_settable_property and e.func.info:
4952 name = e.func.name
4953 for base in e.func.info.mro[1:]:
4954 base_attr = base.names.get(name)
4955 if not base_attr:
4956 continue
4957 if (
4958 isinstance(base_attr.node, OverloadedFuncDef)
4959 and base_attr.node.is_property
4960 and cast(Decorator, base_attr.node.items[0]).var.is_settable_property
4961 ):
4962 self.fail(message_registry.READ_ONLY_PROPERTY_OVERRIDES_READ_WRITE, e)
4963  
4964 def visit_with_stmt(self, s: WithStmt) -> None:
4965 exceptions_maybe_suppressed = False
4966 for expr, target in zip(s.expr, s.target):
4967 if s.is_async:
4968 exit_ret_type = self.check_async_with_item(expr, target, s.unanalyzed_type is None)
4969 else:
4970 exit_ret_type = self.check_with_item(expr, target, s.unanalyzed_type is None)
4971  
4972 # Based on the return type, determine if this context manager 'swallows'
4973 # exceptions or not. We determine this using a heuristic based on the
4974 # return type of the __exit__ method -- see the discussion in
4975 # https://github.com/python/mypy/issues/7214 and the section about context managers
4976 # in https://github.com/python/typeshed/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#conventions
4977 # for more details.
4978  
4979 exit_ret_type = get_proper_type(exit_ret_type)
4980 if is_literal_type(exit_ret_type, "builtins.bool", False):
4981 continue
4982  
4983 if is_literal_type(exit_ret_type, "builtins.bool", True) or (
4984 isinstance(exit_ret_type, Instance)
4985 and exit_ret_type.type.fullname == "builtins.bool"
4986 and state.strict_optional
4987 ):
4988 # Note: if strict-optional is disabled, this bool instance
4989 # could actually be an Optional[bool].
4990 exceptions_maybe_suppressed = True
4991  
4992 if exceptions_maybe_suppressed:
4993 # Treat this 'with' block in the same way we'd treat a 'try: BODY; except: pass'
4994 # block. This means control flow can continue after the 'with' even if the 'with'
4995 # block immediately returns.
4996 with self.binder.frame_context(can_skip=True, try_frame=True):
4997 self.accept(s.body)
4998 else:
4999 self.accept(s.body)
5000  
5001 def check_untyped_after_decorator(self, typ: Type, func: FuncDef) -> None:
5002 if not self.options.disallow_any_decorated or self.is_stub:
5003 return
5004  
5005 if mypy.checkexpr.has_any_type(typ):
5006 self.msg.untyped_decorated_function(typ, func)
5007  
5008 def check_async_with_item(
5009 self, expr: Expression, target: Expression | None, infer_lvalue_type: bool
5010 ) -> Type:
5011 echk = self.expr_checker
5012 ctx = echk.accept(expr)
5013 obj = echk.check_method_call_by_name("__aenter__", ctx, [], [], expr)[0]
5014 obj = echk.check_awaitable_expr(
5015 obj, expr, message_registry.INCOMPATIBLE_TYPES_IN_ASYNC_WITH_AENTER
5016 )
5017 if target:
5018 self.check_assignment(target, self.temp_node(obj, expr), infer_lvalue_type)
5019 arg = self.temp_node(AnyType(TypeOfAny.special_form), expr)
5020 res, _ = echk.check_method_call_by_name(
5021 "__aexit__", ctx, [arg] * 3, [nodes.ARG_POS] * 3, expr
5022 )
5023 return echk.check_awaitable_expr(
5024 res, expr, message_registry.INCOMPATIBLE_TYPES_IN_ASYNC_WITH_AEXIT
5025 )
5026  
5027 def check_with_item(
5028 self, expr: Expression, target: Expression | None, infer_lvalue_type: bool
5029 ) -> Type:
5030 echk = self.expr_checker
5031 ctx = echk.accept(expr)
5032 obj = echk.check_method_call_by_name("__enter__", ctx, [], [], expr)[0]
5033 if target:
5034 self.check_assignment(target, self.temp_node(obj, expr), infer_lvalue_type)
5035 arg = self.temp_node(AnyType(TypeOfAny.special_form), expr)
5036 res, _ = echk.check_method_call_by_name(
5037 "__exit__", ctx, [arg] * 3, [nodes.ARG_POS] * 3, expr
5038 )
5039 return res
5040  
5041 def visit_break_stmt(self, s: BreakStmt) -> None:
5042 self.binder.handle_break()
5043  
5044 def visit_continue_stmt(self, s: ContinueStmt) -> None:
5045 self.binder.handle_continue()
5046 return None
5047  
5048 def visit_match_stmt(self, s: MatchStmt) -> None:
5049 with self.binder.frame_context(can_skip=False, fall_through=0):
5050 subject_type = get_proper_type(self.expr_checker.accept(s.subject))
5051  
5052 if isinstance(subject_type, DeletedType):
5053 self.msg.deleted_as_rvalue(subject_type, s)
5054  
5055 # We infer types of patterns twice. The first pass is used
5056 # to infer the types of capture variables. The type of a
5057 # capture variable may depend on multiple patterns (it
5058 # will be a union of all capture types). This pass ignores
5059 # guard expressions.
5060 pattern_types = [self.pattern_checker.accept(p, subject_type) for p in s.patterns]
5061 type_maps: list[TypeMap] = [t.captures for t in pattern_types]
5062 inferred_types = self.infer_variable_types_from_type_maps(type_maps)
5063  
5064 # The second pass narrows down the types and type checks bodies.
5065 for p, g, b in zip(s.patterns, s.guards, s.bodies):
5066 current_subject_type = self.expr_checker.narrow_type_from_binder(
5067 s.subject, subject_type
5068 )
5069 pattern_type = self.pattern_checker.accept(p, current_subject_type)
5070 with self.binder.frame_context(can_skip=True, fall_through=2):
5071 if b.is_unreachable or isinstance(
5072 get_proper_type(pattern_type.type), UninhabitedType
5073 ):
5074 self.push_type_map(None)
5075 else_map: TypeMap = {}
5076 else:
5077 pattern_map, else_map = conditional_types_to_typemaps(
5078 s.subject, pattern_type.type, pattern_type.rest_type
5079 )
5080 self.remove_capture_conflicts(pattern_type.captures, inferred_types)
5081 self.push_type_map(pattern_map)
5082 self.push_type_map(pattern_type.captures)
5083 if g is not None:
5084 with self.binder.frame_context(can_skip=False, fall_through=3):
5085 gt = get_proper_type(self.expr_checker.accept(g))
5086  
5087 if isinstance(gt, DeletedType):
5088 self.msg.deleted_as_rvalue(gt, s)
5089  
5090 guard_map, guard_else_map = self.find_isinstance_check(g)
5091 else_map = or_conditional_maps(else_map, guard_else_map)
5092  
5093 # If the guard narrowed the subject, copy the narrowed types over
5094 if isinstance(p, AsPattern):
5095 case_target = p.pattern or p.name
5096 if isinstance(case_target, NameExpr):
5097 for type_map in (guard_map, else_map):
5098 if not type_map:
5099 continue
5100 for expr in list(type_map):
5101 if not (
5102 isinstance(expr, NameExpr)
5103 and expr.fullname == case_target.fullname
5104 ):
5105 continue
5106 type_map[s.subject] = type_map[expr]
5107  
5108 self.push_type_map(guard_map)
5109 self.accept(b)
5110 else:
5111 self.accept(b)
5112 self.push_type_map(else_map)
5113  
5114 # This is needed due to a quirk in frame_context. Without it types will stay narrowed
5115 # after the match.
5116 with self.binder.frame_context(can_skip=False, fall_through=2):
5117 pass
5118  
5119 def infer_variable_types_from_type_maps(self, type_maps: list[TypeMap]) -> dict[Var, Type]:
5120 all_captures: dict[Var, list[tuple[NameExpr, Type]]] = defaultdict(list)
5121 for tm in type_maps:
5122 if tm is not None:
5123 for expr, typ in tm.items():
5124 if isinstance(expr, NameExpr):
5125 node = expr.node
5126 assert isinstance(node, Var)
5127 all_captures[node].append((expr, typ))
5128  
5129 inferred_types: dict[Var, Type] = {}
5130 for var, captures in all_captures.items():
5131 already_exists = False
5132 types: list[Type] = []
5133 for expr, typ in captures:
5134 types.append(typ)
5135  
5136 previous_type, _, _ = self.check_lvalue(expr)
5137 if previous_type is not None:
5138 already_exists = True
5139 if self.check_subtype(
5140 typ,
5141 previous_type,
5142 expr,
5143 msg=message_registry.INCOMPATIBLE_TYPES_IN_CAPTURE,
5144 subtype_label="pattern captures type",
5145 supertype_label="variable has type",
5146 ):
5147 inferred_types[var] = previous_type
5148  
5149 if not already_exists:
5150 new_type = UnionType.make_union(types)
5151 # Infer the union type at the first occurrence
5152 first_occurrence, _ = captures[0]
5153 inferred_types[var] = new_type
5154 self.infer_variable_type(var, first_occurrence, new_type, first_occurrence)
5155 return inferred_types
5156  
5157 def remove_capture_conflicts(self, type_map: TypeMap, inferred_types: dict[Var, Type]) -> None:
5158 if type_map:
5159 for expr, typ in list(type_map.items()):
5160 if isinstance(expr, NameExpr):
5161 node = expr.node
5162 assert isinstance(node, Var)
5163 if node not in inferred_types or not is_subtype(typ, inferred_types[node]):
5164 del type_map[expr]
5165  
5166 def make_fake_typeinfo(
5167 self,
5168 curr_module_fullname: str,
5169 class_gen_name: str,
5170 class_short_name: str,
5171 bases: list[Instance],
5172 ) -> tuple[ClassDef, TypeInfo]:
5173 # Build the fake ClassDef and TypeInfo together.
5174 # The ClassDef is full of lies and doesn't actually contain a body.
5175 # Use format_bare to generate a nice name for error messages.
5176 # We skip fully filling out a handful of TypeInfo fields because they
5177 # should be irrelevant for a generated type like this:
5178 # is_protocol, protocol_members, is_abstract
5179 cdef = ClassDef(class_short_name, Block([]))
5180 cdef.fullname = curr_module_fullname + "." + class_gen_name
5181 info = TypeInfo(SymbolTable(), cdef, curr_module_fullname)
5182 cdef.info = info
5183 info.bases = bases
5184 calculate_mro(info)
5185 info.metaclass_type = info.calculate_metaclass_type()
5186 return cdef, info
5187  
5188 def intersect_instances(
5189 self, instances: tuple[Instance, Instance], errors: list[tuple[str, str]]
5190 ) -> Instance | None:
5191 """Try creating an ad-hoc intersection of the given instances.
5192  
5193 Note that this function does *not* try and create a full-fledged
5194 intersection type. Instead, it returns an instance of a new ad-hoc
5195 subclass of the given instances.
5196  
5197 This is mainly useful when you need a way of representing some
5198 theoretical subclass of the instances the user may be trying to use
5199 the generated intersection can serve as a placeholder.
5200  
5201 This function will create a fresh subclass every time you call it,
5202 even if you pass in the exact same arguments. So this means calling
5203 `self.intersect_intersection([inst_1, inst_2], ctx)` twice will result
5204 in instances of two distinct subclasses of inst_1 and inst_2.
5205  
5206 This is by design: we want each ad-hoc intersection to be unique since
5207 they're supposed represent some other unknown subclass.
5208  
5209 Returns None if creating the subclass is impossible (e.g. due to
5210 MRO errors or incompatible signatures). If we do successfully create
5211 a subclass, its TypeInfo will automatically be added to the global scope.
5212 """
5213 curr_module = self.scope.stack[0]
5214 assert isinstance(curr_module, MypyFile)
5215  
5216 # First, retry narrowing while allowing promotions (they are disabled by default
5217 # for isinstance() checks, etc). This way we will still type-check branches like
5218 # x: complex = 1
5219 # if isinstance(x, int):
5220 # ...
5221 left, right = instances
5222 if is_proper_subtype(left, right, ignore_promotions=False):
5223 return left
5224 if is_proper_subtype(right, left, ignore_promotions=False):
5225 return right
5226  
5227 def _get_base_classes(instances_: tuple[Instance, Instance]) -> list[Instance]:
5228 base_classes_ = []
5229 for inst in instances_:
5230 if inst.type.is_intersection:
5231 expanded = inst.type.bases
5232 else:
5233 expanded = [inst]
5234  
5235 for expanded_inst in expanded:
5236 base_classes_.append(expanded_inst)
5237 return base_classes_
5238  
5239 def _make_fake_typeinfo_and_full_name(
5240 base_classes_: list[Instance], curr_module_: MypyFile
5241 ) -> tuple[TypeInfo, str]:
5242 names_list = pretty_seq([x.type.name for x in base_classes_], "and")
5243 short_name = f"<subclass of {names_list}>"
5244 full_name_ = gen_unique_name(short_name, curr_module_.names)
5245 cdef, info_ = self.make_fake_typeinfo(
5246 curr_module_.fullname, full_name_, short_name, base_classes_
5247 )
5248 return info_, full_name_
5249  
5250 base_classes = _get_base_classes(instances)
5251 # We use the pretty_names_list for error messages but can't
5252 # use it for the real name that goes into the symbol table
5253 # because it can have dots in it.
5254 pretty_names_list = pretty_seq(
5255 format_type_distinctly(*base_classes, options=self.options, bare=True), "and"
5256 )
5257  
5258 new_errors = []
5259 for base in base_classes:
5260 if base.type.is_final:
5261 new_errors.append((pretty_names_list, f'"{base.type.name}" is final'))
5262 if new_errors:
5263 errors.extend(new_errors)
5264 return None
5265  
5266 try:
5267 info, full_name = _make_fake_typeinfo_and_full_name(base_classes, curr_module)
5268 with self.msg.filter_errors() as local_errors:
5269 self.check_multiple_inheritance(info)
5270 if local_errors.has_new_errors():
5271 # "class A(B, C)" unsafe, now check "class A(C, B)":
5272 base_classes = _get_base_classes(instances[::-1])
5273 info, full_name = _make_fake_typeinfo_and_full_name(base_classes, curr_module)
5274 with self.msg.filter_errors() as local_errors:
5275 self.check_multiple_inheritance(info)
5276 info.is_intersection = True
5277 except MroError:
5278 errors.append((pretty_names_list, "would have inconsistent method resolution order"))
5279 return None
5280 if local_errors.has_new_errors():
5281 errors.append((pretty_names_list, "would have incompatible method signatures"))
5282 return None
5283  
5284 curr_module.names[full_name] = SymbolTableNode(GDEF, info)
5285 return Instance(info, [], extra_attrs=instances[0].extra_attrs or instances[1].extra_attrs)
5286  
5287 def intersect_instance_callable(self, typ: Instance, callable_type: CallableType) -> Instance:
5288 """Creates a fake type that represents the intersection of an Instance and a CallableType.
5289  
5290 It operates by creating a bare-minimum dummy TypeInfo that
5291 subclasses type and adds a __call__ method matching callable_type.
5292 """
5293  
5294 # In order for this to work in incremental mode, the type we generate needs to
5295 # have a valid fullname and a corresponding entry in a symbol table. We generate
5296 # a unique name inside the symbol table of the current module.
5297 cur_module = self.scope.stack[0]
5298 assert isinstance(cur_module, MypyFile)
5299 gen_name = gen_unique_name(f"<callable subtype of {typ.type.name}>", cur_module.names)
5300  
5301 # Synthesize a fake TypeInfo
5302 short_name = format_type_bare(typ, self.options)
5303 cdef, info = self.make_fake_typeinfo(cur_module.fullname, gen_name, short_name, [typ])
5304  
5305 # Build up a fake FuncDef so we can populate the symbol table.
5306 func_def = FuncDef("__call__", [], Block([]), callable_type)
5307 func_def._fullname = cdef.fullname + ".__call__"
5308 func_def.info = info
5309 info.names["__call__"] = SymbolTableNode(MDEF, func_def)
5310  
5311 cur_module.names[gen_name] = SymbolTableNode(GDEF, info)
5312  
5313 return Instance(info, [], extra_attrs=typ.extra_attrs)
5314  
5315 def make_fake_callable(self, typ: Instance) -> Instance:
5316 """Produce a new type that makes type Callable with a generic callable type."""
5317  
5318 fallback = self.named_type("builtins.function")
5319 callable_type = CallableType(
5320 [AnyType(TypeOfAny.explicit), AnyType(TypeOfAny.explicit)],
5321 [nodes.ARG_STAR, nodes.ARG_STAR2],
5322 [None, None],
5323 ret_type=AnyType(TypeOfAny.explicit),
5324 fallback=fallback,
5325 is_ellipsis_args=True,
5326 )
5327  
5328 return self.intersect_instance_callable(typ, callable_type)
5329  
5330 def partition_by_callable(
5331 self, typ: Type, unsound_partition: bool
5332 ) -> tuple[list[Type], list[Type]]:
5333 """Partitions a type into callable subtypes and uncallable subtypes.
5334  
5335 Thus, given:
5336 `callables, uncallables = partition_by_callable(type)`
5337  
5338 If we assert `callable(type)` then `type` has type Union[*callables], and
5339 If we assert `not callable(type)` then `type` has type Union[*uncallables]
5340  
5341 If unsound_partition is set, assume that anything that is not
5342 clearly callable is in fact not callable. Otherwise we generate a
5343 new subtype that *is* callable.
5344  
5345 Guaranteed to not return [], [].
5346 """
5347 typ = get_proper_type(typ)
5348  
5349 if isinstance(typ, (FunctionLike, TypeType)):
5350 return [typ], []
5351  
5352 if isinstance(typ, AnyType):
5353 return [typ], [typ]
5354  
5355 if isinstance(typ, NoneType):
5356 return [], [typ]
5357  
5358 if isinstance(typ, UnionType):
5359 callables = []
5360 uncallables = []
5361 for subtype in typ.items:
5362 # Use unsound_partition when handling unions in order to
5363 # allow the expected type discrimination.
5364 subcallables, subuncallables = self.partition_by_callable(
5365 subtype, unsound_partition=True
5366 )
5367 callables.extend(subcallables)
5368 uncallables.extend(subuncallables)
5369 return callables, uncallables
5370  
5371 if isinstance(typ, TypeVarType):
5372 # We could do better probably?
5373 # Refine the the type variable's bound as our type in the case that
5374 # callable() is true. This unfortunately loses the information that
5375 # the type is a type variable in that branch.
5376 # This matches what is done for isinstance, but it may be possible to
5377 # do better.
5378 # If it is possible for the false branch to execute, return the original
5379 # type to avoid losing type information.
5380 callables, uncallables = self.partition_by_callable(
5381 erase_to_union_or_bound(typ), unsound_partition
5382 )
5383 uncallables = [typ] if uncallables else []
5384 return callables, uncallables
5385  
5386 # A TupleType is callable if its fallback is, but needs special handling
5387 # when we dummy up a new type.
5388 ityp = typ
5389 if isinstance(typ, TupleType):
5390 ityp = tuple_fallback(typ)
5391  
5392 if isinstance(ityp, Instance):
5393 method = ityp.type.get_method("__call__")
5394 if method and method.type:
5395 callables, uncallables = self.partition_by_callable(
5396 method.type, unsound_partition=False
5397 )
5398 if callables and not uncallables:
5399 # Only consider the type callable if its __call__ method is
5400 # definitely callable.
5401 return [typ], []
5402  
5403 if not unsound_partition:
5404 fake = self.make_fake_callable(ityp)
5405 if isinstance(typ, TupleType):
5406 fake.type.tuple_type = TupleType(typ.items, fake)
5407 return [fake.type.tuple_type], [typ]
5408 return [fake], [typ]
5409  
5410 if unsound_partition:
5411 return [], [typ]
5412 else:
5413 # We don't know how properly make the type callable.
5414 return [typ], [typ]
5415  
5416 def conditional_callable_type_map(
5417 self, expr: Expression, current_type: Type | None
5418 ) -> tuple[TypeMap, TypeMap]:
5419 """Takes in an expression and the current type of the expression.
5420  
5421 Returns a 2-tuple: The first element is a map from the expression to
5422 the restricted type if it were callable. The second element is a
5423 map from the expression to the type it would hold if it weren't
5424 callable.
5425 """
5426 if not current_type:
5427 return {}, {}
5428  
5429 if isinstance(get_proper_type(current_type), AnyType):
5430 return {}, {}
5431  
5432 callables, uncallables = self.partition_by_callable(current_type, unsound_partition=False)
5433  
5434 if callables and uncallables:
5435 callable_map = {expr: UnionType.make_union(callables)} if callables else None
5436 uncallable_map = {expr: UnionType.make_union(uncallables)} if uncallables else None
5437 return callable_map, uncallable_map
5438  
5439 elif callables:
5440 return {}, None
5441  
5442 return None, {}
5443  
5444 def conditional_types_for_iterable(
5445 self, item_type: Type, iterable_type: Type
5446 ) -> tuple[Type | None, Type | None]:
5447 """
5448 Narrows the type of `iterable_type` based on the type of `item_type`.
5449 For now, we only support narrowing unions of TypedDicts based on left operand being literal string(s).
5450 """
5451 if_types: list[Type] = []
5452 else_types: list[Type] = []
5453  
5454 iterable_type = get_proper_type(iterable_type)
5455 if isinstance(iterable_type, UnionType):
5456 possible_iterable_types = get_proper_types(iterable_type.relevant_items())
5457 else:
5458 possible_iterable_types = [iterable_type]
5459  
5460 item_str_literals = try_getting_str_literals_from_type(item_type)
5461  
5462 for possible_iterable_type in possible_iterable_types:
5463 if item_str_literals and isinstance(possible_iterable_type, TypedDictType):
5464 for key in item_str_literals:
5465 if key in possible_iterable_type.required_keys:
5466 if_types.append(possible_iterable_type)
5467 elif (
5468 key in possible_iterable_type.items or not possible_iterable_type.is_final
5469 ):
5470 if_types.append(possible_iterable_type)
5471 else_types.append(possible_iterable_type)
5472 else:
5473 else_types.append(possible_iterable_type)
5474 else:
5475 if_types.append(possible_iterable_type)
5476 else_types.append(possible_iterable_type)
5477  
5478 return (
5479 UnionType.make_union(if_types) if if_types else None,
5480 UnionType.make_union(else_types) if else_types else None,
5481 )
5482  
5483 def _is_truthy_type(self, t: ProperType) -> bool:
5484 return (
5485 (
5486 isinstance(t, Instance)
5487 and bool(t.type)
5488 and not t.type.has_readable_member("__bool__")
5489 and not t.type.has_readable_member("__len__")
5490 and t.type.fullname != "builtins.object"
5491 )
5492 or isinstance(t, FunctionLike)
5493 or (
5494 isinstance(t, UnionType)
5495 and all(self._is_truthy_type(t) for t in get_proper_types(t.items))
5496 )
5497 )
5498  
5499 def _check_for_truthy_type(self, t: Type, expr: Expression) -> None:
5500 if not state.strict_optional:
5501 return # if everything can be None, all bets are off
5502  
5503 t = get_proper_type(t)
5504 if not self._is_truthy_type(t):
5505 return
5506  
5507 def format_expr_type() -> str:
5508 typ = format_type(t, self.options)
5509 if isinstance(expr, MemberExpr):
5510 return f'Member "{expr.name}" has type {typ}'
5511 elif isinstance(expr, RefExpr) and expr.fullname:
5512 return f'"{expr.fullname}" has type {typ}'
5513 elif isinstance(expr, CallExpr):
5514 if isinstance(expr.callee, MemberExpr):
5515 return f'"{expr.callee.name}" returns {typ}'
5516 elif isinstance(expr.callee, RefExpr) and expr.callee.fullname:
5517 return f'"{expr.callee.fullname}" returns {typ}'
5518 return f"Call returns {typ}"
5519 else:
5520 return f"Expression has type {typ}"
5521  
5522 def get_expr_name() -> str:
5523 if isinstance(expr, (NameExpr, MemberExpr)):
5524 return f'"{expr.name}"'
5525 else:
5526 # return type if expr has no name
5527 return format_type(t, self.options)
5528  
5529 if isinstance(t, FunctionLike):
5530 self.fail(message_registry.FUNCTION_ALWAYS_TRUE.format(get_expr_name()), expr)
5531 elif isinstance(t, UnionType):
5532 self.fail(message_registry.TYPE_ALWAYS_TRUE_UNIONTYPE.format(format_expr_type()), expr)
5533 elif isinstance(t, Instance) and t.type.fullname == "typing.Iterable":
5534 _, info = self.make_fake_typeinfo("typing", "Collection", "Collection", [])
5535 self.fail(
5536 message_registry.ITERABLE_ALWAYS_TRUE.format(
5537 format_expr_type(), format_type(Instance(info, t.args), self.options)
5538 ),
5539 expr,
5540 )
5541 else:
5542 self.fail(message_registry.TYPE_ALWAYS_TRUE.format(format_expr_type()), expr)
5543  
5544 def find_type_equals_check(
5545 self, node: ComparisonExpr, expr_indices: list[int]
5546 ) -> tuple[TypeMap, TypeMap]:
5547 """Narrow types based on any checks of the type ``type(x) == T``
5548  
5549 Args:
5550 node: The node that might contain the comparison
5551 expr_indices: The list of indices of expressions in ``node`` that are being
5552 compared
5553 """
5554  
5555 def is_type_call(expr: CallExpr) -> bool:
5556 """Is expr a call to type with one argument?"""
5557 return refers_to_fullname(expr.callee, "builtins.type") and len(expr.args) == 1
5558  
5559 # exprs that are being passed into type
5560 exprs_in_type_calls: list[Expression] = []
5561 # type that is being compared to type(expr)
5562 type_being_compared: list[TypeRange] | None = None
5563 # whether the type being compared to is final
5564 is_final = False
5565  
5566 for index in expr_indices:
5567 expr = node.operands[index]
5568  
5569 if isinstance(expr, CallExpr) and is_type_call(expr):
5570 exprs_in_type_calls.append(expr.args[0])
5571 else:
5572 current_type = self.get_isinstance_type(expr)
5573 if current_type is None:
5574 continue
5575 if type_being_compared is not None:
5576 # It doesn't really make sense to have several types being
5577 # compared to the output of type (like type(x) == int == str)
5578 # because whether that's true is solely dependent on what the
5579 # types being compared are, so we don't try to narrow types any
5580 # further because we can't really get any information about the
5581 # type of x from that check
5582 return {}, {}
5583 else:
5584 if isinstance(expr, RefExpr) and isinstance(expr.node, TypeInfo):
5585 is_final = expr.node.is_final
5586 type_being_compared = current_type
5587  
5588 if not exprs_in_type_calls:
5589 return {}, {}
5590  
5591 if_maps: list[TypeMap] = []
5592 else_maps: list[TypeMap] = []
5593 for expr in exprs_in_type_calls:
5594 current_if_type, current_else_type = self.conditional_types_with_intersection(
5595 self.lookup_type(expr), type_being_compared, expr
5596 )
5597 current_if_map, current_else_map = conditional_types_to_typemaps(
5598 expr, current_if_type, current_else_type
5599 )
5600 if_maps.append(current_if_map)
5601 else_maps.append(current_else_map)
5602  
5603 def combine_maps(list_maps: list[TypeMap]) -> TypeMap:
5604 """Combine all typemaps in list_maps into one typemap"""
5605 result_map = {}
5606 for d in list_maps:
5607 if d is not None:
5608 result_map.update(d)
5609 return result_map
5610  
5611 if_map = combine_maps(if_maps)
5612 # type(x) == T is only true when x has the same type as T, meaning
5613 # that it can be false if x is an instance of a subclass of T. That means
5614 # we can't do any narrowing in the else case unless T is final, in which
5615 # case T can't be subclassed
5616 if is_final:
5617 else_map = combine_maps(else_maps)
5618 else:
5619 else_map = {}
5620 return if_map, else_map
5621  
5622 def find_isinstance_check(self, node: Expression) -> tuple[TypeMap, TypeMap]:
5623 """Find any isinstance checks (within a chain of ands). Includes
5624 implicit and explicit checks for None and calls to callable.
5625 Also includes TypeGuard functions.
5626  
5627 Return value is a map of variables to their types if the condition
5628 is true and a map of variables to their types if the condition is false.
5629  
5630 If either of the values in the tuple is None, then that particular
5631 branch can never occur.
5632  
5633 May return {}, {}.
5634 Can return None, None in situations involving NoReturn.
5635 """
5636 if_map, else_map = self.find_isinstance_check_helper(node)
5637 new_if_map = self.propagate_up_typemap_info(if_map)
5638 new_else_map = self.propagate_up_typemap_info(else_map)
5639 return new_if_map, new_else_map
5640  
5641 def find_isinstance_check_helper(self, node: Expression) -> tuple[TypeMap, TypeMap]:
5642 if is_true_literal(node):
5643 return {}, None
5644 if is_false_literal(node):
5645 return None, {}
5646  
5647 if isinstance(node, CallExpr) and len(node.args) != 0:
5648 expr = collapse_walrus(node.args[0])
5649 if refers_to_fullname(node.callee, "builtins.isinstance"):
5650 if len(node.args) != 2: # the error will be reported elsewhere
5651 return {}, {}
5652 if literal(expr) == LITERAL_TYPE:
5653 return conditional_types_to_typemaps(
5654 expr,
5655 *self.conditional_types_with_intersection(
5656 self.lookup_type(expr), self.get_isinstance_type(node.args[1]), expr
5657 ),
5658 )
5659 elif refers_to_fullname(node.callee, "builtins.issubclass"):
5660 if len(node.args) != 2: # the error will be reported elsewhere
5661 return {}, {}
5662 if literal(expr) == LITERAL_TYPE:
5663 return self.infer_issubclass_maps(node, expr)
5664 elif refers_to_fullname(node.callee, "builtins.callable"):
5665 if len(node.args) != 1: # the error will be reported elsewhere
5666 return {}, {}
5667 if literal(expr) == LITERAL_TYPE:
5668 vartype = self.lookup_type(expr)
5669 return self.conditional_callable_type_map(expr, vartype)
5670 elif refers_to_fullname(node.callee, "builtins.hasattr"):
5671 if len(node.args) != 2: # the error will be reported elsewhere
5672 return {}, {}
5673 attr = try_getting_str_literals(node.args[1], self.lookup_type(node.args[1]))
5674 if literal(expr) == LITERAL_TYPE and attr and len(attr) == 1:
5675 return self.hasattr_type_maps(expr, self.lookup_type(expr), attr[0])
5676 elif isinstance(node.callee, RefExpr):
5677 if node.callee.type_guard is not None:
5678 # TODO: Follow *args, **kwargs
5679 if node.arg_kinds[0] != nodes.ARG_POS:
5680 # the first argument might be used as a kwarg
5681 called_type = get_proper_type(self.lookup_type(node.callee))
5682  
5683 # TODO: there are some more cases in check_call() to handle.
5684 if isinstance(called_type, Instance):
5685 call = find_member(
5686 "__call__", called_type, called_type, is_operator=True
5687 )
5688 if call is not None:
5689 called_type = get_proper_type(call)
5690  
5691 # *assuming* the overloaded function is correct, there's a couple cases:
5692 # 1) The first argument has different names, but is pos-only. We don't
5693 # care about this case, the argument must be passed positionally.
5694 # 2) The first argument allows keyword reference, therefore must be the
5695 # same between overloads.
5696 if isinstance(called_type, (CallableType, Overloaded)):
5697 name = called_type.items[0].arg_names[0]
5698 if name in node.arg_names:
5699 idx = node.arg_names.index(name)
5700 # we want the idx-th variable to be narrowed
5701 expr = collapse_walrus(node.args[idx])
5702 else:
5703 self.fail(message_registry.TYPE_GUARD_POS_ARG_REQUIRED, node)
5704 return {}, {}
5705 if literal(expr) == LITERAL_TYPE:
5706 # Note: we wrap the target type, so that we can special case later.
5707 # Namely, for isinstance() we use a normal meet, while TypeGuard is
5708 # considered "always right" (i.e. even if the types are not overlapping).
5709 # Also note that a care must be taken to unwrap this back at read places
5710 # where we use this to narrow down declared type.
5711 return {expr: TypeGuardedType(node.callee.type_guard)}, {}
5712 elif isinstance(node, ComparisonExpr):
5713 # Step 1: Obtain the types of each operand and whether or not we can
5714 # narrow their types. (For example, we shouldn't try narrowing the
5715 # types of literal string or enum expressions).
5716  
5717 operands = [collapse_walrus(x) for x in node.operands]
5718 operand_types = []
5719 narrowable_operand_index_to_hash = {}
5720 for i, expr in enumerate(operands):
5721 if not self.has_type(expr):
5722 return {}, {}
5723 expr_type = self.lookup_type(expr)
5724 operand_types.append(expr_type)
5725  
5726 if (
5727 literal(expr) == LITERAL_TYPE
5728 and not is_literal_none(expr)
5729 and not self.is_literal_enum(expr)
5730 ):
5731 h = literal_hash(expr)
5732 if h is not None:
5733 narrowable_operand_index_to_hash[i] = h
5734  
5735 # Step 2: Group operands chained by either the 'is' or '==' operands
5736 # together. For all other operands, we keep them in groups of size 2.
5737 # So the expression:
5738 #
5739 # x0 == x1 == x2 < x3 < x4 is x5 is x6 is not x7 is not x8
5740 #
5741 # ...is converted into the simplified operator list:
5742 #
5743 # [("==", [0, 1, 2]), ("<", [2, 3]), ("<", [3, 4]),
5744 # ("is", [4, 5, 6]), ("is not", [6, 7]), ("is not", [7, 8])]
5745 #
5746 # We group identity/equality expressions so we can propagate information
5747 # we discover about one operand across the entire chain. We don't bother
5748 # handling 'is not' and '!=' chains in a special way: those are very rare
5749 # in practice.
5750  
5751 simplified_operator_list = group_comparison_operands(
5752 node.pairwise(), narrowable_operand_index_to_hash, {"==", "is"}
5753 )
5754  
5755 # Step 3: Analyze each group and infer more precise type maps for each
5756 # assignable operand, if possible. We combine these type maps together
5757 # in the final step.
5758  
5759 partial_type_maps = []
5760 for operator, expr_indices in simplified_operator_list:
5761 if operator in {"is", "is not", "==", "!="}:
5762 # is_valid_target:
5763 # Controls which types we're allowed to narrow exprs to. Note that
5764 # we cannot use 'is_literal_type_like' in both cases since doing
5765 # 'x = 10000 + 1; x is 10001' is not always True in all Python
5766 # implementations.
5767 #
5768 # coerce_only_in_literal_context:
5769 # If true, coerce types into literal types only if one or more of
5770 # the provided exprs contains an explicit Literal type. This could
5771 # technically be set to any arbitrary value, but it seems being liberal
5772 # with narrowing when using 'is' and conservative when using '==' seems
5773 # to break the least amount of real-world code.
5774 #
5775 # should_narrow_by_identity:
5776 # Set to 'false' only if the user defines custom __eq__ or __ne__ methods
5777 # that could cause identity-based narrowing to produce invalid results.
5778 if operator in {"is", "is not"}:
5779 is_valid_target: Callable[[Type], bool] = is_singleton_type
5780 coerce_only_in_literal_context = False
5781 should_narrow_by_identity = True
5782 else:
5783  
5784 def is_exactly_literal_type(t: Type) -> bool:
5785 return isinstance(get_proper_type(t), LiteralType)
5786  
5787 def has_no_custom_eq_checks(t: Type) -> bool:
5788 return not custom_special_method(
5789 t, "__eq__", check_all=False
5790 ) and not custom_special_method(t, "__ne__", check_all=False)
5791  
5792 is_valid_target = is_exactly_literal_type
5793 coerce_only_in_literal_context = True
5794  
5795 expr_types = [operand_types[i] for i in expr_indices]
5796 should_narrow_by_identity = all(map(has_no_custom_eq_checks, expr_types))
5797  
5798 if_map: TypeMap = {}
5799 else_map: TypeMap = {}
5800 if should_narrow_by_identity:
5801 if_map, else_map = self.refine_identity_comparison_expression(
5802 operands,
5803 operand_types,
5804 expr_indices,
5805 narrowable_operand_index_to_hash.keys(),
5806 is_valid_target,
5807 coerce_only_in_literal_context,
5808 )
5809  
5810 # Strictly speaking, we should also skip this check if the objects in the expr
5811 # chain have custom __eq__ or __ne__ methods. But we (maybe optimistically)
5812 # assume nobody would actually create a custom objects that considers itself
5813 # equal to None.
5814 if if_map == {} and else_map == {}:
5815 if_map, else_map = self.refine_away_none_in_comparison(
5816 operands,
5817 operand_types,
5818 expr_indices,
5819 narrowable_operand_index_to_hash.keys(),
5820 )
5821  
5822 # If we haven't been able to narrow types yet, we might be dealing with a
5823 # explicit type(x) == some_type check
5824 if if_map == {} and else_map == {}:
5825 if_map, else_map = self.find_type_equals_check(node, expr_indices)
5826 elif operator in {"in", "not in"}:
5827 assert len(expr_indices) == 2
5828 left_index, right_index = expr_indices
5829 item_type = operand_types[left_index]
5830 iterable_type = operand_types[right_index]
5831  
5832 if_map, else_map = {}, {}
5833  
5834 if left_index in narrowable_operand_index_to_hash:
5835 # We only try and narrow away 'None' for now
5836 if is_overlapping_none(item_type):
5837 collection_item_type = get_proper_type(
5838 builtin_item_type(iterable_type)
5839 )
5840 if (
5841 collection_item_type is not None
5842 and not is_overlapping_none(collection_item_type)
5843 and not (
5844 isinstance(collection_item_type, Instance)
5845 and collection_item_type.type.fullname == "builtins.object"
5846 )
5847 and is_overlapping_erased_types(item_type, collection_item_type)
5848 ):
5849 if_map[operands[left_index]] = remove_optional(item_type)
5850  
5851 if right_index in narrowable_operand_index_to_hash:
5852 if_type, else_type = self.conditional_types_for_iterable(
5853 item_type, iterable_type
5854 )
5855 expr = operands[right_index]
5856 if if_type is None:
5857 if_map = None
5858 else:
5859 if_map[expr] = if_type
5860 if else_type is None:
5861 else_map = None
5862 else:
5863 else_map[expr] = else_type
5864  
5865 else:
5866 if_map = {}
5867 else_map = {}
5868  
5869 if operator in {"is not", "!=", "not in"}:
5870 if_map, else_map = else_map, if_map
5871  
5872 partial_type_maps.append((if_map, else_map))
5873  
5874 # If we have found non-trivial restrictions from the regular comparisons,
5875 # then return soon. Otherwise try to infer restrictions involving `len(x)`.
5876 # TODO: support regular and len() narrowing in the same chain.
5877 if any(m != ({}, {}) for m in partial_type_maps):
5878 return reduce_conditional_maps(partial_type_maps)
5879 else:
5880 # Use meet for `and` maps to get correct results for chained checks
5881 # like `if 1 < len(x) < 4: ...`
5882 return reduce_conditional_maps(self.find_tuple_len_narrowing(node), use_meet=True)
5883 elif isinstance(node, AssignmentExpr):
5884 if_map = {}
5885 else_map = {}
5886  
5887 if_assignment_map, else_assignment_map = self.find_isinstance_check(node.target)
5888  
5889 if if_assignment_map is not None:
5890 if_map.update(if_assignment_map)
5891 if else_assignment_map is not None:
5892 else_map.update(else_assignment_map)
5893  
5894 if_condition_map, else_condition_map = self.find_isinstance_check(node.value)
5895  
5896 if if_condition_map is not None:
5897 if_map.update(if_condition_map)
5898 if else_condition_map is not None:
5899 else_map.update(else_condition_map)
5900  
5901 return (
5902 (None if if_assignment_map is None or if_condition_map is None else if_map),
5903 (None if else_assignment_map is None or else_condition_map is None else else_map),
5904 )
5905 elif isinstance(node, OpExpr) and node.op == "and":
5906 left_if_vars, left_else_vars = self.find_isinstance_check(node.left)
5907 right_if_vars, right_else_vars = self.find_isinstance_check(node.right)
5908  
5909 # (e1 and e2) is true if both e1 and e2 are true,
5910 # and false if at least one of e1 and e2 is false.
5911 return (
5912 and_conditional_maps(left_if_vars, right_if_vars),
5913 # Note that if left else type is Any, we can't add any additional
5914 # types to it, since the right maps were computed assuming
5915 # the left is True, which may be not the case in the else branch.
5916 or_conditional_maps(left_else_vars, right_else_vars, coalesce_any=True),
5917 )
5918 elif isinstance(node, OpExpr) and node.op == "or":
5919 left_if_vars, left_else_vars = self.find_isinstance_check(node.left)
5920 right_if_vars, right_else_vars = self.find_isinstance_check(node.right)
5921  
5922 # (e1 or e2) is true if at least one of e1 or e2 is true,
5923 # and false if both e1 and e2 are false.
5924 return (
5925 or_conditional_maps(left_if_vars, right_if_vars),
5926 and_conditional_maps(left_else_vars, right_else_vars),
5927 )
5928 elif isinstance(node, UnaryExpr) and node.op == "not":
5929 left, right = self.find_isinstance_check(node.expr)
5930 return right, left
5931 elif (
5932 literal(node) == LITERAL_TYPE
5933 and self.has_type(node)
5934 and self.can_be_narrowed_with_len(self.lookup_type(node))
5935 # Only translate `if x` to `if len(x) > 0` when possible.
5936 and not custom_special_method(self.lookup_type(node), "__bool__")
5937 and self.options.strict_optional
5938 ):
5939 # Combine a `len(x) > 0` check with the default logic below.
5940 yes_type, no_type = self.narrow_with_len(self.lookup_type(node), ">", 0)
5941 if yes_type is not None:
5942 yes_type = true_only(yes_type)
5943 else:
5944 yes_type = UninhabitedType()
5945 if no_type is not None:
5946 no_type = false_only(no_type)
5947 else:
5948 no_type = UninhabitedType()
5949 if_map = {node: yes_type} if not isinstance(yes_type, UninhabitedType) else None
5950 else_map = {node: no_type} if not isinstance(no_type, UninhabitedType) else None
5951 return if_map, else_map
5952  
5953 # Restrict the type of the variable to True-ish/False-ish in the if and else branches
5954 # respectively
5955 original_vartype = self.lookup_type(node)
5956 self._check_for_truthy_type(original_vartype, node)
5957 vartype = try_expanding_sum_type_to_union(original_vartype, "builtins.bool")
5958  
5959 if_type = true_only(vartype)
5960 else_type = false_only(vartype)
5961 if_map = {node: if_type} if not isinstance(if_type, UninhabitedType) else None
5962 else_map = {node: else_type} if not isinstance(else_type, UninhabitedType) else None
5963 return if_map, else_map
5964  
5965 def propagate_up_typemap_info(self, new_types: TypeMap) -> TypeMap:
5966 """Attempts refining parent expressions of any MemberExpr or IndexExprs in new_types.
5967  
5968 Specifically, this function accepts two mappings of expression to original types:
5969 the original mapping (existing_types), and a new mapping (new_types) intended to
5970 update the original.
5971  
5972 This function iterates through new_types and attempts to use the information to try
5973 refining any parent types that happen to be unions.
5974  
5975 For example, suppose there are two types "A = Tuple[int, int]" and "B = Tuple[str, str]".
5976 Next, suppose that 'new_types' specifies the expression 'foo[0]' has a refined type
5977 of 'int' and that 'foo' was previously deduced to be of type Union[A, B].
5978  
5979 Then, this function will observe that since A[0] is an int and B[0] is not, the type of
5980 'foo' can be further refined from Union[A, B] into just B.
5981  
5982 We perform this kind of "parent narrowing" for member lookup expressions and indexing
5983 expressions into tuples, namedtuples, and typeddicts. We repeat this narrowing
5984 recursively if the parent is also a "lookup expression". So for example, if we have
5985 the expression "foo['bar'].baz[0]", we'd potentially end up refining types for the
5986 expressions "foo", "foo['bar']", and "foo['bar'].baz".
5987  
5988 We return the newly refined map. This map is guaranteed to be a superset of 'new_types'.
5989 """
5990 if new_types is None:
5991 return None
5992 output_map = {}
5993 for expr, expr_type in new_types.items():
5994 # The original inferred type should always be present in the output map, of course
5995 output_map[expr] = expr_type
5996  
5997 # Next, try using this information to refine the parent types, if applicable.
5998 new_mapping = self.refine_parent_types(expr, expr_type)
5999 for parent_expr, proposed_parent_type in new_mapping.items():
6000 # We don't try inferring anything if we've already inferred something for
6001 # the parent expression.
6002 # TODO: Consider picking the narrower type instead of always discarding this?
6003 if parent_expr in new_types:
6004 continue
6005 output_map[parent_expr] = proposed_parent_type
6006 return output_map
6007  
6008 def refine_parent_types(self, expr: Expression, expr_type: Type) -> Mapping[Expression, Type]:
6009 """Checks if the given expr is a 'lookup operation' into a union and iteratively refines
6010 the parent types based on the 'expr_type'.
6011  
6012 For example, if 'expr' is an expression like 'a.b.c.d', we'll potentially return refined
6013 types for expressions 'a', 'a.b', and 'a.b.c'.
6014  
6015 For more details about what a 'lookup operation' is and how we use the expr_type to refine
6016 the parent types of lookup_expr, see the docstring in 'propagate_up_typemap_info'.
6017 """
6018 output: dict[Expression, Type] = {}
6019  
6020 # Note: parent_expr and parent_type are progressively refined as we crawl up the
6021 # parent lookup chain.
6022 while True:
6023 # First, check if this expression is one that's attempting to
6024 # "lookup" some key in the parent type. If so, save the parent type
6025 # and create function that will try replaying the same lookup
6026 # operation against arbitrary types.
6027 if isinstance(expr, MemberExpr):
6028 parent_expr = collapse_walrus(expr.expr)
6029 parent_type = self.lookup_type_or_none(parent_expr)
6030 member_name = expr.name
6031  
6032 def replay_lookup(new_parent_type: ProperType) -> Type | None:
6033 with self.msg.filter_errors() as w:
6034 member_type = analyze_member_access(
6035 name=member_name,
6036 typ=new_parent_type,
6037 context=parent_expr,
6038 is_lvalue=False,
6039 is_super=False,
6040 is_operator=False,
6041 msg=self.msg,
6042 original_type=new_parent_type,
6043 chk=self,
6044 in_literal_context=False,
6045 )
6046 if w.has_new_errors():
6047 return None
6048 else:
6049 return member_type
6050  
6051 elif isinstance(expr, IndexExpr):
6052 parent_expr = collapse_walrus(expr.base)
6053 parent_type = self.lookup_type_or_none(parent_expr)
6054  
6055 index_type = self.lookup_type_or_none(expr.index)
6056 if index_type is None:
6057 return output
6058  
6059 str_literals = try_getting_str_literals_from_type(index_type)
6060 if str_literals is not None:
6061 # Refactoring these two indexing replay functions is surprisingly
6062 # tricky -- see https://github.com/python/mypy/pull/7917, which
6063 # was blocked by https://github.com/mypyc/mypyc/issues/586
6064 def replay_lookup(new_parent_type: ProperType) -> Type | None:
6065 if not isinstance(new_parent_type, TypedDictType):
6066 return None
6067 try:
6068 assert str_literals is not None
6069 member_types = [new_parent_type.items[key] for key in str_literals]
6070 except KeyError:
6071 return None
6072 return make_simplified_union(member_types)
6073  
6074 else:
6075 int_literals = try_getting_int_literals_from_type(index_type)
6076 if int_literals is not None:
6077  
6078 def replay_lookup(new_parent_type: ProperType) -> Type | None:
6079 if not isinstance(new_parent_type, TupleType):
6080 return None
6081 try:
6082 assert int_literals is not None
6083 member_types = [new_parent_type.items[key] for key in int_literals]
6084 except IndexError:
6085 return None
6086 return make_simplified_union(member_types)
6087  
6088 else:
6089 return output
6090 else:
6091 return output
6092  
6093 # If we somehow didn't previously derive the parent type, abort completely
6094 # with what we have so far: something went wrong at an earlier stage.
6095 if parent_type is None:
6096 return output
6097  
6098 # We currently only try refining the parent type if it's a Union.
6099 # If not, there's no point in trying to refine any further parents
6100 # since we have no further information we can use to refine the lookup
6101 # chain, so we end early as an optimization.
6102 parent_type = get_proper_type(parent_type)
6103 if not isinstance(parent_type, UnionType):
6104 return output
6105  
6106 # Take each element in the parent union and replay the original lookup procedure
6107 # to figure out which parents are compatible.
6108 new_parent_types = []
6109 for item in flatten_nested_unions(parent_type.items):
6110 member_type = replay_lookup(get_proper_type(item))
6111 if member_type is None:
6112 # We were unable to obtain the member type. So, we give up on refining this
6113 # parent type entirely and abort.
6114 return output
6115  
6116 if is_overlapping_types(member_type, expr_type):
6117 new_parent_types.append(item)
6118  
6119 # If none of the parent types overlap (if we derived an empty union), something
6120 # went wrong. We should never hit this case, but deriving the uninhabited type or
6121 # reporting an error both seem unhelpful. So we abort.
6122 if not new_parent_types:
6123 return output
6124  
6125 expr = parent_expr
6126 expr_type = output[parent_expr] = make_simplified_union(new_parent_types)
6127  
6128 def refine_identity_comparison_expression(
6129 self,
6130 operands: list[Expression],
6131 operand_types: list[Type],
6132 chain_indices: list[int],
6133 narrowable_operand_indices: AbstractSet[int],
6134 is_valid_target: Callable[[ProperType], bool],
6135 coerce_only_in_literal_context: bool,
6136 ) -> tuple[TypeMap, TypeMap]:
6137 """Produce conditional type maps refining expressions by an identity/equality comparison.
6138  
6139 The 'operands' and 'operand_types' lists should be the full list of operands used
6140 in the overall comparison expression. The 'chain_indices' list is the list of indices
6141 actually used within this identity comparison chain.
6142  
6143 So if we have the expression:
6144  
6145 a <= b is c is d <= e
6146  
6147 ...then 'operands' and 'operand_types' would be lists of length 5 and 'chain_indices'
6148 would be the list [1, 2, 3].
6149  
6150 The 'narrowable_operand_indices' parameter is the set of all indices we are allowed
6151 to refine the types of: that is, all operands that will potentially be a part of
6152 the output TypeMaps.
6153  
6154 Although this function could theoretically try setting the types of the operands
6155 in the chains to the meet, doing that causes too many issues in real-world code.
6156 Instead, we use 'is_valid_target' to identify which of the given chain types
6157 we could plausibly use as the refined type for the expressions in the chain.
6158  
6159 Similarly, 'coerce_only_in_literal_context' controls whether we should try coercing
6160 expressions in the chain to a Literal type. Performing this coercion is sometimes
6161 too aggressive of a narrowing, depending on context.
6162 """
6163 should_coerce = True
6164 if coerce_only_in_literal_context:
6165  
6166 def should_coerce_inner(typ: Type) -> bool:
6167 typ = get_proper_type(typ)
6168 return is_literal_type_like(typ) or (
6169 isinstance(typ, Instance) and typ.type.is_enum
6170 )
6171  
6172 should_coerce = any(should_coerce_inner(operand_types[i]) for i in chain_indices)
6173  
6174 target: Type | None = None
6175 possible_target_indices = []
6176 for i in chain_indices:
6177 expr_type = operand_types[i]
6178 if should_coerce:
6179 expr_type = coerce_to_literal(expr_type)
6180 if not is_valid_target(get_proper_type(expr_type)):
6181 continue
6182 if target and not is_same_type(target, expr_type):
6183 # We have multiple disjoint target types. So the 'if' branch
6184 # must be unreachable.
6185 return None, {}
6186 target = expr_type
6187 possible_target_indices.append(i)
6188  
6189 # There's nothing we can currently infer if none of the operands are valid targets,
6190 # so we end early and infer nothing.
6191 if target is None:
6192 return {}, {}
6193  
6194 # If possible, use an unassignable expression as the target.
6195 # We skip refining the type of the target below, so ideally we'd
6196 # want to pick an expression we were going to skip anyways.
6197 singleton_index = -1
6198 for i in possible_target_indices:
6199 if i not in narrowable_operand_indices:
6200 singleton_index = i
6201  
6202 # But if none of the possible singletons are unassignable ones, we give up
6203 # and arbitrarily pick the last item, mostly because other parts of the
6204 # type narrowing logic bias towards picking the rightmost item and it'd be
6205 # nice to stay consistent.
6206 #
6207 # That said, it shouldn't matter which index we pick. For example, suppose we
6208 # have this if statement, where 'x' and 'y' both have singleton types:
6209 #
6210 # if x is y:
6211 # reveal_type(x)
6212 # reveal_type(y)
6213 # else:
6214 # reveal_type(x)
6215 # reveal_type(y)
6216 #
6217 # At this point, 'x' and 'y' *must* have the same singleton type: we would have
6218 # ended early in the first for-loop in this function if they weren't.
6219 #
6220 # So, we should always get the same result in the 'if' case no matter which
6221 # index we pick. And while we do end up getting different results in the 'else'
6222 # case depending on the index (e.g. if we pick 'y', then its type stays the same
6223 # while 'x' is narrowed to '<uninhabited>'), this distinction is also moot: mypy
6224 # currently will just mark the whole branch as unreachable if either operand is
6225 # narrowed to <uninhabited>.
6226 if singleton_index == -1:
6227 singleton_index = possible_target_indices[-1]
6228  
6229 sum_type_name = None
6230 target = get_proper_type(target)
6231 if isinstance(target, LiteralType) and (
6232 target.is_enum_literal() or isinstance(target.value, bool)
6233 ):
6234 sum_type_name = target.fallback.type.fullname
6235  
6236 target_type = [TypeRange(target, is_upper_bound=False)]
6237  
6238 partial_type_maps = []
6239 for i in chain_indices:
6240 # If we try refining a type against itself, conditional_type_map
6241 # will end up assuming that the 'else' branch is unreachable. This is
6242 # typically not what we want: generally the user will intend for the
6243 # target type to be some fixed 'sentinel' value and will want to refine
6244 # the other exprs against this one instead.
6245 if i == singleton_index:
6246 continue
6247  
6248 # Naturally, we can't refine operands which are not permitted to be refined.
6249 if i not in narrowable_operand_indices:
6250 continue
6251  
6252 expr = operands[i]
6253 expr_type = coerce_to_literal(operand_types[i])
6254  
6255 if sum_type_name is not None:
6256 expr_type = try_expanding_sum_type_to_union(expr_type, sum_type_name)
6257  
6258 # We intentionally use 'conditional_types' directly here instead of
6259 # 'self.conditional_types_with_intersection': we only compute ad-hoc
6260 # intersections when working with pure instances.
6261 types = conditional_types(expr_type, target_type)
6262 partial_type_maps.append(conditional_types_to_typemaps(expr, *types))
6263  
6264 return reduce_conditional_maps(partial_type_maps)
6265  
6266 def refine_away_none_in_comparison(
6267 self,
6268 operands: list[Expression],
6269 operand_types: list[Type],
6270 chain_indices: list[int],
6271 narrowable_operand_indices: AbstractSet[int],
6272 ) -> tuple[TypeMap, TypeMap]:
6273 """Produces conditional type maps refining away None in an identity/equality chain.
6274  
6275 For more details about what the different arguments mean, see the
6276 docstring of 'refine_identity_comparison_expression' up above.
6277 """
6278 non_optional_types = []
6279 for i in chain_indices:
6280 typ = operand_types[i]
6281 if not is_overlapping_none(typ):
6282 non_optional_types.append(typ)
6283  
6284 # Make sure we have a mixture of optional and non-optional types.
6285 if len(non_optional_types) == 0 or len(non_optional_types) == len(chain_indices):
6286 return {}, {}
6287  
6288 if_map = {}
6289 for i in narrowable_operand_indices:
6290 expr_type = operand_types[i]
6291 if not is_overlapping_none(expr_type):
6292 continue
6293 if any(is_overlapping_erased_types(expr_type, t) for t in non_optional_types):
6294 if_map[operands[i]] = remove_optional(expr_type)
6295  
6296 return if_map, {}
6297  
6298 def is_len_of_tuple(self, expr: Expression) -> bool:
6299 """Is this expression a `len(x)` call where x is a tuple or union of tuples?"""
6300 if not isinstance(expr, CallExpr):
6301 return False
6302 if not refers_to_fullname(expr.callee, "builtins.len"):
6303 return False
6304 if len(expr.args) != 1:
6305 return False
6306 expr = expr.args[0]
6307 if literal(expr) != LITERAL_TYPE:
6308 return False
6309 if not self.has_type(expr):
6310 return False
6311 return self.can_be_narrowed_with_len(self.lookup_type(expr))
6312  
6313 def can_be_narrowed_with_len(self, typ: Type) -> bool:
6314 """Is this a type that can benefit from length check type restrictions?
6315  
6316 Currently supported types are TupleTypes, Instances of builtins.tuple, and
6317 unions involving such types.
6318 """
6319 if custom_special_method(typ, "__len__"):
6320 # If user overrides builtin behavior, we can't do anything.
6321 return False
6322 p_typ = get_proper_type(typ)
6323 # Note: we are conservative about tuple subclasses, because some code may rely on
6324 # the fact that tuple_type of fallback TypeInfo matches the original TupleType.
6325 if isinstance(p_typ, TupleType):
6326 if any(isinstance(t, UnpackType) for t in p_typ.items):
6327 return p_typ.partial_fallback.type.fullname == "builtins.tuple"
6328 return True
6329 if isinstance(p_typ, Instance):
6330 return p_typ.type.has_base("builtins.tuple")
6331 if isinstance(p_typ, UnionType):
6332 return any(self.can_be_narrowed_with_len(t) for t in p_typ.items)
6333 return False
6334  
6335 def literal_int_expr(self, expr: Expression) -> int | None:
6336 """Is this expression an int literal, or a reference to an int constant?
6337  
6338 If yes, return the corresponding int value, otherwise return None.
6339 """
6340 if not self.has_type(expr):
6341 return None
6342 expr_type = self.lookup_type(expr)
6343 expr_type = coerce_to_literal(expr_type)
6344 proper_type = get_proper_type(expr_type)
6345 if not isinstance(proper_type, LiteralType):
6346 return None
6347 if not isinstance(proper_type.value, int):
6348 return None
6349 return proper_type.value
6350  
6351 def find_tuple_len_narrowing(self, node: ComparisonExpr) -> list[tuple[TypeMap, TypeMap]]:
6352 """Top-level logic to find type restrictions from a length check on tuples.
6353  
6354 We try to detect `if` checks like the following:
6355 x: tuple[int, int] | tuple[int, int, int]
6356 y: tuple[int, int] | tuple[int, int, int]
6357 if len(x) == len(y) == 2:
6358 a, b = x # OK
6359 c, d = y # OK
6360  
6361 z: tuple[int, ...]
6362 if 1 < len(z) < 4:
6363 x = z # OK
6364 and report corresponding type restrictions to the binder.
6365 """
6366 # First step: group consecutive `is` and `==` comparisons together.
6367 # This is essentially a simplified version of group_comparison_operands(),
6368 # tuned to the len()-like checks. Note that we don't propagate indirect
6369 # restrictions like e.g. `len(x) > foo() > 1` yet, since it is tricky.
6370 # TODO: propagate indirect len() comparison restrictions.
6371 chained = []
6372 last_group = set()
6373 for op, left, right in node.pairwise():
6374 if isinstance(left, AssignmentExpr):
6375 left = left.value
6376 if isinstance(right, AssignmentExpr):
6377 right = right.value
6378 if op in ("is", "=="):
6379 last_group.add(left)
6380 last_group.add(right)
6381 else:
6382 if last_group:
6383 chained.append(("==", list(last_group)))
6384 last_group = set()
6385 if op in {"is not", "!=", "<", "<=", ">", ">="}:
6386 chained.append((op, [left, right]))
6387 if last_group:
6388 chained.append(("==", list(last_group)))
6389  
6390 # Second step: infer type restrictions from each group found above.
6391 type_maps = []
6392 for op, items in chained:
6393 # TODO: support unions of literal types as len() comparison targets.
6394 if not any(self.literal_int_expr(it) is not None for it in items):
6395 continue
6396 if not any(self.is_len_of_tuple(it) for it in items):
6397 continue
6398  
6399 # At this step we know there is at least one len(x) and one literal in the group.
6400 if op in ("is", "=="):
6401 literal_values = set()
6402 tuples = []
6403 for it in items:
6404 lit = self.literal_int_expr(it)
6405 if lit is not None:
6406 literal_values.add(lit)
6407 continue
6408 if self.is_len_of_tuple(it):
6409 assert isinstance(it, CallExpr)
6410 tuples.append(it.args[0])
6411 if len(literal_values) > 1:
6412 # More than one different literal value found, like 1 == len(x) == 2,
6413 # so the corresponding branch is unreachable.
6414 return [(None, {})]
6415 size = literal_values.pop()
6416 if size > MAX_PRECISE_TUPLE_SIZE:
6417 # Avoid creating huge tuples from checks like if len(x) == 300.
6418 continue
6419 for tpl in tuples:
6420 yes_type, no_type = self.narrow_with_len(self.lookup_type(tpl), op, size)
6421 yes_map = None if yes_type is None else {tpl: yes_type}
6422 no_map = None if no_type is None else {tpl: no_type}
6423 type_maps.append((yes_map, no_map))
6424 else:
6425 left, right = items
6426 if self.is_len_of_tuple(right):
6427 # Normalize `1 < len(x)` and similar as `len(x) > 1`.
6428 left, right = right, left
6429 op = flip_ops.get(op, op)
6430 r_size = self.literal_int_expr(right)
6431 assert r_size is not None
6432 if r_size > MAX_PRECISE_TUPLE_SIZE:
6433 # Avoid creating huge unions from checks like if len(x) > 300.
6434 continue
6435 assert isinstance(left, CallExpr)
6436 yes_type, no_type = self.narrow_with_len(
6437 self.lookup_type(left.args[0]), op, r_size
6438 )
6439 yes_map = None if yes_type is None else {left.args[0]: yes_type}
6440 no_map = None if no_type is None else {left.args[0]: no_type}
6441 type_maps.append((yes_map, no_map))
6442 return type_maps
6443  
6444 def narrow_with_len(self, typ: Type, op: str, size: int) -> tuple[Type | None, Type | None]:
6445 """Dispatch tuple type narrowing logic depending on the kind of type we got."""
6446 typ = get_proper_type(typ)
6447 if isinstance(typ, TupleType):
6448 return self.refine_tuple_type_with_len(typ, op, size)
6449 elif isinstance(typ, Instance):
6450 return self.refine_instance_type_with_len(typ, op, size)
6451 elif isinstance(typ, UnionType):
6452 yes_types = []
6453 no_types = []
6454 other_types = []
6455 for t in typ.items:
6456 if not self.can_be_narrowed_with_len(t):
6457 other_types.append(t)
6458 continue
6459 yt, nt = self.narrow_with_len(t, op, size)
6460 if yt is not None:
6461 yes_types.append(yt)
6462 if nt is not None:
6463 no_types.append(nt)
6464 yes_types += other_types
6465 no_types += other_types
6466 if yes_types:
6467 yes_type = make_simplified_union(yes_types)
6468 else:
6469 yes_type = None
6470 if no_types:
6471 no_type = make_simplified_union(no_types)
6472 else:
6473 no_type = None
6474 return yes_type, no_type
6475 else:
6476 assert False, "Unsupported type for len narrowing"
6477  
6478 def refine_tuple_type_with_len(
6479 self, typ: TupleType, op: str, size: int
6480 ) -> tuple[Type | None, Type | None]:
6481 """Narrow a TupleType using length restrictions."""
6482 unpack_index = find_unpack_in_list(typ.items)
6483 if unpack_index is None:
6484 # For fixed length tuple situation is trivial, it is either reachable or not,
6485 # depending on the current length, expected length, and the comparison op.
6486 method = int_op_to_method[op]
6487 if method(typ.length(), size):
6488 return typ, None
6489 return None, typ
6490 unpack = typ.items[unpack_index]
6491 assert isinstance(unpack, UnpackType)
6492 unpacked = get_proper_type(unpack.type)
6493 if isinstance(unpacked, TypeVarTupleType):
6494 # For tuples involving TypeVarTuple unpack we can't do much except
6495 # inferring reachability, and recording the restrictions on TypeVarTuple
6496 # for further "manual" use elsewhere.
6497 min_len = typ.length() - 1 + unpacked.min_len
6498 if op in ("==", "is"):
6499 if min_len <= size:
6500 return typ, typ
6501 return None, typ
6502 elif op in ("<", "<="):
6503 if op == "<=":
6504 size += 1
6505 if min_len < size:
6506 prefix = typ.items[:unpack_index]
  • E203 Whitespace before ':'
6507 suffix = typ.items[unpack_index + 1 :]
6508 # TODO: also record max_len to avoid false negatives?
6509 unpack = UnpackType(unpacked.copy_modified(min_len=size - typ.length() + 1))
6510 return typ, typ.copy_modified(items=prefix + [unpack] + suffix)
6511 return None, typ
6512 else:
6513 yes_type, no_type = self.refine_tuple_type_with_len(typ, neg_ops[op], size)
6514 return no_type, yes_type
6515 # Homogeneous variadic item is the case where we are most flexible. Essentially,
6516 # we adjust the variadic item by "eating away" from it to satisfy the restriction.
6517 assert isinstance(unpacked, Instance) and unpacked.type.fullname == "builtins.tuple"
6518 min_len = typ.length() - 1
6519 arg = unpacked.args[0]
6520 prefix = typ.items[:unpack_index]
  • E203 Whitespace before ':'
6521 suffix = typ.items[unpack_index + 1 :]
6522 if op in ("==", "is"):
6523 if min_len <= size:
6524 # TODO: return fixed union + prefixed variadic tuple for no_type?
6525 return typ.copy_modified(items=prefix + [arg] * (size - min_len) + suffix), typ
6526 return None, typ
6527 elif op in ("<", "<="):
6528 if op == "<=":
6529 size += 1
6530 if min_len < size:
6531 # Note: there is some ambiguity w.r.t. to where to put the additional
6532 # items: before or after the unpack. However, such types are equivalent,
6533 # so we always put them before for consistency.
6534 no_type = typ.copy_modified(
6535 items=prefix + [arg] * (size - min_len) + [unpack] + suffix
6536 )
6537 yes_items = []
6538 for n in range(size - min_len):
6539 yes_items.append(typ.copy_modified(items=prefix + [arg] * n + suffix))
6540 return UnionType.make_union(yes_items, typ.line, typ.column), no_type
6541 return None, typ
6542 else:
6543 yes_type, no_type = self.refine_tuple_type_with_len(typ, neg_ops[op], size)
6544 return no_type, yes_type
6545  
6546 def refine_instance_type_with_len(
6547 self, typ: Instance, op: str, size: int
6548 ) -> tuple[Type | None, Type | None]:
6549 """Narrow a homogeneous tuple using length restrictions."""
6550 base = map_instance_to_supertype(typ, self.lookup_typeinfo("builtins.tuple"))
6551 arg = base.args[0]
6552 # Again, we are conservative about subclasses until we gain more confidence.
6553 allow_precise = (
6554 PRECISE_TUPLE_TYPES in self.options.enable_incomplete_feature
6555 ) and typ.type.fullname == "builtins.tuple"
6556 if op in ("==", "is"):
6557 # TODO: return fixed union + prefixed variadic tuple for no_type?
6558 return TupleType(items=[arg] * size, fallback=typ), typ
6559 elif op in ("<", "<="):
6560 if op == "<=":
6561 size += 1
6562 if allow_precise:
6563 unpack = UnpackType(self.named_generic_type("builtins.tuple", [arg]))
6564 no_type: Type | None = TupleType(items=[arg] * size + [unpack], fallback=typ)
6565 else:
6566 no_type = typ
6567 if allow_precise:
6568 items = []
6569 for n in range(size):
6570 items.append(TupleType([arg] * n, fallback=typ))
6571 yes_type: Type | None = UnionType.make_union(items, typ.line, typ.column)
6572 else:
6573 yes_type = typ
6574 return yes_type, no_type
6575 else:
6576 yes_type, no_type = self.refine_instance_type_with_len(typ, neg_ops[op], size)
6577 return no_type, yes_type

6596 ...

6598 @overload
6599 def check_subtype(
6600 self,
6601 subtype: Type,
6602 supertype: Type,
6603 context: Context,
6604 msg: ErrorMessage,
6605 subtype_label: str | None = None,
6606 supertype_label: str | None = None,
6607 *,
6608 notes: list[str] | None = None,
6609 outer_context: Context | None = None,
6610 ) -> bool:
6611 ...
6612  
6613 def check_subtype(
6614 self,
6615 subtype: Type,
6616 supertype: Type,
6617 context: Context,
6618 msg: str | ErrorMessage,
6619 subtype_label: str | None = None,
6620 supertype_label: str | None = None,
6621 *,
6622 notes: list[str] | None = None,
6623 code: ErrorCode | None = None,
6624 outer_context: Context | None = None,
6625 ) -> bool:
6626 """Generate an error if the subtype is not compatible with supertype."""
6627 if is_subtype(subtype, supertype, options=self.options):
6628 return True
6629  
6630 if isinstance(msg, str):
6631 msg = ErrorMessage(msg, code=code)
6632  
6633 if self.msg.prefer_simple_messages():
6634 self.fail(msg, context) # Fast path -- skip all fancy logic
6635 return False
6636  
6637 orig_subtype = subtype
6638 subtype = get_proper_type(subtype)
6639 orig_supertype = supertype
6640 supertype = get_proper_type(supertype)
6641 if self.msg.try_report_long_tuple_assignment_error(
6642 subtype, supertype, context, msg, subtype_label, supertype_label
6643 ):
6644 return False
6645 extra_info: list[str] = []
6646 note_msg = ""
6647 notes = notes or []
6648 if subtype_label is not None or supertype_label is not None:
6649 subtype_str, supertype_str = format_type_distinctly(
6650 orig_subtype, orig_supertype, options=self.options
6651 )
6652 if subtype_label is not None:
6653 extra_info.append(subtype_label + " " + subtype_str)
6654 if supertype_label is not None:
6655 extra_info.append(supertype_label + " " + supertype_str)
6656 note_msg = make_inferred_type_note(
6657 outer_context or context, subtype, supertype, supertype_str
6658 )
6659 if isinstance(subtype, Instance) and isinstance(supertype, Instance):
6660 notes = append_invariance_notes(notes, subtype, supertype)
6661 if extra_info:
6662 msg = msg.with_additional_msg(" (" + ", ".join(extra_info) + ")")
6663  
6664 self.fail(msg, context)
6665 for note in notes:
6666 self.msg.note(note, context, code=msg.code)
6667 if note_msg:
6668 self.note(note_msg, context, code=msg.code)
6669 self.msg.maybe_note_concatenate_pos_args(subtype, supertype, context, code=msg.code)
6670 if (
6671 isinstance(supertype, Instance)
6672 and supertype.type.is_protocol
6673 and isinstance(subtype, (CallableType, Instance, TupleType, TypedDictType))
6674 ):
6675 self.msg.report_protocol_problems(subtype, supertype, context, code=msg.code)
6676 if isinstance(supertype, CallableType) and isinstance(subtype, Instance):
6677 call = find_member("__call__", subtype, subtype, is_operator=True)
6678 if call:
6679 self.msg.note_call(subtype, call, context, code=msg.code)
6680 if isinstance(subtype, (CallableType, Overloaded)) and isinstance(supertype, Instance):
6681 if supertype.type.is_protocol and "__call__" in supertype.type.protocol_members:
6682 call = find_member("__call__", supertype, subtype, is_operator=True)
6683 assert call is not None
6684 if not is_subtype(subtype, call, options=self.options):
6685 self.msg.note_call(supertype, call, context, code=msg.code)
6686 self.check_possible_missing_await(subtype, supertype, context, code=msg.code)
6687 return False
6688  
6689 def get_precise_awaitable_type(self, typ: Type, local_errors: ErrorWatcher) -> Type | None:
6690 """If type implements Awaitable[X] with non-Any X, return X.
6691  
6692 In all other cases return None. This method must be called in context
6693 of local_errors.
6694 """
6695 if isinstance(get_proper_type(typ), PartialType):
6696 # Partial types are special, ignore them here.
6697 return None
6698 try:
6699 aw_type = self.expr_checker.check_awaitable_expr(
6700 typ, Context(), "", ignore_binder=True
6701 )
6702 except KeyError:
6703 # This is a hack to speed up tests by not including Awaitable in all typing stubs.
6704 return None
6705 if local_errors.has_new_errors():
6706 return None
6707 if isinstance(get_proper_type(aw_type), (AnyType, UnboundType)):
6708 return None
6709 return aw_type
6710  
6711 @contextmanager
6712 def checking_await_set(self) -> Iterator[None]:
6713 self.checking_missing_await = True
6714 try:
6715 yield
6716 finally:
6717 self.checking_missing_await = False
6718  
6719 def check_possible_missing_await(
6720 self, subtype: Type, supertype: Type, context: Context, code: ErrorCode | None
6721 ) -> None:
6722 """Check if the given type becomes a subtype when awaited."""
6723 if self.checking_missing_await:
6724 # Avoid infinite recursion.
6725 return
6726 with self.checking_await_set(), self.msg.filter_errors() as local_errors:
6727 aw_type = self.get_precise_awaitable_type(subtype, local_errors)
6728 if aw_type is None:
6729 return
6730 if not self.check_subtype(
6731 aw_type, supertype, context, msg=message_registry.INCOMPATIBLE_TYPES
6732 ):
6733 return
6734 self.msg.possible_missing_await(context, code)

6736 def named_type(self, name: str) -> Instance:
6737 """Return an instance type with given name and implicit Any type args.
6738  
6739 For example, named_type('builtins.object') produces the 'object' type.
6740 """
6741 # Assume that the name refers to a type.
6742 sym = self.lookup_qualified(name)
6743 node = sym.node
6744 if isinstance(node, TypeAlias):
6745 assert isinstance(node.target, Instance) # type: ignore[misc]
6746 node = node.target.type
6747 assert isinstance(node, TypeInfo)
6748 any_type = AnyType(TypeOfAny.from_omitted_generics)
6749 return Instance(node, [any_type] * len(node.defn.type_vars))
6750  
6751 def named_generic_type(self, name: str, args: list[Type]) -> Instance:
6752 """Return an instance with the given name and type arguments.
6753  
6754 Assume that the number of arguments is correct. Assume that
6755 the name refers to a compatible generic type.
6756 """
6757 info = self.lookup_typeinfo(name)
6758 args = [remove_instance_last_known_values(arg) for arg in args]
6759 # TODO: assert len(args) == len(info.defn.type_vars)
6760 return Instance(info, args)
6761  
6762 def lookup_typeinfo(self, fullname: str) -> TypeInfo:
6763 # Assume that the name refers to a class.
6764 sym = self.lookup_qualified(fullname)
6765 node = sym.node
6766 assert isinstance(node, TypeInfo)
6767 return node
6768  
6769 def type_type(self) -> Instance:
6770 """Return instance type 'type'."""
6771 return self.named_type("builtins.type")
6772  
6773 def str_type(self) -> Instance:
6774 """Return instance type 'str'."""
6775 return self.named_type("builtins.str")

6777 def store_type(self, node: Expression, typ: Type) -> None:
6778 """Store the type of a node in the type map."""
6779 self._type_maps[-1][node] = typ
6780  
6781 def has_type(self, node: Expression) -> bool:
6782 return any(node in m for m in reversed(self._type_maps))
6783  
6784 def lookup_type_or_none(self, node: Expression) -> Type | None:
6785 for m in reversed(self._type_maps):
6786 if node in m:
6787 return m[node]
6788 return None
6789  
6790 def lookup_type(self, node: Expression) -> Type:
6791 for m in reversed(self._type_maps):
6792 t = m.get(node)
6793 if t is not None:
6794 return t
6795 raise KeyError(node)
6796  
6797 def store_types(self, d: dict[Expression, Type]) -> None:
6798 self._type_maps[-1].update(d)

6800 @contextmanager
6801 def local_type_map(self) -> Iterator[dict[Expression, Type]]:
6802 """Store inferred types into a temporary type map (returned).
6803  
6804 This can be used to perform type checking "experiments" without
6805 affecting exported types (which are used by mypyc).
6806 """
6807 temp_type_map: dict[Expression, Type] = {}
6808 self._type_maps.append(temp_type_map)
6809 yield temp_type_map
6810 self._type_maps.pop()

6812 def in_checked_function(self) -> bool:
6813 """Should we type-check the current function?
6814  
6815 - Yes if --check-untyped-defs is set.
6816 - Yes outside functions.
6817 - Yes in annotated functions.
6818 - No otherwise.
6819 """
6820 return (
6821 self.options.check_untyped_defs or not self.dynamic_funcs or not self.dynamic_funcs[-1]
6822 )

6824 def lookup(self, name: str) -> SymbolTableNode:
6825 """Look up a definition from the symbol table with the given name."""
6826 if name in self.globals:
6827 return self.globals[name]
6828 else:
6829 b = self.globals.get("__builtins__", None)
6830 if b:
6831 assert isinstance(b.node, MypyFile)
6832 table = b.node.names
6833 if name in table:
6834 return table[name]
6835 raise KeyError(f"Failed lookup: {name}")
6836  
6837 def lookup_qualified(self, name: str) -> SymbolTableNode:
6838 if "." not in name:
6839 return self.lookup(name)
6840 else:
6841 parts = name.split(".")
6842 n = self.modules[parts[0]]
6843 for i in range(1, len(parts) - 1):
6844 sym = n.names.get(parts[i])
6845 assert sym is not None, "Internal error: attempted lookup of unknown name"
6846 assert isinstance(sym.node, MypyFile)
6847 n = sym.node
6848 last = parts[-1]
6849 if last in n.names:
6850 return n.names[last]
6851 elif len(parts) == 2 and parts[0] in ("builtins", "typing"):
6852 fullname = ".".join(parts)
6853 if fullname in SUGGESTED_TEST_FIXTURES:
6854 suggestion = ", e.g. add '[{} fixtures/{}]' to your test".format(
6855 parts[0], SUGGESTED_TEST_FIXTURES[fullname]
6856 )
6857 else:
6858 suggestion = ""
6859 raise KeyError(
6860 "Could not find builtin symbol '{}' (If you are running a "
6861 "test case, use a fixture that "
6862 "defines this symbol{})".format(last, suggestion)
6863 )
6864 else:
6865 msg = "Failed qualified lookup: '{}' (fullname = '{}')."
6866 raise KeyError(msg.format(last, name))
