6868 @contextmanager
6869 def enter_partial_types(
6870 self, *, is_function: bool = False, is_class: bool = False
6871 ) -> Iterator[None]:
6872 """Enter a new scope for collecting partial types.
6873  
6874 Also report errors for (some) variables which still have partial
6875 types, i.e. we couldn't infer a complete type.
6876 """
6877 is_local = (self.partial_types and self.partial_types[-1].is_local) or is_function
6878 self.partial_types.append(PartialTypeScope({}, is_function, is_local))
6879 yield
6880  
6881 # Don't complain about not being able to infer partials if it is
6882 # at the toplevel (with allow_untyped_globals) or if it is in an
6883 # untyped function being checked with check_untyped_defs.
6884 permissive = (self.options.allow_untyped_globals and not is_local) or (
6885 self.options.check_untyped_defs and self.dynamic_funcs and self.dynamic_funcs[-1]
6886 )
6887  
6888 partial_types, _, _ = self.partial_types.pop()
6889 if not self.current_node_deferred:
6890 for var, context in partial_types.items():
6891 # If we require local partial types, there are a few exceptions where
6892 # we fall back to inferring just "None" as the type from a None initializer:
6893 #
6894 # 1. If all happens within a single function this is acceptable, since only
6895 # the topmost function is a separate target in fine-grained incremental mode.
6896 # We primarily want to avoid "splitting" partial types across targets.
6897 #
6898 # 2. A None initializer in the class body if the attribute is defined in a base
6899 # class is fine, since the attribute is already defined and it's currently okay
6900 # to vary the type of an attribute covariantly. The None type will still be
6901 # checked for compatibility with base classes elsewhere. Without this exception
6902 # mypy could require an annotation for an attribute that already has been
6903 # declared in a base class, which would be bad.
6904 allow_none = (
6905 not self.options.local_partial_types
6906 or is_function
6907 or (is_class and self.is_defined_in_base_class(var))
6908 )
6909 if (
6910 allow_none
6911 and isinstance(var.type, PartialType)
6912 and var.type.type is None
6913 and not permissive
6914 ):
6915 var.type = NoneType()
6916 else:
6917 if var not in self.partial_reported and not permissive:
6918 self.msg.need_annotation_for_var(var, context, self.options.python_version)
6919 self.partial_reported.add(var)
6920 if var.type:
6921 fixed = fixup_partial_type(var.type)
6922 var.invalid_partial_type = fixed != var.type
6923 var.type = fixed
6924  
6925 def handle_partial_var_type(
6926 self, typ: PartialType, is_lvalue: bool, node: Var, context: Context
6927 ) -> Type:
6928 """Handle a reference to a partial type through a var.
6929  
6930 (Used by checkexpr and checkmember.)
6931 """
6932 in_scope, is_local, partial_types = self.find_partial_types_in_all_scopes(node)
6933 if typ.type is None and in_scope:
6934 # 'None' partial type. It has a well-defined type. In an lvalue context
6935 # we want to preserve the knowledge of it being a partial type.
6936 if not is_lvalue:
6937 return NoneType()
6938 else:
6939 return typ
6940 else:
6941 if partial_types is not None and not self.current_node_deferred:
6942 if in_scope:
6943 context = partial_types[node]
6944 if is_local or not self.options.allow_untyped_globals:
6945 self.msg.need_annotation_for_var(
6946 node, context, self.options.python_version
6947 )
6948 self.partial_reported.add(node)
6949 else:
6950 # Defer the node -- we might get a better type in the outer scope
6951 self.handle_cannot_determine_type(node.name, context)
6952 return fixup_partial_type(typ)
6953  
6954 def is_defined_in_base_class(self, var: Var) -> bool:
6955 if not var.info:
6956 return False
6957 return var.info.fallback_to_any or any(
6958 base.get(var.name) is not None for base in var.info.mro[1:]
6959 )
6960  
6961 def find_partial_types(self, var: Var) -> dict[Var, Context] | None:
6962 """Look for an active partial type scope containing variable.
6963  
6964 A scope is active if assignments in the current context can refine a partial
6965 type originally defined in the scope. This is affected by the local_partial_types
6966 configuration option.
6967 """
6968 in_scope, _, partial_types = self.find_partial_types_in_all_scopes(var)
6969 if in_scope:
6970 return partial_types
6971 return None
6972  
6973 def find_partial_types_in_all_scopes(
6974 self, var: Var
6975 ) -> tuple[bool, bool, dict[Var, Context] | None]:
6976 """Look for partial type scope containing variable.
6977  
6978 Return tuple (is the scope active, is the scope a local scope, scope).
6979 """
6980 for scope in reversed(self.partial_types):
6981 if var in scope.map:
6982 # All scopes within the outermost function are active. Scopes out of
6983 # the outermost function are inactive to allow local reasoning (important
6984 # for fine-grained incremental mode).
6985 disallow_other_scopes = self.options.local_partial_types
6986  
6987 if isinstance(var.type, PartialType) and var.type.type is not None and var.info:
6988 # This is an ugly hack to make partial generic self attributes behave
6989 # as if --local-partial-types is always on (because it used to be like this).
6990 disallow_other_scopes = True
6991  
6992 scope_active = (
6993 not disallow_other_scopes or scope.is_local == self.partial_types[-1].is_local
6994 )
6995 return scope_active, scope.is_local, scope.map
6996 return False, False, None
6997  
6998 def temp_node(self, t: Type, context: Context | None = None) -> TempNode:
6999 """Create a temporary node with the given, fixed type."""
7000 return TempNode(t, context=context)

7003 self, msg: str | ErrorMessage, context: Context, *, code: ErrorCode | None = None
7004 ) -> None:
7005 """Produce an error message."""
7006 if isinstance(msg, ErrorMessage):
7007 self.msg.fail(msg.value, context, code=msg.code)
7008 return
7009 self.msg.fail(msg, context, code=code)

7012 self,

7025 def iterable_item_type(
7026 self, it: Instance | CallableType | TypeType | Overloaded, context: Context
7027 ) -> Type:
7028 if isinstance(it, Instance):
7029 iterable = map_instance_to_supertype(it, self.lookup_typeinfo("typing.Iterable"))
7030 item_type = iterable.args[0]
7031 if not isinstance(get_proper_type(item_type), AnyType):
7032 # This relies on 'map_instance_to_supertype' returning 'Iterable[Any]'
7033 # in case there is no explicit base class.
7034 return item_type
7035 # Try also structural typing.
7036 return self.analyze_iterable_item_type_without_expression(it, context)[1]

7038 def function_type(self, func: FuncBase) -> FunctionLike:
7039 return function_type(func, self.named_type("builtins.function"))
7040  
7041 def push_type_map(self, type_map: TypeMap) -> None:
7042 if type_map is None:
7043 self.binder.unreachable()
7044 else:
7045 for expr, type in type_map.items():
7046 self.binder.put(expr, type)
7047  
7048 def infer_issubclass_maps(self, node: CallExpr, expr: Expression) -> tuple[TypeMap, TypeMap]:
7049 """Infer type restrictions for an expression in issubclass call."""
7050 vartype = self.lookup_type(expr)
7051 type = self.get_isinstance_type(node.args[1])
7052 if isinstance(vartype, TypeVarType):
7053 vartype = vartype.upper_bound
7054 vartype = get_proper_type(vartype)
7055 if isinstance(vartype, UnionType):
7056 union_list = []
7057 for t in get_proper_types(vartype.items):
7058 if isinstance(t, TypeType):
7059 union_list.append(t.item)
7060 else:
7061 # This is an error that should be reported earlier
7062 # if we reach here, we refuse to do any type inference.
7063 return {}, {}
7064 vartype = UnionType(union_list)
7065 elif isinstance(vartype, TypeType):
7066 vartype = vartype.item
7067 elif isinstance(vartype, Instance) and vartype.type.is_metaclass():
7068 vartype = self.named_type("builtins.object")
7069 else:
7070 # Any other object whose type we don't know precisely
7071 # for example, Any or a custom metaclass.
7072 return {}, {} # unknown type
7073 yes_type, no_type = self.conditional_types_with_intersection(vartype, type, expr)
7074 yes_map, no_map = conditional_types_to_typemaps(expr, yes_type, no_type)
7075 yes_map, no_map = map(convert_to_typetype, (yes_map, no_map))
7076 return yes_map, no_map
7077  
7078 @overload
7079 def conditional_types_with_intersection(
7080 self,
7081 expr_type: Type,
7082 type_ranges: list[TypeRange] | None,
7083 ctx: Context,
7084 default: None = None,
7085 ) -> tuple[Type | None, Type | None]:
7086 ...
7087  
7088 @overload
7089 def conditional_types_with_intersection(
7090 self, expr_type: Type, type_ranges: list[TypeRange] | None, ctx: Context, default: Type
7091 ) -> tuple[Type, Type]:
7092 ...
7093  
7094 def conditional_types_with_intersection(
7095 self,
7096 expr_type: Type,
7097 type_ranges: list[TypeRange] | None,
7098 ctx: Context,
7099 default: Type | None = None,
7100 ) -> tuple[Type | None, Type | None]:
7101 initial_types = conditional_types(expr_type, type_ranges, default)
7102 # For some reason, doing "yes_map, no_map = conditional_types_to_typemaps(...)"
7103 # doesn't work: mypyc will decide that 'yes_map' is of type None if we try.
7104 yes_type: Type | None = initial_types[0]
7105 no_type: Type | None = initial_types[1]
7106  
7107 if not isinstance(get_proper_type(yes_type), UninhabitedType) or type_ranges is None:
7108 return yes_type, no_type
7109  
7110 # If conditional_types was unable to successfully narrow the expr_type
7111 # using the type_ranges and concluded if-branch is unreachable, we try
7112 # computing it again using a different algorithm that tries to generate
7113 # an ad-hoc intersection between the expr_type and the type_ranges.
7114 proper_type = get_proper_type(expr_type)
7115 if isinstance(proper_type, UnionType):
7116 possible_expr_types = get_proper_types(proper_type.relevant_items())
7117 else:
7118 possible_expr_types = [proper_type]
7119  
7120 possible_target_types = []
7121 for tr in type_ranges:
7122 item = get_proper_type(tr.item)
7123 if not isinstance(item, Instance) or tr.is_upper_bound:
7124 return yes_type, no_type
7125 possible_target_types.append(item)
7126  
7127 out = []
7128 errors: list[tuple[str, str]] = []
7129 for v in possible_expr_types:
7130 if not isinstance(v, Instance):
7131 return yes_type, no_type
7132 for t in possible_target_types:
7133 intersection = self.intersect_instances((v, t), errors)
7134 if intersection is None:
7135 continue
7136 out.append(intersection)
7137 if not out:
7138 # Only report errors if no element in the union worked.
7139 if self.should_report_unreachable_issues():
7140 for types, reason in errors:
7141 self.msg.impossible_intersection(types, reason, ctx)
7142 return UninhabitedType(), expr_type
7143 new_yes_type = make_simplified_union(out)
7144 return new_yes_type, expr_type
7145  
7146 def is_writable_attribute(self, node: Node) -> bool:
7147 """Check if an attribute is writable"""
7148 if isinstance(node, Var):
7149 if node.is_property and not node.is_settable_property:
7150 return False
7151 return True
7152 elif isinstance(node, OverloadedFuncDef) and node.is_property:
7153 first_item = node.items[0]
7154 assert isinstance(first_item, Decorator)
7155 return first_item.var.is_settable_property
7156 return False
7157  
7158 def get_isinstance_type(self, expr: Expression) -> list[TypeRange] | None:
7159 if isinstance(expr, OpExpr) and expr.op == "|":
7160 left = self.get_isinstance_type(expr.left)
7161 right = self.get_isinstance_type(expr.right)
7162 if left is None or right is None:
7163 return None
7164 return left + right
7165 all_types = get_proper_types(flatten_types(self.lookup_type(expr)))
7166 types: list[TypeRange] = []
7167 for typ in all_types:
7168 if isinstance(typ, FunctionLike) and typ.is_type_obj():
7169 # Type variables may be present -- erase them, which is the best
7170 # we can do (outside disallowing them here).
7171 erased_type = erase_typevars(typ.items[0].ret_type)
7172 types.append(TypeRange(erased_type, is_upper_bound=False))
7173 elif isinstance(typ, TypeType):
7174 # Type[A] means "any type that is a subtype of A" rather than "precisely type A"
7175 # we indicate this by setting is_upper_bound flag
7176 types.append(TypeRange(typ.item, is_upper_bound=True))
7177 elif isinstance(typ, Instance) and typ.type.fullname == "builtins.type":
7178 object_type = Instance(typ.type.mro[-1], [])
7179 types.append(TypeRange(object_type, is_upper_bound=True))
7180 elif isinstance(typ, AnyType):
7181 types.append(TypeRange(typ, is_upper_bound=False))
7182 else: # we didn't see an actual type, but rather a variable with unknown value
7183 return None
7184 if not types:
7185 # this can happen if someone has empty tuple as 2nd argument to isinstance
7186 # strictly speaking, we should return UninhabitedType but for simplicity we will simply
7187 # refuse to do any type inference for now
7188 return None
7189 return types
7190  
7191 def is_literal_enum(self, n: Expression) -> bool:
7192 """Returns true if this expression (with the given type context) is an Enum literal.
7193  
7194 For example, if we had an enum:
7195  
7196 class Foo(Enum):
7197 A = 1
7198 B = 2
7199  
7200 ...and if the expression 'Foo' referred to that enum within the current type context,
7201 then the expression 'Foo.A' would be a literal enum. However, if we did 'a = Foo.A',
7202 then the variable 'a' would *not* be a literal enum.
7203  
7204 We occasionally special-case expressions like 'Foo.A' and treat them as a single primitive
7205 unit for the same reasons we sometimes treat 'True', 'False', or 'None' as a single
7206 primitive unit.
7207 """
7208 if not isinstance(n, MemberExpr) or not isinstance(n.expr, NameExpr):
7209 return False
7210  
7211 parent_type = self.lookup_type_or_none(n.expr)
7212 member_type = self.lookup_type_or_none(n)
7213 if member_type is None or parent_type is None:
7214 return False
7215  
7216 parent_type = get_proper_type(parent_type)
7217 member_type = get_proper_type(coerce_to_literal(member_type))
7218 if not isinstance(parent_type, FunctionLike) or not isinstance(member_type, LiteralType):
7219 return False
7220  
7221 if not parent_type.is_type_obj():
7222 return False
7223  
7224 return (
7225 member_type.is_enum_literal()
7226 and member_type.fallback.type == parent_type.type_object()
7227 )
7228  
7229 def add_any_attribute_to_type(self, typ: Type, name: str) -> Type:
7230 """Inject an extra attribute with Any type using fallbacks."""
7231 orig_typ = typ
7232 typ = get_proper_type(typ)
7233 any_type = AnyType(TypeOfAny.unannotated)
7234 if isinstance(typ, Instance):
7235 result = typ.copy_with_extra_attr(name, any_type)
7236 # For instances, we erase the possible module name, so that restrictions
7237 # become anonymous types.ModuleType instances, allowing hasattr() to
7238 # have effect on modules.
7239 assert result.extra_attrs is not None
7240 result.extra_attrs.mod_name = None
7241 return result
7242 if isinstance(typ, TupleType):
7243 fallback = typ.partial_fallback.copy_with_extra_attr(name, any_type)
7244 return typ.copy_modified(fallback=fallback)
7245 if isinstance(typ, CallableType):
7246 fallback = typ.fallback.copy_with_extra_attr(name, any_type)
7247 return typ.copy_modified(fallback=fallback)
7248 if isinstance(typ, TypeType) and isinstance(typ.item, Instance):
7249 return TypeType.make_normalized(self.add_any_attribute_to_type(typ.item, name))
7250 if isinstance(typ, TypeVarType):
7251 return typ.copy_modified(
7252 upper_bound=self.add_any_attribute_to_type(typ.upper_bound, name),
7253 values=[self.add_any_attribute_to_type(v, name) for v in typ.values],
7254 )
7255 if isinstance(typ, UnionType):
7256 with_attr, without_attr = self.partition_union_by_attr(typ, name)
7257 return make_simplified_union(
7258 with_attr + [self.add_any_attribute_to_type(typ, name) for typ in without_attr]
7259 )
7260 return orig_typ
7261  
7262 def hasattr_type_maps(
7263 self, expr: Expression, source_type: Type, name: str
7264 ) -> tuple[TypeMap, TypeMap]:
7265 """Simple support for hasattr() checks.
7266  
7267 Essentially the logic is following:
7268 * In the if branch, keep types that already has a valid attribute as is,
7269 for other inject an attribute with `Any` type.
7270 * In the else branch, remove types that already have a valid attribute,
7271 while keeping the rest.
7272 """
7273 if self.has_valid_attribute(source_type, name):
7274 return {expr: source_type}, {}
7275  
7276 source_type = get_proper_type(source_type)
7277 if isinstance(source_type, UnionType):
7278 _, without_attr = self.partition_union_by_attr(source_type, name)
7279 yes_map = {expr: self.add_any_attribute_to_type(source_type, name)}
7280 return yes_map, {expr: make_simplified_union(without_attr)}
7281  
7282 type_with_attr = self.add_any_attribute_to_type(source_type, name)
7283 if type_with_attr != source_type:
7284 return {expr: type_with_attr}, {}
7285 return {}, {}
7286  
7287 def partition_union_by_attr(
7288 self, source_type: UnionType, name: str
7289 ) -> tuple[list[Type], list[Type]]:
7290 with_attr = []
7291 without_attr = []
7292 for item in source_type.items:
7293 if self.has_valid_attribute(item, name):
7294 with_attr.append(item)
7295 else:
7296 without_attr.append(item)
7297 return with_attr, without_attr
7298  
7299 def has_valid_attribute(self, typ: Type, name: str) -> bool:
7300 p_typ = get_proper_type(typ)
7301 if isinstance(p_typ, AnyType):
7302 return False
7303 if isinstance(p_typ, Instance) and p_typ.extra_attrs and p_typ.extra_attrs.mod_name:
7304 # Presence of module_symbol_table means this check will skip ModuleType.__getattr__
7305 module_symbol_table = p_typ.type.names
7306 else:
7307 module_symbol_table = None
7308 with self.msg.filter_errors() as watcher:
7309 analyze_member_access(
7310 name,
7311 typ,
7312 TempNode(AnyType(TypeOfAny.special_form)),
7313 False,
7314 False,
7315 False,
7316 self.msg,
7317 original_type=typ,
7318 chk=self,
7319 # This is not a real attribute lookup so don't mess with deferring nodes.
7320 no_deferral=True,
7321 module_symbol_table=module_symbol_table,
7322 )
7323 return not watcher.has_new_errors()
7324  
7325 def get_expression_type(self, node: Expression, type_context: Type | None = None) -> Type:
7326 return self.expr_checker.accept(node, type_context=type_context)

7339 @overload
7340 def conditional_types(
7341 current_type: Type, proposed_type_ranges: list[TypeRange] | None, default: None = None
7342 ) -> tuple[Type | None, Type | None]:
7343 ...
7344  
7345  
7346 @overload
7347 def conditional_types(
7348 current_type: Type, proposed_type_ranges: list[TypeRange] | None, default: Type
7349 ) -> tuple[Type, Type]:
7350 ...
7351  
7352  
7353 def conditional_types(
7354 current_type: Type, proposed_type_ranges: list[TypeRange] | None, default: Type | None = None
7355 ) -> tuple[Type | None, Type | None]:
7356 """Takes in the current type and a proposed type of an expression.
7357  
7358 Returns a 2-tuple: The first element is the proposed type, if the expression
7359 can be the proposed type. The second element is the type it would hold
7360 if it was not the proposed type, if any. UninhabitedType means unreachable.
7361 None means no new information can be inferred. If default is set it is returned
7362 instead."""
7363 if proposed_type_ranges:
7364 if len(proposed_type_ranges) == 1:
7365 target = proposed_type_ranges[0].item
7366 target = get_proper_type(target)
7367 if isinstance(target, LiteralType) and (
7368 target.is_enum_literal() or isinstance(target.value, bool)
7369 ):
7370 enum_name = target.fallback.type.fullname
7371 current_type = try_expanding_sum_type_to_union(current_type, enum_name)
7372 proposed_items = [type_range.item for type_range in proposed_type_ranges]
7373 proposed_type = make_simplified_union(proposed_items)
7374 if isinstance(proposed_type, AnyType):
7375 # We don't really know much about the proposed type, so we shouldn't
7376 # attempt to narrow anything. Instead, we broaden the expr to Any to
7377 # avoid false positives
7378 return proposed_type, default
7379 elif not any(
7380 type_range.is_upper_bound for type_range in proposed_type_ranges
7381 ) and is_proper_subtype(current_type, proposed_type, ignore_promotions=True):
7382 # Expression is always of one of the types in proposed_type_ranges
7383 return default, UninhabitedType()
7384 elif not is_overlapping_types(
7385 current_type, proposed_type, prohibit_none_typevar_overlap=True, ignore_promotions=True
7386 ):
7387 # Expression is never of any type in proposed_type_ranges
7388 return UninhabitedType(), default
7389 else:
7390 # we can only restrict when the type is precise, not bounded
7391 proposed_precise_type = UnionType.make_union(
7392 [
7393 type_range.item
7394 for type_range in proposed_type_ranges
7395 if not type_range.is_upper_bound
7396 ]
7397 )
7398 remaining_type = restrict_subtype_away(current_type, proposed_precise_type)
7399 return proposed_type, remaining_type
7400 else:
7401 # An isinstance check, but we don't understand the type
7402 return current_type, default
7403  
7404  
7405 def conditional_types_to_typemaps(
7406 expr: Expression, yes_type: Type | None, no_type: Type | None
7407 ) -> tuple[TypeMap, TypeMap]:
7408 expr = collapse_walrus(expr)
7409 maps: list[TypeMap] = []
7410 for typ in (yes_type, no_type):
7411 proper_type = get_proper_type(typ)
7412 if isinstance(proper_type, UninhabitedType):
7413 maps.append(None)
7414 elif proper_type is None:
7415 maps.append({})
7416 else:
7417 assert typ is not None
7418 maps.append({expr: typ})
7419  
7420 return cast(Tuple[TypeMap, TypeMap], tuple(maps))
7421  
7422  
7423 def gen_unique_name(base: str, table: SymbolTable) -> str:
7424 """Generate a name that does not appear in table by appending numbers to base."""
7425 if base not in table:
7426 return base
7427 i = 1
7428 while base + str(i) in table:
7429 i += 1
7430 return base + str(i)

7451  
7452 def _is_empty_generator_function(func: FuncItem) -> bool:
7453 """
7454 Checks whether a function's body is 'return; yield' (the yield being added only
7455 to promote the function into a generator function).
7456 """
7457 body = func.body.body
7458 return (
7459 len(body) == 2
7460 and isinstance(ret_stmt := body[0], ReturnStmt)
7461 and (ret_stmt.expr is None or is_literal_none(ret_stmt.expr))
7462 and isinstance(expr_stmt := body[1], ExpressionStmt)
7463 and isinstance(yield_expr := expr_stmt.expr, YieldExpr)
7464 and (yield_expr.expr is None or is_literal_none(yield_expr.expr))
7465 )
7466  
7467  
7468 def builtin_item_type(tp: Type) -> Type | None:
7469 """Get the item type of a builtin container.
7470  
7471 If 'tp' is not one of the built containers (these includes NamedTuple and TypedDict)
7472 or if the container is not parameterized (like List or List[Any])
7473 return None. This function is used to narrow optional types in situations like this:
7474  
7475 x: Optional[int]
7476 if x in (1, 2, 3):
7477 x + 42 # OK
7478  
7479 Note: this is only OK for built-in containers, where we know the behavior
7480 of __contains__.
7481 """
7482 tp = get_proper_type(tp)
7483  
7484 if isinstance(tp, Instance):
7485 if tp.type.fullname in [
7486 "builtins.list",
7487 "builtins.tuple",
7488 "builtins.dict",
7489 "builtins.set",
7490 "builtins.frozenset",
7491 "_collections_abc.dict_keys",
7492 "typing.KeysView",
7493 ]:
7494 if not tp.args:
7495 # TODO: fix tuple in lib-stub/builtins.pyi (it should be generic).
7496 return None
7497 if not isinstance(get_proper_type(tp.args[0]), AnyType):
7498 return tp.args[0]
7499 elif isinstance(tp, TupleType):
7500 normalized_items = []
7501 for it in tp.items:
7502 # This use case is probably rare, but not handling unpacks here can cause crashes.
7503 if isinstance(it, UnpackType):
7504 unpacked = get_proper_type(it.type)
7505 if isinstance(unpacked, TypeVarTupleType):
7506 unpacked = get_proper_type(unpacked.upper_bound)
7507 assert (
7508 isinstance(unpacked, Instance) and unpacked.type.fullname == "builtins.tuple"
7509 )
7510 normalized_items.append(unpacked.args[0])
7511 else:
7512 normalized_items.append(it)
7513 if all(not isinstance(it, AnyType) for it in get_proper_types(normalized_items)):
7514 return make_simplified_union(normalized_items) # this type is not externally visible
7515 elif isinstance(tp, TypedDictType):
7516 # TypedDict always has non-optional string keys. Find the key type from the Mapping
7517 # base class.
7518 for base in tp.fallback.type.mro:
7519 if base.fullname == "typing.Mapping":
7520 return map_instance_to_supertype(tp.fallback, base).args[0]
7521 assert False, "No Mapping base class found for TypedDict fallback"
7522 return None
7523  
7524  
7525 def and_conditional_maps(m1: TypeMap, m2: TypeMap, use_meet: bool = False) -> TypeMap:
7526 """Calculate what information we can learn from the truth of (e1 and e2)
7527 in terms of the information that we can learn from the truth of e1 and
7528 the truth of e2.
7529 """
7530  
7531 if m1 is None or m2 is None:
7532 # One of the conditions can never be true.
7533 return None
7534 # Both conditions can be true; combine the information. Anything
7535 # we learn from either conditions' truth is valid. If the same
7536 # expression's type is refined by both conditions, we somewhat
7537 # arbitrarily give precedence to m2 unless m1 value is Any.
7538 # In the future, we could use an intersection type or meet_types().
7539 result = m2.copy()
7540 m2_keys = {literal_hash(n2) for n2 in m2}
7541 for n1 in m1:
7542 if literal_hash(n1) not in m2_keys or isinstance(get_proper_type(m1[n1]), AnyType):
7543 result[n1] = m1[n1]
7544 if use_meet:
7545 # For now, meet common keys only if specifically requested.
7546 # This is currently used for tuple types narrowing, where having
7547 # a precise result is important.
7548 for n1 in m1:
7549 for n2 in m2:
7550 if literal_hash(n1) == literal_hash(n2):
7551 result[n1] = meet_types(m1[n1], m2[n2])
7552 return result
7553  
7554  
7555 def or_conditional_maps(m1: TypeMap, m2: TypeMap, coalesce_any: bool = False) -> TypeMap:
7556 """Calculate what information we can learn from the truth of (e1 or e2)
7557 in terms of the information that we can learn from the truth of e1 and
7558 the truth of e2. If coalesce_any is True, consider Any a supertype when
7559 joining restrictions.
7560 """
7561  
7562 if m1 is None:
7563 return m2
7564 if m2 is None:
7565 return m1
7566 # Both conditions can be true. Combine information about
7567 # expressions whose type is refined by both conditions. (We do not
7568 # learn anything about expressions whose type is refined by only
7569 # one condition.)
7570 result: dict[Expression, Type] = {}
7571 for n1 in m1:
7572 for n2 in m2:
7573 if literal_hash(n1) == literal_hash(n2):
7574 if coalesce_any and isinstance(get_proper_type(m1[n1]), AnyType):
7575 result[n1] = m1[n1]
7576 else:
7577 result[n1] = make_simplified_union([m1[n1], m2[n2]])
7578 return result
7579  
7580  
7581 def reduce_conditional_maps(
7582 type_maps: list[tuple[TypeMap, TypeMap]], use_meet: bool = False
7583 ) -> tuple[TypeMap, TypeMap]:
7584 """Reduces a list containing pairs of if/else TypeMaps into a single pair.
7585  
7586 We "and" together all of the if TypeMaps and "or" together the else TypeMaps. So
7587 for example, if we had the input:
7588  
7589 [
7590 ({x: TypeIfX, shared: TypeIfShared1}, {x: TypeElseX, shared: TypeElseShared1}),
7591 ({y: TypeIfY, shared: TypeIfShared2}, {y: TypeElseY, shared: TypeElseShared2}),
7592 ]
7593  
7594 ...we'd return the output:
7595  
7596 (
7597 {x: TypeIfX, y: TypeIfY, shared: PseudoIntersection[TypeIfShared1, TypeIfShared2]},
7598 {shared: Union[TypeElseShared1, TypeElseShared2]},
7599 )
7600  
7601 ...where "PseudoIntersection[X, Y] == Y" because mypy actually doesn't understand intersections
7602 yet, so we settle for just arbitrarily picking the right expr's type.
7603  
7604 We only retain the shared expression in the 'else' case because we don't actually know
7605 whether x was refined or y was refined -- only just that one of the two was refined.
7606 """
7607 if len(type_maps) == 0:
7608 return {}, {}
7609 elif len(type_maps) == 1:
7610 return type_maps[0]
7611 else:
7612 final_if_map, final_else_map = type_maps[0]
7613 for if_map, else_map in type_maps[1:]:
7614 final_if_map = and_conditional_maps(final_if_map, if_map, use_meet=use_meet)
7615 final_else_map = or_conditional_maps(final_else_map, else_map)
7616  
7617 return final_if_map, final_else_map
7618  
7619  
7620 def convert_to_typetype(type_map: TypeMap) -> TypeMap:
7621 converted_type_map: dict[Expression, Type] = {}
7622 if type_map is None:
7623 return None
7624 for expr, typ in type_map.items():
7625 t = typ
7626 if isinstance(t, TypeVarType):
7627 t = t.upper_bound
7628 # TODO: should we only allow unions of instances as per PEP 484?
7629 if not isinstance(get_proper_type(t), (UnionType, Instance)):
7630 # unknown type; error was likely reported earlier
7631 return {}
7632 converted_type_map[expr] = TypeType.make_normalized(typ)
7633 return converted_type_map
7634  
7635  
7636 def flatten(t: Expression) -> list[Expression]:
7637 """Flatten a nested sequence of tuples/lists into one list of nodes."""
7638 if isinstance(t, (TupleExpr, ListExpr)):
7639 return [b for a in t.items for b in flatten(a)]
7640 elif isinstance(t, StarExpr):
7641 return flatten(t.expr)
7642 else:
7643 return [t]
7644  
7645  
7646 def flatten_types(t: Type) -> list[Type]:
7647 """Flatten a nested sequence of tuples into one list of nodes."""
7648 t = get_proper_type(t)
7649 if isinstance(t, TupleType):
7650 return [b for a in t.items for b in flatten_types(a)]
7651 elif is_named_instance(t, "builtins.tuple"):
7652 return [t.args[0]]
7653 else:
7654 return [t]

7657 def expand_func(defn: FuncItem, map: dict[TypeVarId, Type]) -> FuncItem:
7658 visitor = TypeTransformVisitor(map)
7659 ret = visitor.node(defn)
7660 assert isinstance(ret, FuncItem)
7661 return ret
7662

7664 class TypeTransformVisitor(TransformVisitor):
7665 def __init__(self, map: dict[TypeVarId, Type]) -> None:
7666 super().__init__()
7667 self.map = map
7668  
7669 def type(self, type: Type) -> Type:
7670 return expand_type(type, self.map)

7672  
7673 def are_argument_counts_overlapping(t: CallableType, s: CallableType) -> bool:
7674 """Can a single call match both t and s, based just on positional argument counts?"""
7675 min_args = max(t.min_args, s.min_args)
7676 max_args = min(t.max_possible_positional_args(), s.max_possible_positional_args())
7677 return min_args <= max_args
7678  
7679  
7680 def is_unsafe_overlapping_overload_signatures(
7681 signature: CallableType, other: CallableType, class_type_vars: list[TypeVarLikeType]
7682 ) -> bool:
7683 """Check if two overloaded signatures are unsafely overlapping or partially overlapping.
7684  
7685 We consider two functions 's' and 't' to be unsafely overlapping if both
7686 of the following are true:
7687  
7688 1. s's parameters are all more precise or partially overlapping with t's
7689 2. s's return type is NOT a subtype of t's.
7690  
7691 Assumes that 'signature' appears earlier in the list of overload
7692 alternatives then 'other' and that their argument counts are overlapping.
7693 """
7694 # Try detaching callables from the containing class so that all TypeVars
7695 # are treated as being free.
7696 #
7697 # This lets us identify cases where the two signatures use completely
7698 # incompatible types -- e.g. see the testOverloadingInferUnionReturnWithMixedTypevars
7699 # test case.
7700 signature = detach_callable(signature, class_type_vars)
7701 other = detach_callable(other, class_type_vars)
7702  
7703 # Note: We repeat this check twice in both directions due to a slight
7704 # asymmetry in 'is_callable_compatible'. When checking for partial overlaps,
7705 # we attempt to unify 'signature' and 'other' both against each other.
7706 #
7707 # If 'signature' cannot be unified with 'other', we end early. However,
7708 # if 'other' cannot be modified with 'signature', the function continues
7709 # using the older version of 'other'.
7710 #
7711 # This discrepancy is unfortunately difficult to get rid of, so we repeat the
7712 # checks twice in both directions for now.
7713 #
7714 # Note that we ignore possible overlap between type variables and None. This
7715 # is technically unsafe, but unsafety is tiny and this prevents some common
7716 # use cases like:
7717 # @overload
7718 # def foo(x: None) -> None: ..
7719 # @overload
7720 # def foo(x: T) -> Foo[T]: ...
7721 return is_callable_compatible(
7722 signature,
7723 other,
7724 is_compat=is_overlapping_types_no_promote_no_uninhabited_no_none,
7725 is_proper_subtype=False,
  • E741 Ambiguous variable name 'l'
7726 is_compat_return=lambda l, r: not is_subtype_no_promote(l, r),
7727 ignore_return=False,
7728 check_args_covariantly=True,
7729 allow_partial_overlap=True,
7730 no_unify_none=True,
7731 ) or is_callable_compatible(
7732 other,
7733 signature,
7734 is_compat=is_overlapping_types_no_promote_no_uninhabited_no_none,
7735 is_proper_subtype=False,
  • E741 Ambiguous variable name 'l'
7736 is_compat_return=lambda l, r: not is_subtype_no_promote(r, l),
7737 ignore_return=False,
7738 check_args_covariantly=False,
7739 allow_partial_overlap=True,
7740 no_unify_none=True,
7741 )
7742  
7743  
7744 def detach_callable(typ: CallableType, class_type_vars: list[TypeVarLikeType]) -> CallableType:
7745 """Ensures that the callable's type variables are 'detached' and independent of the context.
7746  
7747 A callable normally keeps track of the type variables it uses within its 'variables' field.
7748 However, if the callable is from a method and that method is using a class type variable,
7749 the callable will not keep track of that type variable since it belongs to the class.
7750  
7751 This function will traverse the callable and find all used type vars and add them to the
7752 variables field if it isn't already present.
7753  
7754 The caller can then unify on all type variables whether the callable is originally from
7755 the class or not."""
7756 if not class_type_vars:
7757 # Fast path, nothing to update.
7758 return typ
7759 seen_type_vars = set()
7760 for t in typ.arg_types + [typ.ret_type]:
7761 seen_type_vars |= set(get_type_vars(t))
7762 return typ.copy_modified(
7763 variables=list(typ.variables) + [tv for tv in class_type_vars if tv in seen_type_vars]
7764 )
7765  
7766  
7767 def overload_can_never_match(signature: CallableType, other: CallableType) -> bool:
7768 """Check if the 'other' method can never be matched due to 'signature'.
7769  
7770 This can happen if signature's parameters are all strictly broader then
7771 other's parameters.
7772  
7773 Assumes that both signatures have overlapping argument counts.
7774 """
7775 # The extra erasure is needed to prevent spurious errors
7776 # in situations where an `Any` overload is used as a fallback
7777 # for an overload with type variables. The spurious error appears
7778 # because the type variables turn into `Any` during unification in
7779 # the below subtype check and (surprisingly?) `is_proper_subtype(Any, Any)`
7780 # returns `True`.
7781 # TODO: find a cleaner solution instead of this ad-hoc erasure.
7782 exp_signature = expand_type(
7783 signature, {tvar.id: erase_def_to_union_or_bound(tvar) for tvar in signature.variables}
7784 )
7785 return is_callable_compatible(
7786 exp_signature, other, is_compat=is_more_precise, is_proper_subtype=True, ignore_return=True
7787 )
7788  
7789  
7790 def is_more_general_arg_prefix(t: FunctionLike, s: FunctionLike) -> bool:
7791 """Does t have wider arguments than s?"""
7792 # TODO should an overload with additional items be allowed to be more
7793 # general than one with fewer items (or just one item)?
7794 if isinstance(t, CallableType):
7795 if isinstance(s, CallableType):
7796 return is_callable_compatible(
7797 t, s, is_compat=is_proper_subtype, is_proper_subtype=True, ignore_return=True
7798 )
7799 elif isinstance(t, FunctionLike):
7800 if isinstance(s, FunctionLike):
7801 if len(t.items) == len(s.items):
7802 return all(
7803 is_same_arg_prefix(items, itemt) for items, itemt in zip(t.items, s.items)
7804 )
7805 return False
7806  
7807  
7808 def is_same_arg_prefix(t: CallableType, s: CallableType) -> bool:
7809 return is_callable_compatible(
7810 t,
7811 s,
7812 is_compat=is_same_type,
7813 is_proper_subtype=True,
7814 ignore_return=True,
7815 check_args_covariantly=True,
7816 ignore_pos_arg_names=True,
7817 )
7818  
7819  
7820 def infer_operator_assignment_method(typ: Type, operator: str) -> tuple[bool, str]:
7821 """Determine if operator assignment on given value type is in-place, and the method name.
7822  
7823 For example, if operator is '+', return (True, '__iadd__') or (False, '__add__')
7824 depending on which method is supported by the type.
7825 """
7826 typ = get_proper_type(typ)
7827 method = operators.op_methods[operator]
7828 existing_method = None
7829 if isinstance(typ, Instance):
7830 existing_method = _find_inplace_method(typ, method, operator)
7831 elif isinstance(typ, TypedDictType):
7832 existing_method = _find_inplace_method(typ.fallback, method, operator)
7833  
7834 if existing_method is not None:
7835 return True, existing_method
7836 return False, method
7837  
7838  
7839 def _find_inplace_method(inst: Instance, method: str, operator: str) -> str | None:
7840 if operator in operators.ops_with_inplace_method:
7841 inplace_method = "__i" + method[2:]
7842 if inst.type.has_readable_member(inplace_method):
7843 return inplace_method
7844 return None
7845  
7846  
7847 def is_valid_inferred_type(typ: Type, is_lvalue_final: bool = False) -> bool:
7848 """Is an inferred type valid and needs no further refinement?
7849  
7850 Examples of invalid types include the None type (when we are not assigning
7851 None to a final lvalue) or List[<uninhabited>].
7852  
7853 When not doing strict Optional checking, all types containing None are
7854 invalid. When doing strict Optional checking, only None and types that are
7855 incompletely defined (i.e. contain UninhabitedType) are invalid.
7856 """
7857 proper_type = get_proper_type(typ)
7858 if isinstance(proper_type, NoneType):
7859 # If the lvalue is final, we may immediately infer NoneType when the
7860 # initializer is None.
7861 #
7862 # If not, we want to defer making this decision. The final inferred
7863 # type could either be NoneType or an Optional type, depending on
7864 # the context. This resolution happens in leave_partial_types when
7865 # we pop a partial types scope.
7866 return is_lvalue_final
7867 elif isinstance(proper_type, UninhabitedType):
7868 return False
7869 return not typ.accept(InvalidInferredTypes())
7870  
7871  
7872 class InvalidInferredTypes(BoolTypeQuery):
7873 """Find type components that are not valid for an inferred type.
7874  
7875 These include <Erased> type, and any uninhabited types resulting from failed
7876 (ambiguous) type inference.
7877 """
7878  
7879 def __init__(self) -> None:
7880 super().__init__(ANY_STRATEGY)
7881  
7882 def visit_uninhabited_type(self, t: UninhabitedType) -> bool:
7883 return t.ambiguous
7884  
7885 def visit_erased_type(self, t: ErasedType) -> bool:
7886 # This can happen inside a lambda.
7887 return True
7888  
7889 def visit_type_var(self, t: TypeVarType) -> bool:
7890 # This is needed to prevent leaking into partial types during
7891 # multi-step type inference.
7892 return t.id.is_meta_var()
7893  
7894  
7895 class SetNothingToAny(TypeTranslator):
7896 """Replace all ambiguous Uninhabited types with Any (to avoid spurious extra errors)."""
7897  
7898 def visit_uninhabited_type(self, t: UninhabitedType) -> Type:
7899 if t.ambiguous:
7900 return AnyType(TypeOfAny.from_error)
7901 return t
7902  
7903 def visit_type_alias_type(self, t: TypeAliasType) -> Type:
7904 # Target of the alias cannot be an ambiguous UninhabitedType, so we just
7905 # replace the arguments.
7906 return t.copy_modified(args=[a.accept(self) for a in t.args])
7907  
7908  
7909 def is_node_static(node: Node | None) -> bool | None:
7910 """Find out if a node describes a static function method."""
7911  
7912 if isinstance(node, FuncDef):
7913 return node.is_static
7914  
7915 if isinstance(node, Var):
7916 return node.is_staticmethod
7917  
7918 return None

7920  
7921 class CheckerScope:
7922 # We keep two stacks combined, to maintain the relative order
7923 stack: list[TypeInfo | FuncItem | MypyFile]
7924  
7925 def __init__(self, module: MypyFile) -> None:
7926 self.stack = [module]
7927  
7928 def top_function(self) -> FuncItem | None:
7929 for e in reversed(self.stack):
7930 if isinstance(e, FuncItem):
7931 return e
7932 return None
7933  
7934 def top_non_lambda_function(self) -> FuncItem | None:
7935 for e in reversed(self.stack):
7936 if isinstance(e, FuncItem) and not isinstance(e, LambdaExpr):
7937 return e
7938 return None
7939  
7940 def active_class(self) -> TypeInfo | None:
7941 if isinstance(self.stack[-1], TypeInfo):
7942 return self.stack[-1]
7943 return None
7944  
7945 def enclosing_class(self) -> TypeInfo | None:
7946 """Is there a class *directly* enclosing this function?"""
7947 top = self.top_function()
7948 assert top, "This method must be called from inside a function"
7949 index = self.stack.index(top)
7950 assert index, "CheckerScope stack must always start with a module"
7951 enclosing = self.stack[index - 1]
7952 if isinstance(enclosing, TypeInfo):
7953 return enclosing
7954 return None
7955  
7956 def active_self_type(self) -> Instance | TupleType | None:
7957 """An instance or tuple type representing the current class.
7958  
7959 This returns None unless we are in class body or in a method.
7960 In particular, inside a function nested in method this returns None.
7961 """
7962 info = self.active_class()
7963 if not info and self.top_function():
7964 info = self.enclosing_class()
7965 if info:
7966 return fill_typevars(info)
7967 return None
7968  
7969 @contextmanager
7970 def push_function(self, item: FuncItem) -> Iterator[None]:
7971 self.stack.append(item)
7972 yield
7973 self.stack.pop()
7974  
7975 @contextmanager
7976 def push_class(self, info: TypeInfo) -> Iterator[None]:
7977 self.stack.append(info)
7978 yield
7979 self.stack.pop()
7980  
7981  
7982 TKey = TypeVar("TKey")
7983 TValue = TypeVar("TValue")
7984  
7985  
7986 class DisjointDict(Generic[TKey, TValue]):
7987 """An variation of the union-find algorithm/data structure where instead of keeping
7988 track of just disjoint sets, we keep track of disjoint dicts -- keep track of multiple
7989 Set[Key] -> Set[Value] mappings, where each mapping's keys are guaranteed to be disjoint.
7990  
7991 This data structure is currently used exclusively by 'group_comparison_operands' below
7992 to merge chains of '==' and 'is' comparisons when two or more chains use the same expression
7993 in best-case O(n), where n is the number of operands.
7994  
7995 Specifically, the `add_mapping()` function and `items()` functions will take on average
7996 O(k + v) and O(n) respectively, where k and v are the number of keys and values we're adding
7997 for a given chain. Note that k <= n and v <= n.
7998  
7999 We hit these average/best-case scenarios for most user code: e.g. when the user has just
8000 a single chain like 'a == b == c == d == ...' or multiple disjoint chains like
8001 'a==b < c==d < e==f < ...'. (Note that a naive iterative merging would be O(n^2) for
8002 the latter case).
8003  
8004 In comparison, this data structure will make 'group_comparison_operands' have a worst-case
8005 runtime of O(n*log(n)): 'add_mapping()' and 'items()' are worst-case O(k*log(n) + v) and
8006 O(k*log(n)) respectively. This happens only in the rare case where the user keeps repeatedly
8007 making disjoint mappings before merging them in a way that persistently dodges the path
8008 compression optimization in '_lookup_root_id', which would end up constructing a single
8009 tree of height log_2(n). This makes root lookups no longer amoritized constant time when we
8010 finally call 'items()'.
8011 """
8012  
8013 def __init__(self) -> None:
8014 # Each key maps to a unique ID
8015 self._key_to_id: dict[TKey, int] = {}
8016  
8017 # Each id points to the parent id, forming a forest of upwards-pointing trees. If the
8018 # current id already is the root, it points to itself. We gradually flatten these trees
8019 # as we perform root lookups: eventually all nodes point directly to its root.
8020 self._id_to_parent_id: dict[int, int] = {}
8021  
8022 # Each root id in turn maps to the set of values.
8023 self._root_id_to_values: dict[int, set[TValue]] = {}
8024  
8025 def add_mapping(self, keys: set[TKey], values: set[TValue]) -> None:
8026 """Adds a 'Set[TKey] -> Set[TValue]' mapping. If there already exists a mapping
8027 containing one or more of the given keys, we merge the input mapping with the old one.
8028  
8029 Note that the given set of keys must be non-empty -- otherwise, nothing happens.
8030 """
8031 if not keys:
8032 return
8033  
8034 subtree_roots = [self._lookup_or_make_root_id(key) for key in keys]
8035 new_root = subtree_roots[0]
8036  
8037 root_values = self._root_id_to_values[new_root]
8038 root_values.update(values)
8039 for subtree_root in subtree_roots[1:]:
8040 if subtree_root == new_root or subtree_root not in self._root_id_to_values:
8041 continue
8042 self._id_to_parent_id[subtree_root] = new_root
8043 root_values.update(self._root_id_to_values.pop(subtree_root))
8044  
8045 def items(self) -> list[tuple[set[TKey], set[TValue]]]:
8046 """Returns all disjoint mappings in key-value pairs."""
8047 root_id_to_keys: dict[int, set[TKey]] = {}
8048 for key in self._key_to_id:
8049 root_id = self._lookup_root_id(key)
8050 if root_id not in root_id_to_keys:
8051 root_id_to_keys[root_id] = set()
8052 root_id_to_keys[root_id].add(key)
8053  
8054 output = []
8055 for root_id, keys in root_id_to_keys.items():
8056 output.append((keys, self._root_id_to_values[root_id]))
8057  
8058 return output
8059  
8060 def _lookup_or_make_root_id(self, key: TKey) -> int:
8061 if key in self._key_to_id:
8062 return self._lookup_root_id(key)
8063 else:
8064 new_id = len(self._key_to_id)
8065 self._key_to_id[key] = new_id
8066 self._id_to_parent_id[new_id] = new_id
8067 self._root_id_to_values[new_id] = set()
8068 return new_id
8069  
8070 def _lookup_root_id(self, key: TKey) -> int:
8071 i = self._key_to_id[key]
8072 while i != self._id_to_parent_id[i]:
8073 # Optimization: make keys directly point to their grandparents to speed up
8074 # future traversals. This prevents degenerate trees of height n from forming.
8075 new_parent = self._id_to_parent_id[self._id_to_parent_id[i]]
8076 self._id_to_parent_id[i] = new_parent
8077 i = new_parent
8078 return i
8079  
8080  
8081 def group_comparison_operands(
8082 pairwise_comparisons: Iterable[tuple[str, Expression, Expression]],
8083 operand_to_literal_hash: Mapping[int, Key],
8084 operators_to_group: set[str],
8085 ) -> list[tuple[str, list[int]]]:
8086 """Group a series of comparison operands together chained by any operand
8087 in the 'operators_to_group' set. All other pairwise operands are kept in
8088 groups of size 2.
8089  
8090 For example, suppose we have the input comparison expression:
8091  
8092 x0 == x1 == x2 < x3 < x4 is x5 is x6 is not x7 is not x8
8093  
8094 If we get these expressions in a pairwise way (e.g. by calling ComparisionExpr's
8095 'pairwise()' method), we get the following as input:
8096  
8097 [('==', x0, x1), ('==', x1, x2), ('<', x2, x3), ('<', x3, x4),
8098 ('is', x4, x5), ('is', x5, x6), ('is not', x6, x7), ('is not', x7, x8)]
8099  
8100 If `operators_to_group` is the set {'==', 'is'}, this function will produce
8101 the following "simplified operator list":
8102  
8103 [("==", [0, 1, 2]), ("<", [2, 3]), ("<", [3, 4]),
8104 ("is", [4, 5, 6]), ("is not", [6, 7]), ("is not", [7, 8])]
8105  
8106 Note that (a) we yield *indices* to the operands rather then the operand
8107 expressions themselves and that (b) operands used in a consecutive chain
8108 of '==' or 'is' are grouped together.
8109  
8110 If two of these chains happen to contain operands with the same underlying
8111 literal hash (e.g. are assignable and correspond to the same expression),
8112 we combine those chains together. For example, if we had:
8113  
8114 same == x < y == same
8115  
8116 ...and if 'operand_to_literal_hash' contained the same values for the indices
8117 0 and 3, we'd produce the following output:
8118  
8119 [("==", [0, 1, 2, 3]), ("<", [1, 2])]
8120  
8121 But if the 'operand_to_literal_hash' did *not* contain an entry, we'd instead
8122 default to returning:
8123  
8124 [("==", [0, 1]), ("<", [1, 2]), ("==", [2, 3])]
8125  
8126 This function is currently only used to assist with type-narrowing refinements
8127 and is extracted out to a helper function so we can unit test it.
8128 """
8129 groups: dict[str, DisjointDict[Key, int]] = {op: DisjointDict() for op in operators_to_group}
8130  
8131 simplified_operator_list: list[tuple[str, list[int]]] = []
8132 last_operator: str | None = None
8133 current_indices: set[int] = set()
8134 current_hashes: set[Key] = set()
8135 for i, (operator, left_expr, right_expr) in enumerate(pairwise_comparisons):
8136 if last_operator is None:
8137 last_operator = operator
8138  
8139 if current_indices and (operator != last_operator or operator not in operators_to_group):
8140 # If some of the operands in the chain are assignable, defer adding it: we might
8141 # end up needing to merge it with other chains that appear later.
8142 if not current_hashes:
8143 simplified_operator_list.append((last_operator, sorted(current_indices)))
8144 else:
8145 groups[last_operator].add_mapping(current_hashes, current_indices)
8146 last_operator = operator
8147 current_indices = set()
8148 current_hashes = set()
8149  
8150 # Note: 'i' corresponds to the left operand index, so 'i + 1' is the
8151 # right operand.
8152 current_indices.add(i)
8153 current_indices.add(i + 1)
8154  
8155 # We only ever want to combine operands/combine chains for these operators
8156 if operator in operators_to_group:
8157 left_hash = operand_to_literal_hash.get(i)
8158 if left_hash is not None:
8159 current_hashes.add(left_hash)
8160 right_hash = operand_to_literal_hash.get(i + 1)
8161 if right_hash is not None:
8162 current_hashes.add(right_hash)
8163  
8164 if last_operator is not None:
8165 if not current_hashes:
8166 simplified_operator_list.append((last_operator, sorted(current_indices)))
8167 else:
8168 groups[last_operator].add_mapping(current_hashes, current_indices)
8169  
8170 # Now that we know which chains happen to contain the same underlying expressions
8171 # and can be merged together, add in this info back to the output.
8172 for operator, disjoint_dict in groups.items():
8173 for keys, indices in disjoint_dict.items():
8174 simplified_operator_list.append((operator, sorted(indices)))
8175  
8176 # For stability, reorder list by the first operand index to appear
8177 simplified_operator_list.sort(key=lambda item: item[1][0])
8178 return simplified_operator_list
8179  
8180  
8181 def is_typed_callable(c: Type | None) -> bool:
8182 c = get_proper_type(c)
8183 if not c or not isinstance(c, CallableType):
8184 return False
8185 return not all(
8186 isinstance(t, AnyType) and t.type_of_any == TypeOfAny.unannotated
8187 for t in get_proper_types(c.arg_types + [c.ret_type])
8188 )
8189  
8190  
8191 def is_untyped_decorator(typ: Type | None) -> bool:
8192 typ = get_proper_type(typ)
8193 if not typ:
8194 return True
8195 elif isinstance(typ, CallableType):
8196 return not is_typed_callable(typ)
8197 elif isinstance(typ, Instance):
8198 method = typ.type.get_method("__call__")
8199 if method:
8200 if isinstance(method, Decorator):
8201 return is_untyped_decorator(method.func.type) or is_untyped_decorator(
8202 method.var.type
8203 )
8204  
8205 if isinstance(method.type, Overloaded):
8206 return any(is_untyped_decorator(item) for item in method.type.items)
8207 else:
8208 return not is_typed_callable(method.type)
8209 else:
8210 return False
8211 elif isinstance(typ, Overloaded):
8212 return any(is_untyped_decorator(item) for item in typ.items)
8213 return True
8214  
8215  
8216 def is_static(func: FuncBase | Decorator) -> bool:
8217 if isinstance(func, Decorator):
8218 return is_static(func.func)
8219 elif isinstance(func, FuncBase):
8220 return func.is_static
8221 assert False, f"Unexpected func type: {type(func)}"
8222  
8223  
8224 def is_property(defn: SymbolNode) -> bool:
8225 if isinstance(defn, Decorator):
8226 return defn.func.is_property
8227 if isinstance(defn, OverloadedFuncDef):
8228 if defn.items and isinstance(defn.items[0], Decorator):
8229 return defn.items[0].func.is_property
8230 return False
8231  
8232  
8233 def get_property_type(t: ProperType) -> ProperType:
8234 if isinstance(t, CallableType):
8235 return get_proper_type(t.ret_type)
8236 if isinstance(t, Overloaded):
8237 return get_proper_type(t.items[0].ret_type)
8238 return t
8239  
8240  
8241 def is_subtype_no_promote(left: Type, right: Type) -> bool:
8242 return is_subtype(left, right, ignore_promotions=True)
8243  
8244  
8245 def is_overlapping_types_no_promote_no_uninhabited_no_none(left: Type, right: Type) -> bool:
8246 # For the purpose of unsafe overload checks we consider list[Never] and list[int]
8247 # non-overlapping. This is consistent with how we treat list[int] and list[str] as
8248 # non-overlapping, despite [] belongs to both. Also this will prevent false positives
8249 # for failed type inference during unification.
8250 return is_overlapping_types(
8251 left,
8252 right,
8253 ignore_promotions=True,
8254 ignore_uninhabited=True,
8255 prohibit_none_typevar_overlap=True,
8256 )
8257  
8258  
8259 def is_private(node_name: str) -> bool:
8260 """Check if node is private to class definition."""
8261 return node_name.startswith("__") and not node_name.endswith("__")
8262  
8263  
8264 def is_string_literal(typ: Type) -> bool:
8265 strs = try_getting_str_literals_from_type(typ)
8266 return strs is not None and len(strs) == 1
8267  
8268  
8269 def has_bool_item(typ: ProperType) -> bool:
8270 """Return True if type is 'bool' or a union with a 'bool' item."""
8271 if is_named_instance(typ, "builtins.bool"):
8272 return True
8273 if isinstance(typ, UnionType):
8274 return any(is_named_instance(item, "builtins.bool") for item in typ.items)
8275 return False
8276  
8277  
8278 def collapse_walrus(e: Expression) -> Expression:
8279 """If an expression is an AssignmentExpr, pull out the assignment target.
8280  
8281 We don't make any attempt to pull out all the targets in code like `x := (y := z)`.
8282 We could support narrowing those if that sort of code turns out to be common.
8283 """
8284 if isinstance(e, AssignmentExpr):
8285 return e.target
8286 return e
8287  
8288  
8289 def find_last_var_assignment_line(n: Node, v: Var) -> int:
8290 """Find the highest line number of a potential assignment to variable within node.
8291  
8292 This supports local and global variables.
8293  
8294 Return -1 if no assignment was found.
8295 """
8296 visitor = VarAssignVisitor(v)
8297 n.accept(visitor)
8298 return visitor.last_line
8299  
8300  
8301 class VarAssignVisitor(TraverserVisitor):
8302 def __init__(self, v: Var) -> None:
8303 self.last_line = -1
8304 self.lvalue = False
8305 self.var_node = v
8306  
8307 def visit_assignment_stmt(self, s: AssignmentStmt) -> None:
8308 self.lvalue = True
8309 for lv in s.lvalues:
8310 lv.accept(self)
8311 self.lvalue = False
8312  
8313 def visit_name_expr(self, e: NameExpr) -> None:
8314 if self.lvalue and e.node is self.var_node:
8315 self.last_line = max(self.last_line, e.line)
8316  
8317 def visit_member_expr(self, e: MemberExpr) -> None:
8318 old_lvalue = self.lvalue
8319 self.lvalue = False
8320 super().visit_member_expr(e)
8321 self.lvalue = old_lvalue
8322  
8323 def visit_index_expr(self, e: IndexExpr) -> None:
8324 old_lvalue = self.lvalue
8325 self.lvalue = False
8326 super().visit_index_expr(e)
8327 self.lvalue = old_lvalue
8328  
8329 def visit_with_stmt(self, s: WithStmt) -> None:
8330 self.lvalue = True
8331 for lv in s.target:
8332 if lv is not None:
8333 lv.accept(self)
8334 self.lvalue = False
8335 s.body.accept(self)
8336  
8337 def visit_for_stmt(self, s: ForStmt) -> None:
8338 self.lvalue = True
8339 s.index.accept(self)
8340 self.lvalue = False
8341 s.body.accept(self)
8342 if s.else_body:
8343 s.else_body.accept(self)
8344  
8345 def visit_assignment_expr(self, e: AssignmentExpr) -> None:
8346 self.lvalue = True
8347 e.target.accept(self)
8348 self.lvalue = False
8349 e.value.accept(self)
8350  
8351 def visit_as_pattern(self, p: AsPattern) -> None:
8352 if p.pattern is not None:
8353 p.pattern.accept(self)
8354 if p.name is not None:
8355 self.lvalue = True
8356 p.name.accept(self)
8357 self.lvalue = False
8358  
8359 def visit_starred_pattern(self, p: StarredPattern) -> None:
8360 if p.capture is not None:
8361 self.lvalue = True
8362 p.capture.accept(self)
8363 self.lvalue = False
